<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0696,0385</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Staley; No separates moved for the AMs cycle.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Bill Kennedy</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT SMITH, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill Kennedy, a Pulitzer Prize-winning
journalist and former Southwest Times Record editor, died Friday
from complications of a heart attack. He was 64.
   As a reporter for the Watsonville (Calif.) Register-Pajaronian,
Kennedy was named co-winner of the 1955 Pulitzer Prize for public
service for exposing corruption in government. His coverage of that
story brought him one of his two National Broadcasting Co. Big
Story Award awards. The stories were made into television dramas.
   Kennedy was editor of the Southwest Times Record between 1971
and 1975 after heading the national news bureau of the Donrey Media
Group in Washington, D.C. Between 1975 and 1977, he was editor of
the Donrey newspaper in Hilo, Hawaii.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Garaldine Price</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Garaldine ``Garry'' Price, the widow of
longtime Illinois congressman Melvin Price, died Sunday of lung
cancer at the age of 66.
   Mrs. Price and Price, a veteran Democrat lawmaker from East St.
Louis, Ill., married in 1952 while she was a field representative
for the American Cancer Society in Denver.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Tom Siler</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tom Siler, a former Knoxville sports
editor and author of four books, died Sunday after a long illness
at age 78.
   Siler's career began in 1931 and included stints with The
Associated Press in Nashville and the Chicago Sun Times. He was
Knoxville News-Sentinel sports editor from 1957-1979.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Oren Staley</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oren Lee Staley, former president of
the National Farmers Organization for 20 years and an unsuccessful
candidate for U.S. Senate in Missouri in 1986, died Monday. He was
65.
   Staley owned Oren Staley Realty Inc., which has offices in St.
Joseph and Kansas City, Mo. As president of NFO, a Denver-based
organization which represents more than 250,000 farm families,
Staley often lobbied Congress on farm legislation and related
issues.
   In 1986 Staley finished third in the Democratic primary for the
U.S. Senate in Missouri. In November 1986 he filed for Chapter 11
bankruptcy, saying his 956-acre farm was unprofitable and that
personal loans he took out to cover costs of his Senate bid had
worsened his financial problems.
</TEXT>
