<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iraq-Iran     09-20 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iraq-Iran,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqi Foreign Minister Says Shatt Must Remain Iraqi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crucial Shatt al-Arab waterway must
remain under Iraqi control and cannot be used by Iran as a
negotiating tool in peace talks to end their 8-year-old war, Iraq's
foreign minister was quoted as saying Monday.
   Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz said the waterway, the delta of the
Tigris and Euphrates rivers and Iraq's sole outlet to the sea,
should remain under Iraqi control as ``a historical, logical, legal
and a just matter,'' according to the official Iraqi News Agency.
   Aziz, speaking at a press conference, said Iraq rejects what he
said was Iran's use of the waterway as a means to pressure Iraq in
the U.N.-mediated peace talks that started in Geneva on Aug. 25,
the agency reported.
   Iraq is demanding sovereignty over the Shatt-al-Arab estuary and
that the outlet be cleared of sunken ships and silt. Iran's first
wants to negotiate the withdrawal of both side's troops to
internationally recognized borders, the exchange of war prisoners
and a U.N. investigation to determine who started the war.
   The talks broke off Sept. 13 and are scheduled to resume in New
York in the first week of October.
   Aziz said that Iraq is committed to peace and that ``Iran would
bear the consequences for its insistence on its current position.''
   After the press conference, Aziz left Baghdad for Riyadh and
consultations with King Fahd of Saudi Arabia about the negotiations
and other ``issues of common interest,'' the news agency said.
   In a related development, the agency reported that President
Saddam Hussein met with his military field commanders Monday and
one item on the agenda was the possibility of changing the course
of the Shatt al-Arab.
   Press reports in the region have said Iraq is considering the
project to change the path of the waterway in case its talks with
Iran deadlock completely.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
