<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SATScores-Questions     09-20 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAT Scores-Questions,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SAT Sample Questions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   How hard are SAT questions?
   Here are questions from a test administered on May 2, 1987,
reprinted by permission of the Educational Testing Service, which
is the copyright owner of the questions. Included is the percentage
of test-takers correctly answering each.
   
   MATH:
   
   ``If a, b, and c are integers, the expression a(b + c) is always
equal to each of the following EXCEPT
   (A) (a + b)c
   (B) a(c + b)
   (C) (c + b)a
   (D) ab + ac
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Answer is (A); correctly answered by 79 percent of test-takers.
   
   ``If the average (arithmetic mean) of six numbers is -6, and the
sum of four of the numbers is 20, what is the average of the other
two numbers?
   (A) 7
   (B) 8
   (C) -8
   (D) -28
   (E) -32
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Answer is (D); correctly answered by 16 percent of test-takers.
   
   VERBAL:
   
   Directions: Choose the word most nearly the OPPOSITE in meaning
to the words in capital letters.
   
   ``UNCORK''
   (A) reform
   (B) empty
   (C) seal
   (D) dry out
   (E) blend in
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Answer is (C); correctly answered by 95 percent of test-takers.
   
   ``MAGNANIMOUS''
   (A) dainty
   (B) latent
   (C) vengeful
   (D) conspicuous
   (E) compatible
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Answer is (C); correctly answered by 11 percent of test-takers.
</TEXT>
