<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 0312EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Chile-FarmPolitics     09-20 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chile-Farm Politics,0791</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In Chilean Farm Country, Political Question Is Tinged by Fear</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FERNANDO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the country's agricultural
heartland, old ingrained fears tinge the debate over the referendum
next month on Gen. Augusto Pinochet's presidency.
   For prosperous landowners, frightening memories of farm seizures
by leftist peasants in the early 1970s has helped push them solidly
into the pro-Pinochet camp.
   ``This is the fear we have, of returning to the past,'' said
Francisco Olea, owner of a 100-acre spread here in the country's
fertile Central Valley.
   But for struggling farm workers, the prospect of reprisal by
their bosses or local officials is keeping many from openly voicing
dissent. Some say resentment with Pinochet's authoritarian rule,
and with a hand-to-mouth existence, will find expression in the
ballot box.
   ``At least before there was work, and the worker had the right
to express his opinion,'' said laborer Ramon Arias, as he painted a
tractor by the roadside. Two farmhands with him made similar
comments, but refused to give their names.
   Chileans will decide Oct. 5 in a yes or no ballot on a new term
for Pinochet, the right-wing army commander who seized power in a
bloody 1973 coup and has already ruled longer than any previous
president.
   If a majority vote for him, he will remain as president until
1997, but the military junta that he has headed as the governing
body since 1973 will be disbanded. If he loses, open elections will
be held in a year and he must hand over power in 1990, when a new
Congress, two-thirds elected and one-third appointed, will go into
place.
   Farmowner Olea and others like him have benefited from an
export-oriented, free-market economic program carried out by
Pinochet's administration. Foreign sales of grapes and other fruit,
much of it grown in the Central Valley, have been booming. With
government credits and technological assistance, many farm owners
are expanding production and making solid profits.
   But they have not forgotten the chaotic, radical reform programs
launched by President Salvador Allende, a self-declared Marxist
elected in 1970 and toppled in the coup led by Pinochet three years
later.
   Olea's home and land were illegally seized by peasants. He
negotiated with them so he could live in his house, which also had
been taken over, while they worked his land as they liked.
   ``We lived through a savage lack of order,'' said Luis Aullet,
who is partner with his brother Cesar in a 70-acre farm. ``There
was no respect for your home, your land.''
   Cesar Aullet said the Allende government sent ``experts'' with
no knowledge of agriculture to supervise land reform programs.
``What we fear is (that kind of) ignorance,'' he said.
   The landowners said that, with the production boom, conditions
for farm workers were improving significantly.
   ``Manpower is becoming scarce, and there's competition in
salaries to attract workers,'' Cesar Aullet said. ``Anyone who
wants work can find it.''
   The Aullets said that at the height of the harvesting season,
workers could not be found for less than 1,000 pesos, about twice
the minimum legal daily wage and equivalent to about $4.
   Their positive vision of rural Chile is shared by Pinochet's
campaign strategists, who predict overwhelming voter support from
the heartland.
   Opposition leaders contend that the countryside's poor majority
are suffering economically and are eager for a change but won't say
so publicly because they fear losing their jobs or government
benefits, such as pensions and housing subsidies.
   The opposition's political campaign is aimed at overcoming such
fears, while recognizing them as legitimate. One prominent campaign
slogan in the countryside is ``Say yes, but vote no.''
   Several farm workers said harvesting jobs paid an average 700
pesos, or less than $3 a day, and lasted only a few months a year.
``You can't live on that,'' Arias said.
   Jorge Contreras, who sells bread from the back of his small,
battered truck in the countryside around San Fernando, said most of
his customers opposed Pinochet's continued rule.
   ``I travel 50 kilometers (30 miles) a day, and I can tell you
there are a lot more people for the `no' vote than the `yes'
vote,'' he said.
   But he added: ``Lots of people may vote `yes' because they're
afraid.'' He said that in one remote town on his bread route,
Tinguiririca Alto, ``people are telling each other that if you vote
`no,' you'll be arrested.''
   The government has said the vote will be secret, and the
opposition has publicized its plans to have representatives at each
polling place to prevent intimidation.
</TEXT>
