<1ST_LINE>u i AM-OLY--Newspage-Diving     09-20 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OLY--Newspage-Diving,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Diver Louganis Wins Gold Medal A Day After Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Greg Louganis won his second
consecutive Olympic gold medal in men's springboard diving Tuesday
just a day after he hit the back of his head on the board.
   Sporting a bare spot on his head, Louganis gave a picturesque
performance and knocked off two Chinese challengers.
   He finished with 730.80. Tan Liangde of China, runner-up to
Louganis at the 1984 Summer Games, had 704.88 to win the silver
medal and Li Deliang of China finished with 665.28 to take the
bronze.
   The other American, Mark Bradshaw, came in fifth with 652.99,
behind Albin Killat of West Germany who had 661.47 points.
   The dive that marred Louganis' performance in Monday's
preliminaries caused him no problem Tuesday. The reverse
2{-somersault in the pike position earned three 9s, three 8.5s and
one 8. In the preliminaries, he received two zeros, one .5, three
1s, one 1.5 and five stitches.
   Louganis, 28, is seeking to become the first man to win both the
springboard and platform events in consecutive Olympics. He
captured his first Olympic medal in 1976 when, at the age of 16, he
finished second in the platform competition.
</TEXT>
