<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador     09-20 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebel-Ordered Transport Ban Largely Heeded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A vast majority of bus and
truck drivers heeded a nationwide transportation ban called by
leftist rebels despite assurances from the military that traffic
would be protected.
   Only a handful of mass transit buses circulated Monday in this
capital of 1 million inhabitants, forcing workers to walk to their
jobs or pay inflated fares to pickup truck and van owners.
   More than 70 percent of urban bus traffic was halted and
inter-city service was even more severely curtailed, an official of
the bus owners' association told The Associated Press.
   A dispatcher at one of San Salvador's two terminals said 90
percent of the bus service between provinces was stopped.
   The indefinite ban on bus and truck traffic was the fifth called
this year by Marxist-led guerrillas waging a nearly 9-year-old war
against the U.S.-backed government. Previous rebel bans lasted
three days each.
   The government urged citizens to ignore Monday's ban, saying the
military would protect vehicles.
   Col. Mauricio Vargas, the army chief of operations, told YSU
radio that about 13,000 soldiers were providing and protecting
transport.
   ``We refuse to allow a violent minority to impose its will on
us,'' he said.
   Soldiers rode shotgun aboard several state-owned buses
circulating in the capital and some army trucks carried passengers
to and from the city outskirts.
   Lorgio DeLeon, a 48-year-old father of six, was stranded at the
eastern bus terminal with no way to get to his tailor's job in
Zacatecoluca, 35 miles southeast of San Salvador.
   ``This hurts the poor worker more than anyone. We don't work
today, we get our pay docked,'' he said.
   Rebels of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front said the
ban was in response to the actions of riot troops who broke up a
Sept. 13 demonstration by leftist university students.
   The troops used tear gas and clubs and fired shots in the air to
disperse nearly 3,000 students at that protest. About 250
demonstrators were arrested.
   All but 14 were subsequently released, with the remainder
charged with what the government called ``terrorist acts.''
</TEXT>
