<DOCNO> AP880920-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 0323EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Long-termCare     09-20 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Long-term Care,570</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release 10 a.m. EDT; time set by source</NOTE>
<HEAD>Study Says Many People Can't Collect On Nursing Insurance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six out of 10 people with private nursing home
insurance are likely to receive no benefits because of restrictions
on their policies, says a study released today by the United
Seniors Health Cooperative.
   The study by the consumer advocacy group concludes ``many of the
policies now being offered for sale ... are not likely to pay
adequate benefits if and when people need them.''
   While there may be a role for the private insurance industry in
filling the national need for long-term care protection, ``this
role should not include selling bad policies to unsuspecting
consumers,'' the study said.
   Jim Firman, president of the Washington-based group, and William
Weissert, director of the program on aging at the University of
North Carolina, conducted the study. They based their findings on
an analysis of 77 typical private long-term health care insurance
plans offered by 21 companies.
   The most common restriction, found in 77 percent of the plans,
was that a person must first be hospitalized for his or her
condition before being allowed to collect benefits for subsequent
nursing home care.
   ``Fifty-four percent of nursing home admissions do not come
directly from a hospital and will not qualify for coverage under a
plan with this restriction,'' the report said.
   The other major limitation, included in 40 percent of the plans,
said people must first receive skilled-level nursing home care
before they can qualify for lower levels of long-term care. Such a
requirement excludes 46 percent of nursing home residents, the
study said.
   ``The effect of these exclusions is even more dramatic and
troubling'' when combined with waiting periods and other
restrictions, the report said. ``The average probability of not
collecting benefits... was 61 percent, if you are admitted to a
nursing home.''
   Although 95 percent of the plans studied said they cover
patients with Alzheimer's disease, the researchers said 81 percent
of the plans contain the two major restrictions regarding
hospitalization and skilled care.
   ``Given the long duration and deteriorating characteristics of
Alzheimer's disease, it is likely that for much of the patient's
period of illness, these restrictions would preclude eligibility
for coverage,'' they said.
   The study said the most common type of nursing home coverage is
a $50-a-day indemnity benefit _ an amount it labeled ``grossly
inadequate'' to meet the expected costs of care.
   If someone purchased such a plan now and entered a nursing home
in 20 years, the study said, out-of-pocket costs could reach up to
$130,000 if the plan had no inflation protection. Two-thirds of the
companies studied did not offer inflation protection.
   ``For most people who are in a nursing home for a long period of
time, the effect of most of the plans we studied will be to delay
but not to prevent eventual impoverishment,'' the researchers said.
   Fifty-six of the plans studied offered home health care
coverage, but substantial restrictions ``make it unlikely that most
persons in need of home care will collect significant benefits,''
the study said.
   The most common restriction is requiring a prior covered nursing
home confinement before a policy-holder can tap into home care
benefits. Other plans require only prior hospitalization, according
to the report.
   Several lawmakers have introduced long-term care insurance
schemes involving the federal government or joint public-private
efforts; Congress is expected to consider the matter seriously next
year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
