<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 0252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Census-Homeless     09-20 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Census-Homeless,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Census Planning Special Homeless Count</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special effort to count the nation's
homeless will be conducted as part of the 1990 Census.
   Cynthia Taeuber of the Census Bureau said Monday that officials
have decided to hold a separate count, a few days before the
regular national census, in an effort to count those living on the
streets and in shelters.
   The homeless have become an increasingly visible part of
American society, but there are no concrete estimates of their
numbers.
   On March 20, 1990, Census takers will visit emergency shelters,
both public and private, and will go to various street locations
which have been identified as places the homeless congregate, said
Taeuber.
   The street search for the homeless will be conducted from 2 a.m.
to 4 a.m., and shelters will be visited from 6 p.m. to midnight,
she said.
   Census officials will be working with various groups and
agencies that serve as advocates for the homeless, explained
Taeuber, in order to determine in advance where to look for these
people.
   In addition, the agency will encourage people with those groups,
and the homeless themselves, to work as enumerators in the count.
However, these workers will have to pass the same written exams and
other criteria as all Census workers.
   Census day for most of the nation is April 1, 1990. The count of
the homeless is being taken a few days early, however, because many
shelters close at the end of March or beginning of April, Taeuber
said.
   She added that the Census Bureau will not try to define who
constitutes a homeless person. Instead it will merely issue counts
of people living on the streets and those staying in various types
of shelters.
</TEXT>
