<1ST_LINE>r w PM-RuralHealth     09-20 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rural Health,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grants Awarded For Rural Health Research Centers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than $1 million in federal grants have
been earmarked for five rural health research centers that will
provide information on a range of concerns about medical services.
   The awards were announced Monday by Otis R. Bowen, secretary of
the Department of Health and Human Services, at the first meeting
of the National Advisory Committee on Rural Health. The panel was
created last June to advise Congress and HHS.
   Bowen said the economic diversity of America's towns and
villages must be taken into account in considering ways of
improving rural health care services.
   ``Twenty-eight percent of the rural counties in this country
depend on manufacturing as a source of economic support; a
surprising 21 percent have become retirement settlements; 13
percent depend on farming and 8 percent rely on oil and mining,''
Bowen said.
   Jerry Coopey, a Department of Health and Human Services
spokesman, said that among the problems faced in trying to provide
adequate health services in rural areas are: too few medical
personnel, especially in obstetrics and gynecology; the closing of
small hospitals; and the rising costs of malpractice insurance.
   The research center grants were awarded to:
   _Rural Health Office of the Arizona Area Health Education
Center, College of Medicine, University of Arizona, Tucson,
$209,486;
   _Health Services Research Center, University of North Carolina,
Chapel Hill, $237,000;
   _Center for Rural Health Services, Policy and Research,
University of North Dakota, Grand Forks, $195,739;
   _Research Section, Department of Family Medicine, School of
Medicine, University of Washington, Seattle, $216,028;
   _Marshfield Medical Research Foundation, Marshfield, Wis.,
$202,747.
   Bowen, who practiced rural medicine as a family physician in
Indiana, also announced an award of $69,000 to the National Rural
Health Association in Kansas City, Mo., to support publication of
its Journal of Rural Health and to compile information on rural
health research projects.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
