<DOCNO> AP880920-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 0139EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-MarilynQuayle Bjt   09-20 0752</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marilyn Quayle, Bjt,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marilyn Quayle: Husband's Strong-Willed Adviser Campaigns on Her
Own</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marilyn Quayle has done ``20@20.'' Her husband
Dan, the Republican running for the country's No. 2 job, has not.
He sometimes stumbles over his words. She never does.
   He can freeze when a reporter asks an unexpected question. She
is always prepared, and the only frozen look is the one she icily
bestows on an unfriendly questioner.
   Mrs. Quayle, who is on her first solo national campaign swing
this week, is considered one of the stronger assets of her
husband's campaign.
   Her skills, said a senior campaign official, have ``been
recognized'' and she has been asked to travel independently,
hooking up with the Indiana senator for joint appearances one or
two days each week.
   At 39, Mrs. Quayle is a self-possessed woman whose flip hairdo
and toothy smile evoke early Mary Tyler Moore. She is a mother of
three and a lawyer, although she hasn't practiced for some years.
   As a political wife, she's strong willed, fiercely protective
and her husband's most trusted adviser.
   On the campaign trail, she can be warm and cordial, quick with a
handshake for her husband's supporters or a hug for children at a
day care center. But she also can be cold and withdrawn, especially
around reporters.
   A practiced campaigner, Mrs. Quayle nevertheless is unaccustomed
to the Nancy Reagan-like role she has played so far _ smiling
pleasantly at her husband's side, applauding at the appropriate
points.
   ``I've never sat listening to him give speeches and all of that.
I always had my own schedule'' of campaigning, she said in a recent
interview.
   She handles most situations with aplomb. When a precocious
4-year-old at a Colorado day care center commented on Mrs. Quayle's
slightly protruding teeth as ``a little buck,'' Mrs. Quayle smiled
and said cheerfully, ``Not many people notice that.''
   She believes the press has given her husband ``the bad rap'' in
coverage of controversies over his military service, academic
record and personal life. She told Barbara Walters on ABC-TV's
``20@20'' program that the press was after her husband because he
was so conservative. She hasn't changed that view.
   ``I have my opinion, which is reinforced by some studies that
have been done on where the majority of the media is coming from.
... It's liberal,'' she said.
   She often pulls her husband away from reporters, touching his
arm or patting him on the back if he begins to respond to impromptu
questions.
   It is on such occasions, when Quayle talks extemporaneously,
that he tends to misspeak or otherwise garble his words. But Mrs.
Quayle says she is ``not trying to protect him.''
   ``He'd stand there and talk forever,'' she said. ``I'm trying to
get him back on the plane.''
   He is outgoing and affable. She seems more introspective, often
aloof. But theirs appears to be a marriage more of similarities
than differences.
   Dan Quayle and Marilyn Tucker met in 1972 when both were
attending night classes at Indiana University Law School. Ten weeks
later they were married. They opened a law office together in
Huntington, Ind., Quayle's hometown. Mrs. Quayle worked until the
birth of their second son.
   She is her husband's closest aide. At one news conference,
Quayle said his wife ``is my best adviser, my strongest supporter,
the person that I love more than anybody else in this world.''
   ``She is a very strong, independent-minded woman and she and I
have a very close relationship,'' he said.
   Mrs. Quayle says simply: ``I have a husband who has always
valued my opinion and used me as an aide. ... Our basic fundamental
values are the same. We have the same philosophy.''
   She says she thus far achieved everything she has set out to do.
For several years she has enjoyed oil painting. Eventually, she
says, she may go back to work.
   Her children _ Tucker, 14, Benjamin, 11, and Corinne, 9 _ all
have ideas about what they want to be. She says she wants them to
``pick their goals and make them high enough that once they reach
them or try to attain them, they don't feel that they've
shortchanged themselves.''
   As for her own goals, Mrs. Quayle hasn't picked out a pet
project or special area she would like to concentrate on as a vice
president's wife.
   ``I'm one of those people that have learned in politics you
don't plan anything until the election is over,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
