<1ST_LINE>r w PM-InfantMortality     09-20 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Infant Mortality,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Health Officials Say Care for Poor Women Is Inadequate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A panel of former and present Cabinet-level
health officials agreed that care for America's poor women and
children is inadequate but disagreed on how to improve it.
   Arthur Fleming, who served from 1958-61 as Secretary of Health,
Education and Welfare, the forerunner to today's Department of
Health and Human Services, said the United States needed a
``universal system of coverage'' to ensure adequate care.
   Margaret Heckler, HHS secretary from 1983-85, agreed that health
care services for the poor needed improvement. But Heckler, the
current U.S. ambassador to Ireland, said, ``If it is based on the
system in Great Britain, we don't want that. I've seen it and many
people are now asking to go to private physicians.'' Britain has a
nationalized health care system.
   ``That's not what we're talking about,'' Fleming countered.
``Great Britain has got a government in power that has starved the
system.''
   The comments were made Monday at a meeting of the National
Commission to Prevent Infant Mortality, which is composed of HEW
and HHS secretaries from the Eisenhower through the Reagan
administrations. The group was asked to help find ways to make
child health a national priority, but it issued no program for
action.
   Sen. Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., chairman of the commission created
by Congress, presented the problem in graphic terms.
   ``Millions of children are forced to go without health care
because they can't afford it or they can't find it,'' Chiles said,
noting that the U.S. infant mortality rate in 1985 ranked 19th
among all industrialized nations.
   ``This simply means that a child born in Singapore or Hong Kong
will have a better chance of reaching its first birthday than a
child that is born in the United States,'' he said. ``This means
that nearly 40,000 babies every year in our country will be in a
cemetery rather than in a nursery.''
   Current HHS Secretary Otis R. Bowen put the emphasis on what
parents and local leaders can do, not on federal government
involvement.
   ``Innocent babies are being crippled by AIDS, alcohol or drug
abuse,'' Bowen said, adding that ``50 to 60 percent of all health
costs in the United States are spent on preventable health
problems.''
   He urged prospective parents to make the necessary lifestyle
changes to ensure their children's health and asked religious
leaders to help the children make the proper lifestyle choices.
   Bowen also noted the actions business could take in providing
proper child care and health services to working mothers, as well
as contributions to medical research.
   ``This is a problem that people can do something about,'' said
David Mathews, HEW secretary from 1975-77. ``For all our efforts to
describe the problem, we give the impression that only if you are
professional, if you're an expert, can you do something about the
problem. And that's not true.''
   Other panelists were Joseph A. Califano Jr., HHS secretary
1977-79; Robert Finch, HEW secretary 1969-1970; Elliot Richardson,
HEW secretary 1970-73; and Richard Schweiker, HHS secretary 1981-83.
   Areas of agreement among panelists included:
   _The health care delivery system does not match the population's
needs.
   _Pregnant women cannot get adequate health care.
   _For too many of those who need it, insurance is not available.
   _Too little is being spent on prevention of children's health
problems.
   _There is a fragmentation of services which should be offered at
central locations.
   _The federal government should take some responsibility in
setting up above- standard day care facilities.
</TEXT>
