<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PhillipsGift     09-20 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Phillips Gift,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Industrialist Gives $1.5 Million to Art Gallery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Phillips Collection art gallery announced
Monday it has received a $1.5 million donation, the largest since
its founding, from Japanese industrialist Yasuhiro Goh.
   Phillips officials say they believe Goh's donation is the
largest and possibly the first significant gift from a Japanese
citizen to an American museum.
   ``I like the Phillips, because it's comfortable, a unique sort
of museum,'' said Goh, who has been visiting the gallery for about
40 years.
   Goh said he decided to make the contribution after being asked
to join the gallery's board.
   National Gallery director J. Carter Brown and Tom Freudenheim,
the Smithsonian's assistant secretary for museums, said such a
large gift from a private Japanese citizen was ``unprecedented''
and asked for Goh's address and telephone number.
   Goh's wife is a member of the Ishibashi family, which founded a
collection of French and Japanese impressionist and
postimpressionist art in Tokyo about the same time that Duncan
Phillips began his collection in the first quarter of this century.
But Goh stressed that Phillips gift comes from him, not the
Ishibashi Foundation or the family's Bridgestone tire company.
   The donation will go toward expansion of a wing of the gallery
to be opened in May 1989 which now will be named the Goh annex.
</TEXT>
