<1ST_LINE>u a AM-NavyDeath 2ndLd-Writethru a0629 09-20 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy Death, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0629,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Other Instructors Back Up Rescue-Swimmer Teacher's Story</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with defense resting, closing
arguments scheduled for Thursday. Picks up 2nd graf pvs.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two rescue-swimmer instructors testified
under immunity Monday, backing up the story of a sailor standing
court-martial in the drowning of a Navy recruit during a training
exercise.
   The defense rested later Monday, and the trial was recessed
until Thursday when closing arguments will be made by lawyers on
both sides.
   The military judge, Cmdr. Newell D. Krogmann, planned to meet
Tuesday with lawyers to work on instructions for the panel of five
officers hearing the case. One panel member asked for an additional
day's delay because Wednesday is Yom Kippur, a Jewish holiday, said
Lt. Cmdr. Dennis Hessler, a Navy spokesman.
   Petty Officer 2nd Class Michael Combe, 28, of Tempe, Ariz., has
denied he helped push Airman Recruit Lee Mirecki back into a
swimming pool March 2 after Mirecki panicked and climbed out.
   He also testified that Mirecki, 19, from Appleton, Wis.,
completed a lifesaving maneuver, in which he freed himself from a
head hold applied by Combe, just seconds before collapsing in the
pool at Pensacola Naval Air Station.
   The Navy has accused Combe of forcing Mirecki's head under water
and charged him with involuntary manslaughter, battery and
conspiracy to commit battery.
   Combe was in the pool at the time other instructors pried
Mirecki away from an equipment rack and ``dropped him back in the
water,'' testified Petty Officer 2nd Class Frankie D. Deaton.
   Deaton said he and now-retired Petty Officer 2nd Class David
Smith, who testified Friday, were joined by two other instructors,
whose identity he was unable to remember, in pushing Mirecki into
the pool.
   Deaton said he didn't see what happened after Mirecki was tossed
back in the pool because he went into the lockerroom.
   But Petty Officer 2nd Class John Zelenock was close by and
supported Combe's contention that Mirecki completed the escape and
put Combe in a cross-chest carry.
   ``I really felt good about it overall because I figured his
(Mirecki's) confidence level was boosted 100 percent,'' Zelenock
said.
   Between the time Mirecki was returned to the pool and his
drowning, the recruit had grabbed a rope dividing the pool. Combe
admitted last week he dunked Mirecki for three seconds to get him
to drop his grip.
   Zelenock testified that while at the rope with Combe, Smith and
Mirecki, the recruit said, ``I can't do it. I can't do it. I can't.
I can't.''
   ``I asked, did he want want to be here? And he definitely said
`yes' to me.''
   At that point, Zelenock said he told Mirecki to get on with the
procedure or get out of the pool, and the recruit stayed in.
</TEXT>
