<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolClothes     09-20 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Clothes,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dress Code Aims at Ending Thefts, Rivalry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school made famous by Eddie Murphy has
banned gold chains, designer sunglasses or other expensive status
symbols to prevent an expensive competition students can't afford,
the principal says.
   ``I see and hear about the youngsters being shot over gold
chains as they walk to and from school,'' Mumford High School
Principal Robin E. Oden said. ``My kids (students) have been
harassed. Recognizing that, I want to make sure that it doesn't
spill over into the school.''
   The dress code established this school year also bans tank tops,
jogging suits, snakeskin-adorned gym shoes and like finery at the
2,500-student, inner-city school, which gained fame through
T-shirts Murphy wore in the film ``Beverly Hills Cop.''
   A student who violates the code gets a written notice, which is
sent to his or her parents. Repeat offenses can result in a
three-to five-day suspension.
   Oden said a 14-year-old student told him last year that she had
heard a dress code was being considered and that she hoped one
would be adopted.
   ``She said she couldn't afford to purchase expensive things and
felt bad when she couldn't compete with her peers,'' the principal
said. ``That troubled me, so I talked to other students and found
out they felt the same way.''
   Rivalry involving expensive clothing has sometimes turned
violent. Two 17-year-old boys were wounded by gunfire last year
after one was robbed of a blue sheepskin jacket.
   Three years ago, a Detroit retailer threatened to discontinue a
brand of gym shoes when a 13-year-old was shot in the chest after
giving his gym shoes to five youths who demanded them.
   On a recent afternoon, some students were spotted near Mumford
High wearing gold or other expensive jewelry and other banned
items. They said they stashed it at school during the day, then
wore it home.
   Oden said a student who did the same thing was assaulted by two
boys who robbed her of two gold chains. He said he told other
students of the incident at an assembly.
   Oden said he is encouraged by the students following the code.
   ``I invite you to stand out in the hall and I dare you to find
any gold jewelry,'' he said. ``We've had to deal with some
students, but we have not had any suspensions to this day. About 98
percent of my students adhere to the dress code to the letter.''
</TEXT>
