<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Patients-AIDS     09-20 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Patients-AIDS,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Board Approves Policy To Let Patients Veto Care By AIDS Carriers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite criticism from the American Medical
Association, the county board voted Monday to give patients at Cook
County Hospital the right to refuse treatment from health care
workers who are carriers of the AIDS virus.
   The hospital would become the first in the country to adopt such
a policy. Hospital officials said they have not yet developed a way
to implement it, however.
   The county board, which also serves as the hospital's board of
directors, voted 15-2 to adopt the policy. Approval was expected,
after the policy was adopted by the board's Health and Hospital
Committee last week.
   The policy covers all hospital workers who ``routinely provide
direct patient care'' including doctors and nurses. But medical and
hospital associations have called it misguided.
   ``Our reaction is one of dismay,'' said Dr. Lonnie Bistow,
speaking for the AMA, after the committee vote last week. ``There
has been no case in this country of a patient contracting the AIDS
virus from a health-care worker.''
   Acquired immune defficiency syndrome destroys the body's
defenses against diseases, leaving a person prey to
life-threatening infections and certain cancers.
   AIDS has struck more than 72,000 people in this country since
1979 and killed more than 40,000 of them, according to the natioal
Centers for Disease Control.
</TEXT>
