<1ST_LINE>r i PM-OlympicScalper     09-20 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Olympic Scalper,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Scalper Jailed For Five Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 30-year-old Wisconsin man was
sentenced to five days in jail today for selling Olympic tickets at
a $33 profit, police said.
   James K. Rush of Madison was the first person to be jailed for
scalping Olympic tickets, police said. He was caught Monday selling
five tickets for a diving event for a profit totaling 24,000 won
($33.33), they said.
   Police said Rush told them he bought 44 tickets for Monday's
diving competition at a travel agency in Los Angeles early this
month, but had been unable to sell 34 of the tickets.
   In South Korea, it is illegal to resell tickets at prices higher
than face value at places of public entertainment, stadiums or
transit centers. The maximum penalty for such offenses is 30 days
in jail.
   Meanwhile, Yonhap News Agency reported that two American
teen-agers were booked for investigation on charges of theft after
they were caught snatching a large flag with the five-ring Olympic
emblem from a roadside pole today.
   The report said the two unidentified youths told police they
wanted to give the flag as a gift to their friends.
</TEXT>
