<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoxOffice     09-20 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Box Office,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`A Fish Called Wanda' No. 1 Box Office Lure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``A Fish Called Wanda'' lured enough moviegoers
last weekend to bag first place in the nation's box office
rankings, which was weakened by the Olympics and bad weather.
   ``Wanda,'' a comedy starring John Cleese and Jamie Lee Curtis,
earned $2.55 million, according to figures provided by Exhibitor
Relations Co. It was the comedy's first time in the top slot after
10 weeks of release.
   But the overall box-office take was down for the weekend. By
comparison, ``Moon Over Parador,'' took in $3.2 million for first
place the previous weekend.
   ``Between the Olympics and the ball games, both college and
professional, and the normal letdown for this time of year, box
office suffered,'' said Exhibitor Relations chief John Krier.
``Hurricane Gilbert and cold weather in some areas were also
factors.''
   In second place was ``Die Hard'' with $2.54 million, followed by
``Moon Over Parador,'' which sold $2.45 million in tickets.
``Nightmare On Elm Street 4: The Dream Master,'' earned $2.2
million for fourth place.
   Disney's ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit'' earned $2.08 million,
edging ``Betrayed,'' with $2.07 million, for fifth and sixth place,
respectively.
   In another close-ranking, ``Young Guns'' drew $1.9 million for
seventh place, and ``Cocktail'' stirred up $1.8 million in ticket
sales for eighth spot.
   Ninth was ``Married To The Mob'' with $1.39 million, and the
Eddie Murphy comedy ``Coming To America'' re-entered the top 10
with $1.30 million for 10th place.
   Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations, with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross and number of weeks in
release.
   1. ``A Fish Called Wanda,'' MGM, $2.55 million, 1,207 screens,
$2,117 per screen, $45.1 million, 10 weeks.
   2. ``Die Hard,'' 20th Century Fox, $2.54 million, 1,371 screens,
$1,853 per screen, $65.3 million, 10 weeks.
   3. ``Moon Over Parador,'' Universal, $2.45 million, 1,143
screens, $2,145 per screen, $6.6 million, two weeks.
   4. ``Nightmare on Elm Street 4: The Dream Master,'' New Line,
$2.2 million, 1,465 screens, $1,516 per screen, $41.3 million, five
weeks.
   5. ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit,'' Disney, $2.08 million, 1,393
screens, $1,498 per screen, $135.9 million, 13 weeks.
   6. ``Betrayed,'' MGM, $2.07 million, 1,101 screens, $1,882 per
screen, $19.6 million, four weeks.
   7. ``Young Guns,'' 20th Century Fox, $1.9 million, 1,358
screens, $1,443 per screen, $34.7 million, six weeks.
   8. ``Cocktail,'' Disney, $1.8 million, 1,364 screens, $1,379 per
screen, $63 million, eight weeks.
   9. ``Married To The Mob,'' Orion, $1.39 million, 827 screens,
$1,691 per screen, $16.2 million, five weeks.
   10. ``Coming To America,'' Paramount, $1.30 million, 830
screens, $1,571 per screen, $121 million, 12 weeks.
</TEXT>
