<DOCNO> AP880920-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 0238EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-Bush     09-20 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Bush,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Aides Accuse Bush Of Lies; Promise To Fight Back</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aides to Michael Dukakis, incensed by what one
called George Bush's misleading ``statistical hit-and-run,'' are
organizing Democratic surrogates to respond more aggressively to
the vice president's attacks, which in recent days have focused on
the Massachusetts economy.
   That strategy was evident Monday when, within hours of a Bush
speech, the Dukakis campaign called on eight business leaders to
meet with reporters to rebut Bush's characterization of the
Democratic nominee as an anti-business governor.
   Dukakis advisers, frustrated by what they contend has been far
too little scrutiny of Bush's attacks, promised similar events in
the future.
   The latest salvos have particularly angered the Dukakis camp
because they center on the Massachusetts economy _ the backbone of
the Dukakis candidacy.
   ``Our view is that a candidate has an obligation to tell the
truth to the American people,'' said Kirk O'Donnell, a senior
Dukakis adviser. ``But George Bush has played fast and loose with
the facts last week and he's doing it again this week. It's what we
call statistical hit-and-run.''
   Last week Bush charged that Massachusetts taxpayers had suffered
under Dukakis and that the state was $7.4 billion in debt, a figure
the Bush campaign cited to assert that Dukakis since 1983 had
amassed more debt than all the governors ``from the Pilgrims to Ed
King,'' his predecessor.
   The figures he cited to support the increased tax burden indeed
showed that per-capita taxes increased in Massachusetts from 1983
to 1987 but failed to factor in record growth of personal income in
the state during that period. Taxes were cut in those years _
mostly over Dukakis' objections _ but the average Massachusetts
resident pays more taxes because he or she is earning more money.
   And while Dukakis is authorized to issue bonds totaling $7.4
billion, the state's current bonded indebtedness is $3.9 million _
lower in inflation-adjusted dollars than the debt Dukakis inherited
from King.
   ``The bottom line is that in taxes, across the board,
Massachusetts citizens pay more than they did several years ago,''
said Bush spokesman Mark Goodin. ``We're not going to back down one
iota.''
   Bush continued his assault Monday, telling a Chamber of Commerce
luncheon in Pennsylvania that Dukakis had an ``anti-business
scheme'' and that the number of business bankruptcies in
Massachusetts was up 23.7 percent during the first six months of
the year while the national rate had fallen 23.5 percent. Goodin
said the figures came from the Small Business Administration.
   Dukakis aides said they had not seen those figures but again
accused Bush of misrepresentation _ citing figures showing business
failures in Massachusetts had declined by 28 percent since Dukakis
became governor in 1983, and that they had occurred at less than
half the national rate during the Reagan presidency.
   ``We're running against a guy who kicked off his campaign in
Disneyland,'' said Dukakis spokesman Mark Gearan, referring to a
Labor Day appearance there by Bush. ``He has Goofy as his economist
or something and is throwing out daffy statistics. This is the kind
of opponent we have and expected and we are prepared to run
against.''
   Gearan, citing New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley's appearance on a
weekend news program to support Dukakis' views on defense and
foreign policy, said leading members of the Democratic Party would
be called on to rebut some Bush charges while Massachusetts
business and industry leaders would address Bush comments about the
state economy.
   ``My company has grown and prospered under the leadership of
Governor Dukakis,'' Wang Computer Co. founder An Wang, a Dukakis
supporter, told the Monday briefing. ``He created the atmosphere
that made it possible for us to grow.''
   Dukakis will respond as well when he sees fit, said Gearan, who
with other Dukakis aides encouraged increased media scrutiny of
Bush's statements.
   ``Bush has a record of being wrong,'' O'Donnell said. ``Not only
are we on notice but the press is on notice. He has consistently
misrepresented the facts and not been accurate.''
   Goodin rejected that characterization as ``nonsense.''
   ``I think the big lie is that they are making Massachusetts out
to be some sort of economic miracle,'' Goodin said.
</TEXT>
