<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LaunchFailure     09-20 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Launch Failure,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trident Missile Fails, Is Destroyed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy's new Trident 2 submarine
missile has suffered a second failure in its last three test
firings, its wreckage tumbling into the Atlantic Ocean after it
went astray and was deliberately blown up.
   The $23.7 million missile blasted off a land launch pad Monday
and appeared to be accelerating smoothly across a clear sky when it
suddenly exploded several miles above the ocean.
   The Navy reported that the Trident 2 had developed a problem in
the second stage about 60 seconds after liftoff, and when it veered
off course, the range safety officer sent a radio signal to ignite
explosive packages in the vehicle.
   The failure was the third in 15 test firings for the missile
being groomed as the most powerful in the Navy's nuclear arsenal.
But two of the last three have been destroyed by the range safety
officer.
   The 44-foot, three-stage missile has nearly 6,000-mile range,
but the Navy declined to disclose how far the unarmed warhead
package was to have traveled Monday.
   Five more land pad launches are scheduled here, to be followed
by at least five test launches from submerged submarines. It was
not known if the latest failure would have an impact on the test
schedule.
   The weapons is scheduled to be deployed late next year.
   Each Trident 2 is designed to hurl up to 10 nuclear warheads to
different targets. There will be 24 of the missiles in each Trident
submarine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880920-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 0348EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-GeneralAssembly     09-20 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-General Assembly,0650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>43rd General Assembly Convenes As U.N. Chief Praises Peacemaking
Role</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEAD prospects uncertain. Assembly holds ceremonial opening
at 3:30 p.m. EDT, then elects new president.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations opens its 43rd General
Assembly with enhanced prestige due to the Iran-Iraq truce and
Afghan accords, a reputation that may tarnish once debate begins.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar wryly observed that
the world body, convening today, has high expectations to live up
to.
   ``If the United Nations is treated as an angel, then we must
remember that the halo that slips 10 inches is a noose,'' he said
at a luncheon of the U.N. Correspondents Association on Monday.
   The session opens with the election of the president of the
General Assembly after a behind-the-scenes fight that has revived
some lingering enmity from the 1982 Falkland Islands War between
Britain and Argentina.
   Foreign Minister Dante Caputo of Argentina has campaigned hard
against Barbados' U.N. ambassador, Dame Ruth Nita Barrow, who
Britain has backed.
   Diplomatic sources said the race was too close to call, and
there could be several secret ballots before one candidate wins a
simple majority of the assembly's 159 voting member states. The
outgoing president is Peter Florin, from East Germany's Foreign
Ministry.
   The United Nations has won progress and praise with its
Iran-Iraq truce, Afghan accord, and other looming peace initiatives
in southern Africa, Cambodia and the Western Sahara. But the
general debate that begins Monday may generate more heat than light.
   One fight is expected over a proposed address by South Korea on
the 40th anniversary of its founding. Both it and communist North
Korea have non-voting observer status and cannot speak before the
assembly without an invitation.
   The United States, Japan and other nations back South Korea's
speech. But the Soviet bloc has opposed the move and sponsored a
resolution Monday inviting North Korea to deliver an address.
   China has not sponsored either resolution but opposes a South
Korean speech.
   On Monday, President Reagan is to deliver his final speech to
the world body, which his administration has criticized over the
years for bureaucracy, waste and an anti-Western bias.
   The Soviet foreign minister, Eduard A. Shevardnadze, and
President Francois Mitterrand of France also are to address the
assembly. The session will hear 13 heads of state, six prime
ministers and numerous foreign ministers.
   The assembly will again take up intransigent issues such as
peace in the Middle East and the Palestinian uprising in Israel's
occupied lands.
   In his annual report released Monday, Perez de Cuellar painted a
cautiously optimistic picture of the organization, citing:
   _the U.N.-mediated Afghanstan accords signed April 14 under
which about 100,000 Soviet troops are leaving that nation;
   _a U.N.-supervised cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war that began
Aug. 20;
   _the Iran-Iraq peace talks that opened Aug. 25;
   _a U.N.-sponsored meeting between Greek and Turkish Cypriot
leaders of divided Cyprus;
   _initiatives for peace in Western Sahara, South-West Africa and
neighboring Angola and positive signs for a political settlement to
the guerrilla war in Cambodia.
   Perez de Cuellar noted continuing problems in the Middle East,
Central America, South Africa's enforcement of apartheid and the
division of the Korean Peninsula.
   The secretary-general said the United Nations still faces a
financial crisis, despite a U.S. promise to pay $144 million in
arrears and hundreds of millions of dollars in other back dues for
previous years and for peacekeeping funds.
   The Peruvian diplomat said the organization faces a cash
shortage ``which threatens insolvency in the next few months, and
the virtual depletion of reserves.''
   He said he would ask the General Assembly urgently to consider
new ways of raising money, such as voluntary contributions,
interest-free loans and changes in the scale of assessments.
</TEXT>
