<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 0137EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ForestFiresRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0401 09-20 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forest Fires Rdp, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0401,0699</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yellowstone Fire Managers Say Fires May Hold, Humidity Helps In
Calif</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with confirmed evacuations,
increases acreage count on Vacaville fire to 17,000 acres, two
firefighters critically injured; picks up 5th graf pvs, `Fifteen
fires ...'; SUBS grafs 10-11 pvs, `The Miller ...' with two grafs
to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong winds late Monday fanned an arson fire over a containment
line and into the Northern California town of Vacaville, forcing
500 people to flee, but cool, damp weather helped firefighters
battle blazes in the Northwest.
   The sheriff's department ordered the evacuation from home in
rural Vacaville, but most complied voluntarily, said California
Department of Forestry spokesman John Ferreira.
   The fire, which has destroyed nine homes and charred more than
17,000 acres of brush, is the larger of two major Northern
California blazes. The other destroyed six homes as it roared
across about 8,000 acres of wildland, brush and timber near Redding.
   At the fire in Redding near Shasta County, two men clearing
burned timber were seriously injured Monday when a tree fell on
them, forestry officials said. Both men, suffering head and back
injuries, were hospitalized in critical condition, officials said.
   Fifteen fires still burning Monday had charred 1.39 million
acres in Wyoming, Montana, Washington, Oregon, Idaho and
California, said Arnold Hartigan of the Interagency Fire Center in
Boise, Idaho. In all this season, 69,099 fires have blackened
4,140,000 acres, including about 2 million acres in Alaska, he said.
   The dwindling number of civilian and military firefighters in
Yellowstone National Park worked Monday to deepen fire lines around
fires that have burned 1.1 million acres of the 2.2 million-acre
park.
   Officials said they can now reduce the number of firefighters in
the park, which once totaled more than 8,000. About 550 soldiers
returned to Fort Lewis, Wash., on Sunday after four weeks, and two
battalions were preparing to leave.
   In addition, officials had started releasing employees of the
National Park Service, U.S. Forest Service and Bureau of Land
Management, said fire information officer Marv Crocker.
   ``There are no real hot fires out there,'' he said. ``If there
were, we'd keep the agency people for their experience. There's
nothing very exciting out there today.''
   The Miller fire that destroyed nine homes near Vacaville, 55
miles northeast of San Francisco, was 50 percent contained Monday.
But estimates that the fire would be controlled by Wednesday
morning had to be abandoned when the fire jumped a road Monday and
forced the closure of another, said Alleah Haley, a state forestry
spokeswoman.
   Control of the 8,000-acre Fern fire that destroyed six homes
near Redding in Northern California was predicted for Tuesday
evening, said CDF spokeswoman Sharon Wages.
   Officials said about 5,500 firefighters remained in and around
Yellowstone on Monday, including about 4,000 Army soldiers and
Marines, Crocker said.
   ``Until the fires are out, there is still some potential
threat,'' said park spokeswoman Joan Anzelmo. ``Primarily, the
crews are doing mop-up on existing fire lines, working back into
the fire and creating a bigger break.''
   Fire experts were optimistic that recent frosty days in the park
may have spelled the end of burning conditions such as those that
allowed blazes to race across miles in hours.
   ``I would be surprised if the fires made any more major runs,''
said fire behavior analyst Bruce Freet. ``I think we're into a
cooling, moist trend. I won't say wet, but this might be enough to
hold it where it's at right now.''
   Crews also were being reduced at fires remaining in Oregon,
Washington and Montana, and outdoor fire restrictions were lifted
in Montana and in part of Idaho. Officials in Montana said about
940 firefighters remained at the 35,400-acre Red Bench fire in
Glacier Park and in west-central Montana just three 20-member crews
monitor the smoldering 247,000-acre Canyon Creek fire.
   ``It's all due to the fact that we've gotten a lot of rain up
here, and looking at the forecast we're going to get more,'' said
Allen Gibbs, spokesman for the Panhandle National Forest in Idaho.
</TEXT>
