<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Fireworks     09-20 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Fireworks,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fireworks Factory Blast Kills Five</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion in a private fireworks factory
killed five people, including the owners and their 12-year-old son,
and injured nine, a newspaper Daily reported today
   The Guangming Daily said the Aug. 23 blast was triggered when
the 12-year-old, who worked at the factory, mishandled fuses. He
and the four other victims died in the hospital.
   The paper did not explain the delay in reporting the accident,
the second fireworks explosion in fourth months in coastal Zhejiang
province's Congnan County. In June, an explosion at another factory
injured 15 workers, including 13 children.
   Safety standards generally are low in China's more than 90,000
small-scale private and township-run fireworks factories, and
accidents are common. The most recent government statistic says 644
fireworks factory employees were killed in accidents in 1986.
   Eighteen people died last December in a nearby Jiangxi province
factory where untrained workers were instructed to cut the
fireworks' fuses by hand.
   China has begun drafting workplace safety regulations but
enforcement is lax.
</TEXT>
