<DOCNO> AP880920-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 0340EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Debate-Talks     09-20 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Debate-Talks,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Bush Campaigns Spar on Debate Questioners</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush and Michael Dukakis will step
forward to take questions in their first presidential debate
Sunday, but it remains unclear who will be asking those questions.
   Dukakis, the Democratic hopeful, proposed Monday that the four
commercial television network news anchormen be the moderator and
panelists, sources familiar with the negotiations said.
   Bush, the GOP candidate, had his own list of four possible
peacekeepers and 10 questioners from both electronic and print
journalism.
   By late Monday, the question of questioners was still being
debated by Bush and Dukakis aides as the Sunday date for the
face-off at Wake Forest University in North Carolina drew closer.
   The last-minute sparring is typical of presidential campaigns,
complete with accusations that the other side is breaking their
agreement not to talk about any of the arrangements.
   The first debate is sponsored by the parties' commission on
debates. The second presidential debate, due Oct. 13 or Oct. 15 in
Los Angeles, is sponsored by the League of Women Voters.
   This most recent volley between the campaigns erupted Monday,
when Dukakis campaign chairman Paul Brountas called Bush campaign
chairman James Baker to propose the four-anchor idea for all three
debates.
   Sources who spoke only on the condition they not be identified
said Brountas suggested that the anchors from CBS News, ABC News,
NBC News and the Cable News Network be the moderators and
questioners during both presidential debates and the vice president
debate scheduled Oct. 5 in Omaha.
   That would mean CBS's Dan Rather, NBC's Tom Brokaw, ABC's Peter
Jennings and probably CNN's Bernard Shaw would be on stage for all
three events. And contacts were made with the news organizations to
see if they would agree, one source said.
   `This is a television event,'' said one Dukakis aide of the
idea. ``We want to do what we can to make it an event that people
will pay attention to. We think that they anchors would make it a
bigger event ... More people would watch it.''
   Bush aides flatly rejected the Dukakis idea of all the
presidential debates as well as the vice presidential one.
   The idea is ``blatantly unfair to the print media and other
television correspondents,'' said one Bush aide.
   But a Dukakis aide said that their proposal was still on the
table, despite the Bush campaign's stance.
   The Bush source said the campaign responded later Monday with a
list of four proposed moderators and 10 panelists. The source would
not name any of them, saying only the list was made up of network
anchors, network correspondents and print representatives.
   The Bush source also accused the Dukakis campaign of violating
the agreement not to talk about such matters.
   ``We are operating under a written agreement of understanding
not to discuss the negotiations surrounding'' debate details, said
the aide. ``Obviously that has been violated,'' and thus the source
gave the Bush campaign position on the matters.
   While pre-debate squabbling is normal, the difference this year
is there is no third party _ such as the League of Women Voters _
as the moderator of the pre-debate debate.
   The two political parties tried to wrest the debate sponsorship
away from the league with the formation of the bipartisan debate
commission. But the league _ which has sponsored debates in the
past three presidential campaigns _ kept fighting for a role.
   When the two campaigns agreed to split sponsorship of the
debates, that left them to deal more directly with each other on
these pre-debate matters than in the past.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
