<DOCNO> AP880920-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 0340EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hurricane-Mexico     09-20 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hurricane-Mexico,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flood Survivors Try To Salvage What They Can</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scores of people returned to salvage
possessions from the Santa Catarina riverbed, where a flash flood
spawned by Hurricane Gilbert devastated their homes, but most came
up empty.
   People lined the banks Monday, digging with their hands in the
muck. What was for decades a dry riverbed with thousands of homes
had become a mangled landscape of twisted metal and crumbled
concrete.
   Maria Costa, her husband and their six children, had lived on
the riverbed in a two-room home made of concrete blocks and tin.
Their clothing, furniture and new school books were washed away.
   ``We went yesterday to see it, but there wasn't a thing to
save,'' Ms. Costa said as she washed her 10-month-old son's diapers
in a bucket of water. ``Even the blocks were gone. Now where do we
go?'' she asked.
   More than 100 people were killed in the sudden, storm-whipped
rebirth Saturday of the Santa Catarina, which became a savage
torrent 10 feet deep and 450 feet wide as Hurricane Gilbert dumped
12 inches of rain on the city.
   ``We just got three blankets out and lost everything else,''
said Ramona Carrizales Lopez, sitting outside a shelter for the
homeless.
   Mrs. Lopez was among thousands of people who had built meager
homes in the riverbed that cuts through this industrial city in
northern Mexico's most populated region.
   The riverbed suddenly swelled with water, sweeping away entire
ramshackle communities, miles of roads and a sprawling sports
complex with miles of tennis and basketball courts, soccer and
baseball fields and jogging tracks.
   Four buses and other vehicles were dragged into the torrent. The
bus passengers are presumed to comprise most of the 100 people
confirmed dead.
   The Nuevo Leon state government said a ``considerable number''
of people were missing and 30,000 people were lodged in shelters
around the state.
   Alejandro Chapa, mayor of San Pedro-Garza Garcia, the suburb of
Monterrey hit hardest by the disaster, said Monday that his first
priority is to find better lodgings for the 7,000 homeless people
in his community.
   He said those people with homes on the riverbed that escaped
ruin would be allowed to return there only provisionally.
   ``We're asking for a place to put them,'' Chapa said. ``Houses
can be built pretty fast, but not in a month.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880920-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 0339EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PollMethod     09-20 0942</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poll Method,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll Methods Are Explained</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poll-Election Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Media General-Associated Press poll is
based on telephone interviews Sept. 6-14 with 1,125 adults in the
continental United States. The phone numbers were selected randomly
by computer, and interviews were conducted with the adult who had
the most recent birthday.
   The results were weighted to adjust for variations in the
sample. The poll has a three-point margin of error, meaning that if
every adult American were asked the same questions, the results
theoretically would be within three points of the poll's results,
19 times out of 20. The error margin is larger for subgroups _ four
points, for example, for those who said they planned to vote and
had decided on a candidate.
   There are other sources of potential error in polls, including
the wording and order of questions. These are the questions and
responses in this poll; because of rounding, some totals may exceed
100:
   1. Do you plan to vote in this year's presidential election, or
not? Yes: 85 percent. No: 12 percent. Don't Know-No Answer: 2
percent.
   2a. (If yes) George Bush is the Republican nominee for president
and Michael Dukakis is the Democratic nominee. Have you definitely
decided which presidential candidate you'll vote for in this year's
election, or not? Yes: 66. No: 30. DK-NA: 4.
   2b. (If yes) Which presidential candidate will you definitely
vote for in this year's election? Bush: 56. Dukakis: 39. DK-NA: 5.
   2c. Are you leaning strongly to vote for one of the presidential
candidates, or haven't you made up your mind? Yes: 44. No: 50.
DK-NA: 6.
   2d. Which presidential candidate are you leaning strongly for in
this year's election? Bush: 53. Dukakis: 41. DK-NA: 6.
   3. Do you think the outcome of the election _ that is, whether
George Bush wins or Michael Dukakis wins _ will have a major impact
on your life, or won't have much impact on your life? Major: 45.
Not much: 45. DK-NA: 10.
   4. And do you think whether George Bush wins or Michael Dukakis
wins will have a major impact on the future of the country, or
won't have much impact on the future of the country? Major: 71. Not
much: 20. DK-NA: 9.
   5. If George Bush wins, do you think that as president he will
be able to accomplish most of what he says he wants to do? Yes: 36.
No: 46. DK-NA: 18.
   6. What if Michael Dukakis wins _ do you think that as president
he will be able to accomplish most of what he says he wants to do?
Yes: 31. No: 48. DK-NA: 21.
   7. Regardless of how you may vote, do you think George Bush or
Michael Dukakis will do a better job of ...
   a. helping more people achieve the American dream? Bush: 39.
Dukakis: 35. DK-NA: 25.
   b. reducing the federal budget deficit? Bush: 38. Dukakis: 30.
DK-NA: 32.
   c. improving education in America? Bush: 33. Dukakis: 39. DK-NA:
29.
   d. maintaining a strong defense? Bush: 67. Dukakis: 15. DK-NA:
19.
   e. helping the poor? Bush: 21. Dukakis: 56. DK-NA: 23.
   f. helping the middle class? Bush: 36. Dukakis: 40. DK-NA: 25.
   g. helping the rich? Bush: 67. Dukakis: 10. DK-NA: 25.
   8. Do you think that George Bush ...
   a. understands the complicated problems a president has to deal
with? Yes: 77. No: 16. DK-NA: 7.
   b. offers a vision of where he wants to lead the country? Yes:
60. No: 25. DK-NA: 15.
   c. has clear positions on the issues? Yes: 52. No: 31. DK-NA: 16.
   d. cares about people like you? Yes: 50. No: 37. DK-NA: 13.
   g. is a strong leader? Yes: 50. No: 34. DK-NA: 16.
   h. says too many things carelessly, without considering the
consequences? Yes: 42. No: 41. DK-NA: 17.
   i. would have good judgment under pressure? Yes: 60. No: 23.
DK-NA: 17.
   9. How about Michael Dukakis. Do you think that Michael Dukakis
...
   a. understands the complicated problems a president has to deal
with? Yes: 44. No: 45. DK-NA: 11.
   b. offers a vision of where he wants to lead the country? Yes:
62. No: 25. DK-NA: 13.
   c. has clear positions on the issues? Yes: 47. No: 37. DK-NA: 16.
   d. cares about people like you? Yes: 62. No: 24. DK-NA: 13.
   g. is a strong leader? Yes: 47. No: 32. DK-NA: 21.
   h. says too many things carelessly, without considering the
consequences? Yes: 30. No: 51. DK-NA: 19.
   i. would have good judgment under pressure? Yes: 51. No: 21.
DK-NA: 29.
   10. Do you think it's more likely that taxes would be raised in
a Bush administration, or in a Dukakis administration, or isn't
there likely to be any difference when it comes to raising taxes?
Bush: 11. Dukakis: 38. No Difference: 45. DK-NA: 6.
   11. Do you think of George Bush as a liberal, moderate or
conservative? Liberal: 9. Moderate: 28. Conservative: 50. DK-NA: 14.
   12. And do you think of Michael Dukakis as a liberal, moderate
or conservative? Liberal: 41. Moderate: 33. Conservative: 11.
DK-NA: 15.
   13. Are you better off than you were four years ago? Yes: 59.
No: 36. DK-NA: 5.
   14. Are you better off than you were eight years ago? Yes: 64.
No: 31. DK-NA: 6.
   15. In the next few years, do you expect your family's financial
situation to get better, or worse, or stay about the same? Better:
55. Worse: 6. Same: 33. DK-NA: 5.
   16. Who do you think would be better at managing the federal
government _ George Bush or Michael Dukakis? Bush: 51. Dukakis: 34.
DK-NA: 16.
