<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 0227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Biolab Bjt   09-20 0720</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biolab, Bjt,0738</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Scraps High-Level Biological Warfare Lab</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERN ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOOELE ARMY DEPOT, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army's decision to scrap
plans for a high-level biological warfare test lab in Utah has
drawn praise from state officials, but an environmentalist says
residents still can't rest easy.
   The Army announced Monday it will no longer seek approval for
the lab designed for experiments with genetically altered microbes
or deadly micro-organisms for which there are no known antidotes.
   Instead, Army officials said, they will downgrade the proposed
``biosafety level 4'' laboratory at Dugway Proving Ground to a new
$5.3 million level-3 lab where scientists can experiment with
biological agents for which there are vaccines or cures.
   ``The people of Utah are still at more risk,'' said Jeremy
Rifkin of the Foundation on Economic Trends in Washington, D.C.
``It's easier for viruses to get out of this facility than the one
they proposed. The chance of a micro-organism escaping is low. But
if one does escape, it could be catastrophic.''
   Rifkin said his organization, which brought legal action forcing
the Army to conduct a more extensive environmental assessment of
the proposed lab, would seek another injunction if the Army went
ahead with its plans without a new environmental impact study.
   Michael Owen, the Army's deputy assistant secretary for
installations and logistics, said the level-3 lab would be used for
tests of materials and defenses against biological attack similar
to those conducted at Dugway since the early 1950s in a lab that
now is outdated.
   ``The Army's decision is based on an extensive evaluation of the
requirements for biological defense,'' Owen said. ``Existing Army
BL4 facilities will be used to satisfy any future needs for
material testing that requires a containment level higher than
BL3.''
   The Army's original draft environmental statement, published in
February, said the higher-level lab would be used only for level-3
experiments, but it did not rule out experiments with more exotic
and deadly agents in the future.
   Owen said the final environmental impact statement due next
spring would identify the level-3 lab as ``the preferred
alternative for construction.'' The draft document had listed it
only as a possible alternative, concluding a level-4 lab would be
safer.
   Utah's congressional delegation and Republican Gov. Norm
Bangerter praised the Army's decision. In March, Bangerter had
vowed to block construction of a higher-level lab, including
withholding state construction permits, and later met with Army
officials to seek a compromise.
   ``I appreciate the Army's new-found willingness to compromise
with the people of Utah and negotiate with me as governor on
matters which affect the state and its citizens,'' Bangerter said.
   The governor said he would announce within days the composition
of a civilian-scientist oversight committee to monitor testing at
the desert outpost 70 miles southwest of Salt Lake City.
   ``I will insist the open process continue and the Army shares
with the people in the state information regarding what testing is
being performed in Utah,'' Bangerter said.
   During a public comment period that ended Aug. 2, the Army
received 107 comments, 103 of which opposed building the facility.
   Owen said the outcry over the Army's initial plan was ``not the
sole determining factor in the decision,'' but he added, ``we try
to be good neighbors.''
   ``There was never a decision to back down or away from, as
such,'' he said. ``We did not have a decision prior to now.''
   Owen said there are five higher-level containment labs in the
United States where the Army could conduct such tests, if needed,
including its own lab at Fort Detrick, Md.
   On Monday night, 100 people attended an Army hearing at Tooele
Army Depot on the draft environmental impact statement governing
the Pentagon's biological defense research program. The document
concluded that the program ``does not create significant adverse
impacts on the quality of the environment'' and perceived risks are
``very much exaggerated.''
   It also rejected the idea of a non-military management of the
testing program, saying it would not mute controversies relating to
such issues as genetic engineering, highly infectious organisms or
aerosol testing.
   The United States abandoned research into offensive biological
weapons in 1969 and later signed a treaty banning their use or
possession. The Army continues to conduct research into defensive
measures against biological warfare, such as masks and vaccines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
