<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     09-20 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Tumble In Tokyo Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices plunged on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
Tuesday while the U.S. dollar inched up against the Japanese yen.
   The dollar closed at 134.15 yen, up 0.35 yen from Monday's close
of 133.80 yen. After opening at 133.62 yen, the currency gained
further ground during the day's session, moving within a range of
133.57-134.15 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues plunged 352.42
points, or 1.26 percent, to finish the day's session at 27,548.58.
The market's main index dropped sharply at the start of trading
Tuesday and continued its downward spiral to record the largest
single-day decline since Sept. 10, when the index lost 431.69
points.
   Prices were lower across the board with the exception of a few
pulp and paper issues, according to traders.
   A dealer with Daiwa Securities in Tokyo said share prices fell
``because of a selling drive among investors'' due to the decline
overnight in New York trading.
   ``There might be some concern over the emperor's (Hirohito)
condition among investors, but it's not a major factor affecting
trading,'' the dealer said.
   But other dealers said buy orders were on the rise for
paper-related issues in anticipation of a sharp increase in the
demand for paper in the near future. The demand for paper rises
with the death of any member of the imperial family as government
and business offices print large volumes of announcements.
   Aging Emperor Hirohito vomited blood late Monday and was given
two blood transfusions. Palace officials maintained that his
condition was ``nothing to be concerned about.''
   In foreign exchange, the dollar opened at 133.62 yen, down 0.18
yen from Monday's close, and was trading at 133.77 yen by late
morning.
</TEXT>
