<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Teamsters-Endorsement     09-20 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teamsters-Endorsement,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teamsters Delay Candidate Endorsement Until Mid-October</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Brotherhood of Teamsters is
giving its members more time to vote on their presidential
preference, putting off the union's possible endorsement of a
candidate until mid-October.
   ``My guess is that we're not going to do any endorsement until
our next board meeting Oct. 17,'' Teamsters spokesman Duke Zeller
said Monday.
   Zeller said the 1.6 million-member union has extended until
Sept. 30 the deadline for the rank and file to return poll ballots
on presidential preferences that were mailed to them three weeks
ago.
   Zeller said 10,000 to 12,000 of the ballots have been returned
to Teamsters' headquarters here but have not been tallied.
   With the extended deadline, he said, the responses cannot be
tabulated and analyzed before the next meeting of the union's
18-member executive board Oct. 17-19 in Orlando, Fla.
   The Teamsters were among three of the AFL-CIO's 91 affiliated
unions that abstained last month from the labor federation's
overwhelming endorsement of Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis.
   Until the death of former Teamster President Jackie Presser in
June, union officials had expected the executive board to endorse
Dukakis.
   Several union officials have said the Justice Department's
indictment of Presser in 1986 and a civil suit in June aimed at
taking control of the Teamsters as a corrupt organization have
soured relations with President Reagan and Vice President George
Bush.
   The new Teamster president, William McCarthy of Boston, is known
to dislike Dukakis.
   One Teamster official, speaking only on condition that he not be
identified, said he does not expect the executive board to make any
endorsement this year unless the rank-and-file poll shows
overwhelming support for Dukakis.
   The Teamsters were the only major union to endorse Reagan in
1980 and 1984, although with less enthusiasm the second time. It
made no endorsement in the 1976 race which Jimmy Carter won against
President Ford.
   Since 1952 the Teamsters have endorsed four Democrats and four
Republicans.
</TEXT>
