<HEAD>Stocks Down, Dollar Up On News Of Emperor Hirohito's Health</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices plunged today on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange in apparent reaction to Emperor Hirohito's failing health.
The dollar edged up against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues shed 352.42
points or 1.26 percent to close at 27,548.58. The main index, which
rapidly lost 169.20 points to move down to 27,731.80 points shortly
after the market opened, kept declining afterwards. It was the
fourth biggest one-day decline this year.
   In a moderate trading with volume on the first section estimated
at 1 billion shares, stock prices were lower across the board
except for a few print-related issues such as paper and pulp, said
an analyst with Nomura Securities.
   ``Investors were mainly selling stocks trying to get ready if
the worst happens to the emperor. Their concern was, for example,
the stock market might be closed in that case,'' he said, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   Hirohita, 87, vomited blood Monday night, and was reported in
stable conditon. The emperor also has been reported to have
jaundice.
   Meanwhile, the dollar opened lower at 133.62 yen and finished
the day's trading at 134.15 yen, up 0.35 yen from Monday's close.
   A dealer with Mitsubishi Bank said the emperor's condition did
not affect trading on the foreign exchange market.
