<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrugAgentSlain     09-20 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Agent Slain,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Closing Arguments For Mexican Nationals Accused In Camarena Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drug smuggler and a former Mexican police
official were pawns in a vendetta brought about by two countries
that desperately wanted to avenge the death of a U.S. drug agent,
defense attorneys say.
   ``Demand justice, not politics,'' attorney Michael Pancer urged
jurors Monday, insisting that Rene Verdugo Urquidez, 36, had
nothing to do with the 1985 torture-slaying of Drug Enforcement
Administration agent Enrique Camarena.
   ``Rene Verdugo was offered up to you on a silver platter by the
police in Mexico,'' Pancer told the jury. ``Are you going to take
the scapegoat they offer you?''
   U.S. District Judge Edward Rafeedie scheduled the prosecutor's
rebuttal argument today, saying he would submit the case to the
jury later in the day.
   Yolanda Barrera, chief deputy federal public defender, said
another defendant, Raul Lopez Alvarez, 28, a former Guadalajara
homicide investigator, is a victim of the government's desire to
avenge the Camarena killing at any cost.
   She contended that the defendant's videotaped discussion of the
Camarena slaying with an undercover agent was typical of his
penchant for inventing stories to inflate his own importance.
   ``Mr. Lopez Alvarez ended up in this trial for acting like a
child,'' she said. ``He is a man caught up in the web of his own
lies. He told one lie too many.''
   Admitting that Verdugo was a marijuana smuggler, Pancer accused
Mexican officials of conspiring to blame Verdugo for Camarena's
killing. He said the U.S. government went along with the idea.
   ``Ladies and gentlemen, tell the government of Mexico by your
verdict that you will not accept a scapegoat,'' said Pancer. ``Tell
them that you want the people who were really involved and who are
being protected down there.''
   He accused U.S. prosecutors of engaging in ``illusion, deception
and lies'' to convince jurors that Verdugo participated in
Camarena's torture and murder.
   ``The government has tried to appeal to your emotions,'' he
said, ``to make you feel guilty about rendering the correct
verdict. Don't let them do that.''
   Camarena was abducted in Guadalajara on Feb. 7, 1985. His body
and that of his pilot, Alfredo Zavala Avelar, were found buried at
a remote ranch in Mexico several weeks later. They were severely
beaten and Camarena's skull was crushed.
   Prosecutors sought to show that Verdugo was a leader of a drug
cartel run by Rafael Caro Quintero and that he helped kill
Camarena. Authorities have depicted Caro as the mastermind of the
Camarena killing.
   The third defendant, Jesus Felix Gutierrez, 38, is accused of
helping Caro escape from Mexico after the killings.
   Key evidence against Verdugo is a strand of his hair found at
the Guadalajara home where Camarena is believed to have died and
the testimony of a witness who saw Verdugo at the house near the
time of Camarena's death.
   Nine men were indicted in Los Angeles in connection with the
slaying, but only three are on trial here. Caro, 33, and three
other defendants are in custody and awaiting trial on related
charges in Mexico. An eighth man has died and another is a fugitive.
</TEXT>
