<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RockwellIndictment     09-20 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rockwell Indictment,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defendant Pleads Guilty, Judge Denies Dismissal Motions By
Contractor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former executive for Rockwell International
Corp. has pleaded guilty to charges that he schemed to double-bill
the Air Force by nearly $450,000 on contracts for a satellite
navigational system.
   In an agreement with prosecutors, Robert Zavodnick, a former
manager of major subcontracts at Rockwell, entered the plea Monday
to one count of conspiracy and one count of making false
statements, said Assistant U.S. Attorney George B. Newhouse Jr.
   U.S. District Judge Consuelo Marshall denied motions to dismiss
the conspiracy count and a count of criminal contempt on the part
of Rockwell, said Mary McMenimen, a spokeswoman for the
prosecutor's office.
   ``We're very disappointed,'' said Rockwell spokesman Jeff
Charney. ``Rockwell intends to continue to defend itself vigorously
against the government's charges.''
   Zavodnick, 46, of Fountain Valley, is scheduled to be sentenced
Nov. 28, Newhouse said. He faces a maximum sentence of 10 years in
prison and a $500,000 fine.
   The company, Zavodnick, and Donald Carter _ who was the
materials division director at the Seal Beach plant _ were named in
a 25-count federal indictment in January.
   Zavodnick has offered to testify for the government in exchange
for charges of mail fraud and another count of making false
statements being dropped, Newhouse said.
   Carter is scheduled for trial Oct. 18 on one count of
conspiracy, three counts of mail fraud and two counts of making
false statements, the prosecutor said.
   The indictment alleged the company and two men double-billed the
government for work on the NAVSTAR global navigation system that
uses radio signals from satellites to pinpoint locations on Earth.
   Rockwell received $446,283 in unlawful profits as a result, the
indictment said.
</TEXT>
