<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 0702EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KodakSettlement     09-20 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kodak Settlement,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Considers Settlement For Buyers Of Discontinued Kodak
Cameras</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer for Eastman Kodak Co. customers who
bought the company's discontinued instant cameras says only about
200 people have balked at a plan to give them $50 to $70 in cash
and coupons.
   Attorney Perry M. Berke told Cook County Circuit Judge Thomas
Rakowski on Monday that about 3.4 million people have been approved
for compensation.
   ``It demonstrates you have an overwhelming approval of the
settlement,'' Berke said.
   Rakowski, who presided over a hearing in the case, said he would
rule Sept. 26 on whether the proposed $195 million plan should be
accepted to settle a class-action lawsuit filed by customers.
   The cameras were rendered virtually useless in 1985 when a
federal court said the company had violated several Polaroid Co.
patents on instant film and cameras. That court ordered Kodak to
stop producing film for its line of instant cameras.
   Under the proposal, those who bought the cameras would receive
$19.50 to $52 in cash, with the balance made up in coupons for the
purchase of other Kodak products, said William Harte, one of the
lawyers for the plaintiffs in the class-action lawsuit. The amount
would depend upon the model of camera the person owned, he said.
   ``It is clearly a generous settlement. It is clearly a fair
settlement,'' said William Campbell, a lawyer representing the
Rochester, N.Y.-based Kodak.
   Critics of the plan say an insufficient amount of money is
involved, no provision exists to compensate for accessories like
camera bags and some steps toward getting a rebate were difficult.
   The proposed settlement is limited to U.S. owners. Kodak made 16
million of the instant cameras for domestic sale from 1976 to 1985.
   Harte said 4.3 million camera owners were notified of the
settlement proposal by direct mail, and 3.4 million have valid
claims. About 100,000 more filed claims that are being reviewed by
a court-appointed arbitrator, he said.
   The deadline for filing claims was Sept. 9, and those who have
not filed will not be able to get refunds, he added.
   Instant photography was invented by Edwin H. Land, founder of
Polaroid, and was first marketed in 1948. It enables users to view
a photographic print within moments of taking a picture.
   Polaroid retained a monopoly in the instant photography field
until 1976, when Kodak entered the market with a competing system.
   A week later, Polaroid sued Kodak, charging patent infringement.
   A federal judge in Boston sided with Polaroid. The U.S. Supreme
Court let stand lower court rulings when it refused to hear Kodak's
appeal in October 1986. Polaroid is seeking $5.7 billion in damages
from Kodak.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
