<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TropicalWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0496 09-20 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tropical Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0496,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Depression Forms In Eastern Atlantic</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 2-4, ``It's out ...,'' with 4 grafs to UPDATE with
6 a.m. EDT position, prediction, quote on depression possibly
becoming a tropical storm.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new tropical depression with the potential to
strengthen formed in the eastern Atlantic as the remnants of
Hurricane Gilbert spread from Texas to Illinois.
   ``It's out there. There's no land in front of it or anything
else,'' Martin Nelson, National Hurricane Center meteorologist,
said Monday. ``It's got a chance.''
   At 6 a.m. EDT today, satellite pictures showed the 14th
depression of the Atlantic hurricane season was centered about 700
miles west-southwest of the Cape Verde Islands off the west coast
of Africa.
   The system was moving west at 10 to 15 mph with sustained winds
estimated at 35 mph with higher gusts in squalls, forecasters said.
   ``Conditions appear favorable for strengthening and the
depression could become a tropical storm in the next 12 to 24
hours,'' said Max Mayfield, one of the center's hurricane
specialists.
   The depression, which would be called Helene if its winds reach
39 mph, formed while the last remains of Gilbert swept from Texas
to Illinois with heavy rain and flooding.
   Gilbert killed more than 200 people, left hundreds of thousands
of people homeless and caused more than $8 billion in damage as a
blew from the Caribbean to Mexico.
   Storms become hurricanes when sustained winds reach 74 mph.
Gilbert was the third hurricane of the season, which runs from June
1 to Nov. 30. September is the peak month for tropical weather
activity.
</TEXT>
