<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Steadies, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was little changed in subdued European
trading early today ahead of the release of U.S. economic reports
and a weekend meeting of the seven leading industrialized nations.
Gold prices were higher.
   Dealers said they doubted that the final revision of U.S. gross
national product figures for the second quarter, would stimulate
the markets. Dealers were anticipating a 3.3 percent growth rate in
the U.S. economy.
   The August rate of inflation was due to be released later in the
week.
   Dealers said market players were withdrawing to the sidelines
ahead of Saturday's opening meeting in Berlin of finance ministers
of the Group of Seven industrialized democracies.
   ``The market is very calm and should stay so as long as the
dollar is awaiting some new stimulus,'' said a dealer in Milan,
Italy.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar edged up 0.35 Japanese yen to a closing 134.15 yen.
Later, in London, it fell back to 133.90 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday:
   _1.8690 West German marks, down from 1.8695
   _1.5785 Swiss francs, down from 1.5793
   _6.3545 French francs, up from 6.3520
   _2.1080 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1100
   _1,392.25 Italian lire, down from 1,393.50
   _1.2192 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2194
   In London, the British pound held steady at $1.6785 dollars,
unchanged from Monday's late price.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $409.40 dollars a troy
ounce, up from $409.30 dollars bid late Monday. At midmorning, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$410.40.
   In Zurich, the noon bid price was $410.30, up from $408.50 bid
late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.72 dollars to close at a bid
$413.12.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a bid price of $6.35 a troy
ounce, up from $6.28 bid late Monday.
</TEXT>
