<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     09-20 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cold Front Sweeps Through Central United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A vigorous cold front blasted its way through the central Great
Lakes region and the Ohio Valley today, bringing showers,
thunderstorms and strong, gusty winds.
   In lower Michigan, winds gusted to 70 mph at Mason, causing some
structural damage and downing trees and power lines.
   Thunderstorms produced strong, gusty winds over northern
Indiana, downing trees that blocked roads in some places. In
western and northern Indiana, thunderstorm rains flooded roads and
police reported small tornadoes in three counties.
   Showers were scattered across western parts of New York, central
Pennsylvania and sections of Maryland as warm air ahead of the cold
front pushed northeastward into cooler air covering New England.
   On Monday, tornadoes were reported over parts of central
Wisconsin as thunderstorms moved through. Early today, winds were
gusty from southern Minnesota into northern Illinois.
   Another cold front swept through the Pacific Northwest into the
northern Rockies and Great Basin on Monday evening. Showers and
thunderstorms were scattered over parts of Oregon, northern
California and Nevada.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
from the Gulf Coast states through the Appalachians and upper Ohio
Valley into the northern and eastern Great Lakes and much of New
England; numerous showers and thunderstorms over southern and
central New England; scattered showers from the northern Rockies
into northern parts of the Great Basin; gusty winds from the
central Plateau into central Wyoming.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 70s or 80s over much of
the nation; in the 60s from the Pacific Northwest through northern
Nevada into the northern Plains and the Great Lakes region; from
the upper 40s into the 50s over the northern Rockies; into the
lower 90s over the Gulf Coast states and into the upper 90s to near
100 degrees across the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 30
degrees at Custer, S.D., to 82 degrees at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 72 partly cloudy; Buffalo 73 fair; Charleston,
S.C., 72 fair; Cleveland 62 cloudy; Detroit 57 fair; Miami 79 fair;
New York 66 partly cloudy; Philadelphia 69 partly cloudy;
Pittsburgh 70 partly cloudy; Portland, Maine 56 foggy; Washington
73 cloudy
   _Central: Bismarck 45 cloudy; Chicago 56 windy; Dallas-Fort
Worth 70 fair; Denver 42 fair; Des Moines 54 cloudy; Indianapolis
59 fair; Kansas City 52 fair; Minneapolis-St Paul 51 windy;
Nashville 76 fair; New Orleans 76 fair; St. Louis 60 fair
   _West: Albuquerque 54 fair; Anchorage 51 rain; Las Vegas 80
windy; Los Angeles 62 cloudy; Phoenix 81 fair; Salt Lake City 53
cloudy; San Diego 66 cloudy; San Francisco 55 windy; Seattle 54
cloudy.
</TEXT>
