<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NavyDeath     09-20 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Navy Death,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flight Surgeon: Recruit Shouldn't Have Been In Pool</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A recruit who drowned during
rescue-swimmer training had been declared unfit for the course
because of his intense fear of being dragged under water, a Navy
doctor testified at a sailor's court-martial.
   After Lt. Cmdr. David Shiveley's testimony, the defense rested
its case Monday in the trial of Petty Officer 2nd Class Michael
Combe, 28, of Tempe, Ariz.
   The defendant is charged with involuntary manslaughter, battery
and conspiracy in the March 2 death of Airman Recruit Lee Mirecki
in a training pool at Pensacola Naval Air Station.
   The trial reopens Thursday with closing arguments.
   The military judge, Cmdr. Newell D. Krogmann, was to meet today
with lawyers to prepare instructions for the panel of five officers
hearing the case. One panel member asked for an additional day's
delay because Wednesday is Yom Kippur, a Jewish holiday, said Lt.
Cmdr. Dennis Hessler, a Navy spokesman.
   Shiveley conceded Monday the system probably broke down by
allowing the 19-year-old recruit from Appleton, Wis., to return to
the Navy Rescue Swimmer School after Shiveley disqualified him from
further training.
   ``He related a pretty intense fear to me,'' said Shiveley, who
saw Mirecki a month before his death. ``I diagnosed him as possibly
having a phobia.''
   A psychologist disagreed with Shiveley's diagnosis and found
Mirecki fit for training, but neither doctor consulted the other.
   Shiveley said Mirecki should have been sent back to him before
being readmitted.
   Shiveley said while a noncommissioned officer such as Combe
cannot be expected to detect a phobia, he should have recognized
Mirecki's panic.
   Witnesses have testified Mirecki panicked and climbed out of the
pool, grabbing an equipment rack as instructors converged on him.
Mirecki was pulled free and thrown into the pool where Combe dunked
him and grabbed him in a head hold, witnesses say.
   A pathologist has testified Mirecki's phobia triggered heart
failure, then drowning.
   Two fellow instructors, who testified under immunity, backed up
testimony by Combe, who denied he helped push Mirecki back into the
pool and claimed the recruit completed a lifesaving maneuver, in
which he freed himself from a head hold, just seconds before
collapsing.
</TEXT>
