<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Boat     09-20 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Boat,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ferry Sinks, Killing At Least 61 People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An overloaded ferry sank in a south China river,
killing 61 people and leaving one missing, the official Xinhua News
Agency reported today.
   The sinking Sunday was the eighth major boat accident since July
and brought the total of people killed to more than 320, according
to official figures. Investigators have attributed most of the
accidents to human error.
   Xinhua said more than 80 passengers were on the ferry when it
sank in a river in the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region that
borders Vietnam. It said the boat was overloaded but did not give
its capacity or say if the overloading caused it to sink.
   The Ministry of Communications, which has responsiblity for
inland water navigation, announced last month it had begun an
investigation into the safety of China's river vessels to determine
if standards should be tightened.
   That move followed the July 21 capsizing of a ferry on the Min
River in southwestern Sichuan province, in which 133 people died,
and the July 25 sinking of a passenger boat on the Yangtze River in
which 71 drowned.
</TEXT>
