<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PresidentialPolls 1stLd-Writethru a0495 09-20 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presidential Polls, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0495,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush In Virtual Tie In New York, Maintains Nebraska and
Mississippi</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 new grafs after pvs 6th graf bgng, The results,
with new poll on Dukakis tank ride.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush was in an effective tie with Democrat Michael
Dukakis in New York, the cornerstone of the industrial Northeast,
while the Republican presidential nominee held substantial
advantages in polls conducted in Mississippi and Nebraska.
   A poll released Monday by the Marist College Institute for
Public Opinion showed Dukakis, the Democratic candidate, leading
Bush by 48-42 percent among likely voters.
   But the margin of error of four percentage points either way
erased Dukakis' seeming advantage. Ten percent of those polled said
they were undecided.
   The statistical dead heat came even though 65 percent of
potential New York voters said Bush ``has the experience to be
president'' and only 23 percent named the Democrat.
   At the same time, 52 percent said the vice president ``has the
ability to handle an international crisis,'' while 28 percent said
that of Dukakis. Nonetheless, when it comes to who can provide
strong leadership, Dukakis was on top, 43 percent to 36 percent,
among New Yorkers questioned.
   The results were similar to a Marist poll in March that gave
Dukakis a 47-41 percentage advantage.
   A separate poll indicated that Dukakis lost rather than gained
voter support when he posed last week wearing a helmet and riding
an M-1 battle tank at a defense contractor's plant in Michigan.
   In a telephone survey of 1,002 registered voters around the
country last Friday through Sunday, conducted for the Boston Herald
and station WBZ-TV in Boston, 25 percent said they were less likely
to vote for Dukakis based on what they had seen or heard about the
tank ride.
   Seven percent said the ride made them more likely to vote for
Dukakis, according to the poll, and more than 60 percent said they
either knew nothing about it or it had no impact on how they would
vote. The poll had a margin of error of 3 percent.
   With 36 of the 270 Electoral College votes needed to win the
presidency, New York carries more weight than any other single
state in the traditionally-Democratic Northeast.
   New York has been considered a Dukakis stronghold, in part
because Democrats have a 3-2 enrollment edge over Republicans and
also because Dukakis is from a neighboring state.
   But the state was captured by Republican Ronald Reagan in 1980
and again in 1984. In 1984, Cuomo headed up Democratic candidate
Walter Mondale's New York effort and was unable to deliver the
state for the former vice president.
   Polls released Monday in Mississippi and Nebraska, which
respectively have seven and five electoral votes, indicated Bush is
holding his comfortable leads in those states.
   Nebraskans favored Bush by 44-33 percent, according to an Omaha
World-Herald poll published Monday. The margin of error in the
survey of 755 registered voters conducted Sept. 14-15 by SRI
Research Inc. was plus or minus four percentage points.
   In Mississippi, a telephone survey over last weekend by Rick
Knox and Associates showed Bush the preferred choice of 49 percent
of those polled while Dukakis the pick of only 34 percent. The poll
of 1,000 registered voters showed just about the same margin as a
survey conducted a month ago.
   It had a margin of error of five percentage points in either
direction, however.
   The Marist poll conducted last week surveyed 601 New York voters
said to be likely to cast ballots in the Nov. 8 election.
</TEXT>
