<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StepsonKilled     09-20 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stepson Killed,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sergeant Lives `Every Cop's Worst Nightmare'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police sergeant responding to a fatal shooting
outside a housing project discovered that the victim was his own
stepson in a tragedy that his commander called ``every cop's worst
nightmare.''
   Sgt. Lonnie Owens, 43, found the body of his 19-year-old
stepson, Norris Williams, on the sidewalk near the Brooklyn project
early Sunday. The teen-ager had been shot in the chest with a 9mm
bullet and was pronounced dead at the scene.
   Less than six hours later, Carlos Davis, 18, of Brooklyn was
arrested and charged with murder and possession of an illegal
handgun. The two youths had had a long-running dispute, police said.
   ``It's every cop's worst nightmare,'' Capt. John P. Harkins,
commanding officer of the 75th Precinct, told New York Newsday.
   Owens is taking time off from work until he feels up to coming
back, Harkins said.
   He described Owens as ``a nice, quiet man, a good cop.''
   Owens joined the Police Department in 1969 and was promoted to
sergeant in 1986. He has been assigned to the 75th Precinct for
more than two years, and has received eight commendations and
citations for outstanding police work.
   Williams was the youngest of Owens' three stepsons.
</TEXT>
