<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 0908EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AbortionProtests     09-20 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abortion Protests,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Atlanta To Fine Abortion Protest Leaders Who Break Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials, exasperated by almost daily
anti-abortion demonstrations this summer, have passed a bill to
fine protest leaders who trespass or harass patients at abortion
clinics.
   The City Council voted 12-5 Monday for a measure which asks the
city attorney's office to seek court injunctions against leaders of
Operation Rescue, the group that organized the protests.
   The measure does not interfere with the right to picket and to
free speech, council members said.
   Barbara Magera, a staff member of Operation Rescue in Atlanta,
said the decision would not deter the group, which has taken
September off from the protests but vows to return in October.
   She said similar actions were taken in New York and in
Philadelphia, but protests continued.
   The protests that began during the Democratic National
Convention in July clogged the city's legal system, putting more
than 700 people in jail and costing Atlanta more than $500,000,
said Barbara Asher, chairwoman of the city's Public Safety
Commission and sponsor of Monday's resolution.
   ``They are trying to grind the machinery of this city to a
halt,'' Mrs. Asher said.
   Councilman Hosea Williams said he planned to challenge the
constitutionality of the decision in court. The civil rights leader
compared it to laws passed in the past to deny rights to blacks.
   ``This is a very dangerous bill,'' Williams said. ``It's going
to put Atlanta in such a bad light.''
   However, Councilman Jabari Simama said the bill ``will not deny
this group's rights to exercise its First Amendment rights.''
</TEXT>
