<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Unrest 1stLd-Writethru a0523 09-20 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0523,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Of Armenians Rally, Shut Down Businesses After Shootout</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS new graf 19 to update with Azerbaijani party chief's
comments, details. Picks up graf 19 pvs, `Armenians are ...' Minor
editing throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people rallied in Armenia today,
closing businesses and schools in a protest that followed a bloody
clash between Armenians and Azerbaijanis in a disputed region of
the southern Soviet Union.
   Meanwhile, one of the 25 people who the official news agency
Tass said had been hurt in Sunday's shootout died the next day, an
editor of a Tass affiliate said.
   The clash occurred in the village of Khadzhaly in the
predominantly Armenian Nagorno-Karabakh enclave of Azerbaijan, Tass
said.
   Armenian activist Rafael Popoyan, in a telephone interview from
the Amenian capital of Yerevan, said Armenians did not use weapons.
He did not elaborate. An editor for Armenpress, the Tass affiliate
in Armenia, said Monday that Azerbaijanis were the only ones
carrying firearms.
   The executive committee of Armenia's parliament was to meet
today or Wednesday to discuss protesters' long-standing demands to
annex Nagorno-Karabakh, Popoyan said.
   Armenians began campaigning in February for control of
Nagorno-Karabakh near the Turkish-Iranian border. Armenians make up
76 percent of the region's 162,000 people and have strong
historical links to the enclave, which was made part of Azerbaijan
in 1923.
   Several thousand people gathered today in Yerevan's downtown
square, an Interior Ministry officer said, and were ``just standing
around conversing.''
   Police stepped up patrols in this city, said a duty officer at
Armenia's Interior Ministry, speaking by telephone from Yerevan.
   Popoyan, a 46-year-old former political prisoner, said 1 million
Armenians attended a rally in Yerevan Monday night and demanded an
emergency meeting of the republic's parliament, the Supreme Soviet.
   A deputy director of Armenpress, who spoke on condition his name
not be used, said more than 250,000 people were at the
demonstration.
   The protesters want the Supreme Soviet to demand the annexation
of Nagorno-Karabakh, Popoyan said. The body has made such a
decision, but was rebuffed by the country's Supreme Soviet in
Moscow.
   Armenia's president, Grant Voskanyan, told Monday's rally that
parliament's executive committee would meet today or Wednesday to
decide whether to call a full Supreme Soviet session, according to
Popoyan.
   At Monday night's rally, demonstrators decided to continue a
general strike that began Friday, according to Popoyan, and many
businesses and schools were closed in Yerevan today.
   He said the demonstrators decided to continue the walkout until
the Supreme Soviet acts on their demands.
   A strike also has been reported in the main city of
Nagorno-Karabakh, Stepanakert.
   An Armenpress editor said Sunday's clash was touched off by
reports that Azerbaijanis had stoned a busload of Armenians the
previous day in the village.
   A 61-year-old carpenter injured in the shootout died Monday in a
hospital, an editor of a Tass affiliate in Azerbaijan said by
telephone from the republic's capital, Baku. Both editors spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   In Baku, Azerbaijani Communist Party chief Abdul-Rahman Vezirov
told local officials today the clashes were part of ``anti-social
activities'' among some of the populace, Tass reported. He said
required stricter controls were needed to ensure order, the agency
reported.
   Armenians are predominantly Christian; most Azerbaijanis are
Shiite Moslem. Armenians also differ linguistically and culturally
from ethnic Azerbaijanis.
   At least 32 people, 26 Armenians and six Azerbaijanis, were
killed in three days of rioting that began Feb. 28 in the
Azerbaijani port of Sumgait.
   In July, central authorities in Moscow rejected the annexation
demand and instead approved a plan to redress Armenians' grievances
of poor housing, hospitals, schools and Armenian cultural
facilities in Nagorno-Karabakh.
</TEXT>
