<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Bell     09-20 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Bell,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Who Put Up Famed Roadside Dinosaurs Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Claude K. Bell, whose dinosaur creations
became a landmark to millions of Southern California desert
travelers, has died at 91, but his family vowed that his fanciful
``dinosaur garden'' would live on.
   Bell died Monday of pneumonia at Humana Hospital in Anaheim.
   Bell and his dinosaurs have been featured in People magazine,
the film ``Pee-Wee's Big Adventure'' and a book titled ``The
Well-Built Elephant and Other Roadside Attractions _ A Tribute to
American Eccentricity.''
   The retired amusement park sculptor spent more than two decades
and $300,000 creating the giant creatures _ a 150-ton, concrete
brontosaurus named Dinney and a 100-ton tyrannosaurus named Rex _
on an otherwise desolate stretch of Interstate 10 near Palm Springs.
   The towering dinosaurs can be seen for miles by travelers
approaching the tiny community of Cabazon on the desert route
between Phoenix and Los Angeles.
   ``The dinosaurs aren't dead and they never will be,'' Bell's
daughter, Wendy Murphy of Costa Mesa, said. ``He wanted to build a
monument that would withstand the sands of time, and he has done
that.''
   Bell, a retired sculptor for Orange County's popular Knott's
Berry Farm amusement park, was in his mid-60s when he first began
building the steel-framed, 150-foot-long brontosaurus on 60 acres
of desert land he owned at Cabazon.
   It was meant to be the first of several figures in his Dinosaur
Garden theme park. Plans to add a giant mastodon and a sabre-tooth
tiger are on the drawing board.
   The park, which includes a museum and gift shop, is run by
Bell's son-in-law, Denny Rowing.
   Bell is survived by his wife, Anna Marie, a son, five daughters,
14 grandchildren and two great-grandchildren.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
