<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HowardBeach     09-20 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Howard Beach,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Sentenced in Howard Beach Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three defendants in the Howard Beach racial
assault case have been sentenced to weekends in jail for four
months.
   William Bollander, 19, Thomas Farino, 18, and James Povinelli,
18, also were placed on three years' probation and ordered to serve
200 hours of community service at their sentencing Monday.
   They were convicted of participating in a riotous assault in
late 1986 by a dozen white youths on three black men in the Howard
Beach section of Queens. The charges carried potential sentences of
up to a year in jail.
   The attack led to the death of one of the black men, Michael
Griffith, 23, who was struck by a car while fleeing the white mob.
Three white youths were convicted of manslaughter in the case last
December.
   Three other youths have been acquitted of all charges in the
case; two others were placed on probation after pleading guilty to
riot charges. The twelfth, Robert Riley, 19, has agreed to plead
guilty to manslaughter.
</TEXT>
