<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel     09-20 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0651</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Closes Territories For Yom Kippur, Arab Boy Shot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army sealed off the occupied lands today to
prevent violence during the Jewish Yom Kippur holiday. Earlier,
witnesses said an 11-year-old Arab boy was shot in the thigh by an
Israeli truck driver who was firing at stone throwers.
   The army erected roadblocks throughout the occupied West Bank
and Gaza Strip to stop Palestinians from entering Israel during Yom
Kippur, the day of atonement that was to begin shortly before
sundown today.
   In the biblical city of Bethlehem, four miles south of
Jerusalem, drivers with blue West Bank plates were turned away at
an army checkpoint. A pink sign in Arabic read: ``Dear driver, the
road to Jerusalem is closed starting at 3 p.m.''
   The army seals off the occupied lands for all Jewish High
Holidays to lessen the possibility of Palestinian attacks inside
Israel. In the 9-month-old uprising in the occupied lands, 269
Palestinians and six Israelis have been killed.
   In the Gaza Strip today, the driver of an Israeli gasoline truck
opened fire after his vehicle was stoned, said Naher Yussef
Hassilek, who was shot in the right thigh.
   ``I was passing near the gasoline pump on my way home when this
man shot me,'' Hassilek, a newspaper delivery boy, told an Arab
reporter at Ahli Arab Hospital.
   Arab witnesses said the same driver had opened fire in the area
in the past, and that he shot and wounded an Arab youth earlier
this year.
   The army said it was checking the report.
   Also today, Israeli authorities complied with a Supreme Court
order and disclosed that a 23-year-old Palestinian who died in 1987
during interrogation by secret service agents had suffocated.
Israeli officials said earlier that Awad Hamdan died of a heart
attack.
   Felicia Langer, an attorney for Hamdan's family, said an autopsy
also showed signs of an inflammation in his heart. She said she
would petition the high court for disclosure of the exact
circumstances of Hamdan's death.
   Hamdan, a resident of the West Bank city of Tulkarem, died July
21, 1987, two days after his arrest. Relatives alleged he was
tortured to death by Shin Bet secret service agents.
   Last year, Attorney General Yosef Harish ordered a police
investigation into Hamdan's death. Three Shin Bet agents were
suspended for lying about the circumstances of the death.
   One agent was subsequently ordered to stand trial behind closed
doors on charges he caused Hamdan's death by negligence.
   Also today, five Americans on a Palestinian-sponsored tour
protested the seizure of their passports by the army in the West
Bank. Army officials said the five incited an anti-Israeli
demonstration in Ramallah and would have to submit to questioning
by police to get their passports back.
   U.S. consulate officials said they brought up the incident,
which occurred Sunday, with the government. ``Our position is that
American passports are U.S. government property and should not be
taken,'' consulate spokesman David Good said.
   The Americans, touring the occupied lands at the invitation of
the San Francisco-based Palestine Solidarity Committee, claimed
they were harassed, saying the passports were confiscated while
troops were breaking up a demonstration by Palestinian women by
using tear gas and rubber bullets.
   ``We watched, shocked and horrified,'' the group said in a
statement. ``Before we knew it our passports were being demanded.
No reason was given, nor was it explained how or when they would be
returned.''
   The five are Dick Reilly, 36, a health care worker from Chicago;
Bill Doares, 33, a trade unionist from New York City; Joyce Wilcox,
43, a legal worker in the New York City law office of William
Kunstler; Judy Janda, 49, a photographer from New York City; and
Todd May, 33, a student from Pittsburgh.
</TEXT>
