<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FugitiveSlumlord     09-20 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fugitive Slumlord,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LA's Worst Slumlord Vanishes After Being Freed on Bail in New
Jersey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man authorities call Los Angeles' worst
slumlord is believed to be a fugitive again after being
inadvertently released from custody, officials said.
   Vijaynard Sharma, 41, of Inglewood, posted $20,000 bail in a New
Jersey court and was freed Friday, said Ted Goldstein, a spokesman
for the Los Angeles city attorney's office.
   Sharma, captured last week by FBI agents, had disappeared in
January while on bail pending sentencing in Los Angeles for more
than 100 housing-code violations.
   He failed to appear in a New Jersey courtroom Monday for an
extradition hearing.
   The judge who released him on $20,000 bail apparently was
unaware that Sharma had outstanding warrants with bails totaling
$2.65 million, officials said. The name of the judge was not
immediately known, said Harriet Sherman, assistant chief of
extradition in the Los Angeles district attorney's office.
   Deputy City Attorney Stephanie Sautner said she ``was pretty
surprised and a little angry'' when told of Sharma's disappearance.
   The FBI had been holding Sharma on a no-bail federal fugitive
warrant. However, ``once he was turned over to local authorities,
our warrant no longer applies,'' said John Kundts, special agent in
the FBI's Philadelphia office.
   ``We didn't feel he could be released on any bail,'' said Los
Angeles City Attorney James K. Hahn. ``That was our understanding.
It turns out that that was erroneous.''
   Sharma, a native of Fiji who once owned 18 tenement properties,
was convicted last year of 112 misdemeanor housing-code violations
involving five rat-infested residential buildings. City officials
said it was the biggest slumlord case they had ever prosecuted.
   He also is a defendant in eight pending slumlord cases.
</TEXT>
