<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Hurricane-Texas 1stLd-Writethru a0505 09-20 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hurricane-Texas, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0505,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Governor Tours Areas Hit By Hurricane, Tornadoes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd graf, `At least ...,' with quote
from Red Cross spokesman on number of homes damaged.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Bill Clements, touring this city
where Hurricane Gilbert caused an estimated $35 million in damage,
says he expects to get federal emergency assistance for the area.
   At least 41 tornadoes struck Texas in the aftermath of Hurricane
Gilbert, leaving hundreds of people without homes. Two San Antonio
residents were among the more than 200 killed overall as the storm
swept through the Caribbean and Mexico.
   Throughout south Texas, 981 homes were damaged or destroyed by
the hurricane and tornadoes, said Red Cross spokesman Frank
Stipkala in San Antonio.
   On Saturday, Clements asked the federal government to declare
Brownsville a disaster area. He toured the Rio Grande Valley and
San Antonio on Monday.
   ``This is far worse than anything in Brownsville,'' Clements
said. ``There is no place anywhere (in Texas) that suffered this
kind of damage.''
   The declaration would pave the way for assistance from the
Federal Emergency Management Agency and would enable businesses to
receive low-interest loans from the Small Business Adminstration.
   It also could ultimately help homeless residents with temporary
housing for a certain period, officials said.
   Mayor Henry Cisneros and Bexar County Judge Tom Vickers escorted
Clements on the tour.
   Among the stops was an apartment complex where a twister early
Saturday destroyed 120 units, damaged 260 units and left 300 people
homeless.
   ``It's amazing to me that no one was killed,'' Clements said as
he climbed over bricks on a tour of The Lodge Apartments.
   Vickers said city and county officials were assessing the damage
and would try to get a report to Clements later this week. The
governor said he would await that information before making the
disaster request.
   ``The approval and certification of it being declared a disaster
area can happen very quickly, but the individual payment will be
slower than that,'' Clements said. ``But the first step is to have
it declared an emergency, and I don't think we'll have any problem
doing that.''
   In contrast to the hard-hit San Antonio area, the Rio Grande
Valley may not need federal aid, officials there said.
   Harlingen Mayor Bill Card said his city suffered up to $800,000
in damage to mostly private property and the federal assistance
might not be needed.
   Brownsville Mayor Ygnacio Garza said the city spent thousands of
dollars preparing and cleaning up after the storm.
   ``Whether it will meet the criteria for a true disaster, I don't
think so, or I'm not sure and really we're not too upset about
that,'' Garza said.
   South Padre Island City Manager Eduardo Campriano said the storm
caused about $100,000 in damage to city property, mostly road
damage.
   In Corpus Christi, Nueces County Commissioner J.P. Luby said two
beach parks suffered about $100,000 damage and he was considering a
request for federal aid.
   Most of the damage in Texas was in San Antonio, where residences
at least $5 million in damage. A tornado that cut through Kelly Air
Force Base caused $28 million in damage to 12 buildings and
aircraft parts. Another tornado destroyed the air-conditioning
system at the Veterans Administration Hospital, causing $2 million
in damage.
</TEXT>
