<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CampaignAds 1stLd-Writethru a0467 09-20 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campaign Ads, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0467,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Airing TV Ads During Olympic Games</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS pvs 6th graf bgng, For his part, with 2 grafs to update
with Dukakis education ad, other developments.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential rivals Michael Dukakis and George
Bush are trying to impress a national television audience of
potential voters this month between the dives and somersaults of
the Summer Olympic Games.
   Both candidates are running advertisements during prime-time
Olympic coverage on NBC. The network is getting as much as $330,000
for 30 seconds of advertising time.
   A new Bush spot is called ``The Mission,'' featuring an excerpt
from the vice president's acceptance speech last month at the
Republican National Convention in New Orleans.
   ``I am a man who sees life in terms of missions. Missions
defined and missions completed,'' Bush says in the excerpt. ``I
will keep America moving forward, always forward. ... This is my
mission. I will complete it.''
   Bush's ad director, Sig Rogich, said the 30-second spot was
scheduled for a ``short run'' but other ads, including two
attacking Dukakis on his environmental and crime-fighting records,
would continue during the Olympics in various parts of the country.
   For his part, Dukakis was airing several Olympics spots in
battleground states such as California and Texas. They depict the
Democratic nominee as a responsible leader, an education advocate
and an anti-crime governor of Massachusetts.
   The education spot, promising an affordable college education to
anyone who wants one, dates from the Iowa primary and was added
Tuesday night, said spokeswoman Lorraine Voles. The other two ads
are new and first aired last week. She said another new spot may be
added by week's end.
   Rogich said Olympics viewers may start seeing ads tying Dukakis
to the Carter presidency, which Republicans portray as a failure.
The spots already have been produced.
   ``You could see some comparative commercials reflecting on the
Carter years, the things that he did, the same outline for the
future that comes from Michael Dukakis,'' Rogich said.
</TEXT>
