<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 1018EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-YonkersDeseg     09-20 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yonkers Deseg,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Good News, Bad News in Yonkers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major investors' service has reinstated
Yonkers' bond rating, but efforts failed to bring together the two
sides in the housing desegregation case that led to the city's
financial problems.
   Moody's Investors Service announced Monday it had reinstated the
Baa rating on obligation bonds. The highest rating is Aaa.
   The rating was based on the security derived from the setting
aside of property taxes, with the state comptroller as fiscal
agent, for the purpose of meeting debts, Moody's said. City
officials said $25.9 million was set aside.
   Moody's suspended the bond rating Aug. 4 due to uncertainties
resulting from the daily fines imposed by U.S. District Judge
Leonard Sand after the Yonkers City Council voted to defy his
housing desegregation order.
   Sand's initial fine of $100 had been due to double daily so that
the city would have faced bankruptcy by mid-August. A federal
appeals court later capped the fines at $1 million daily.
   Just as the fines hit the $1 million mark on Sept. 10, the
council voted to pass a zoning ordinance related to the location of
the affordable housing and bring itself into compliance with Sand's
order.
   Yonkers paid $819,100 in fines, $358,041 of which was given to
the city schools.
   Sand had found the city liable for 40 years of segregating
housing and schools in a 1985 landmark decision.
   Meanwhile, Assemblyman Richard Brodsky, who met with leaders of
the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, one
of the plaintiffs in the original lawsuit, and the Save Yonkers
Federation, a coalition of groups battling the plan, said Monday
that talks between the two sides broke off during the weekend.
   The federation issued a statement reiterating its plan to file a
federal lawsuit concerning the case, without specifying the grounds
or parties.
   In a statement, the coalition said, ``No housing, no sites, no
units are acceptable to us anywhere in the city of Yonkers.''
   The NAACP noted its disappointment at the breakdown of the talks
and said it remained interested in ``bringing peace to the city of
Yonkers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
