<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Zaire-Opposition     09-20 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Zaire-Opposition,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader Allowed To Return From Internal Exile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KINSHASA, Zaire (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zaire's leading opposition figure,
Tshisekedi wa Mulumba, has been freed after nearly six months under
house arrest in internal exile in Isiro in northeastern Zaire.
   Tshisekedi met with President Mobutu Sese Seko in the northern
village of Gbado-Lite on Friday, the same day the Judicial Council
lifted his punishment.
   He had been arrested Jan. 17 on charges of disturbing public
order, then provisionally freed, then was ordered into internal
exile in April after calling for a boycott of partial legislative
elections in Kinshasa, Zaire's capital.
   During the summer, rumors circulated in Zairean exile circles
that Tshisekedi, secretary-general of the Union for Democracy and
Social Progress, might have died in custody.
   On Sept. 4, the head of the Black Caucus in the U.S. Congress,
Rep. Mervyn M. Dymally, met with Tshisekedi and said the opposition
leader called on the United States to pressure Mobutu to allow a
multiparty system.
   Every citizen of Zaire, where Mobutu has ruled since 1965, is by
law a member from birth of the Popular Movement of the Revolution,
the only legal political party.
</TEXT>
