<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Webb     09-20 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Webb,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Author of `The Graduate' Leaves Benefactress' House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Author Charles Webb, who wrote ``The
Graduate,'' and his ex-wife Fred have moved out of the home of a
woman who aided the destitute couple because of a ``difference of
opinion on nudism,'' Webb said.
   Marcelle Hall recently invited the couple to stay in her home
after reading that they had little money and no permanent place to
live.
   ``It's not fair to say she threw us out,'' Webb said. ``There
was just a difference of opinion on the nudism. She got really
upset. We didn't realize nudism was such an upsetting thing,
compared to other things that go on in the world.''
   The couple said they moved into the $43-a-night Exit 5 Motel in
Danbury on Saturday night. Destitute by choice after giving away
most of their property, they have only $150 left, they said.
   ``We've got another two nights at the most,'' he said. ``We're
just sort of stunned at this point. She was generous to invite us
into her home. But there were so many things (they disagreed
about). We just feel sort of rocked.''
   Webb is waiting for a call from a lawyer to give him the
go-ahead to write a sequel to ``The Graduate,'' which became a hit
movie that propelled Dustin Hoffman to stardom.
   ``If we get our act together and get this sequel off the ground,
it will be set in the Bethel-Danbury area,'' he said. ``What has
happened to us here will have to be immortalized.''
</TEXT>
