<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 1025EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Polio     09-20 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Polio,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Launches Vaccination Campaign After Polio Outbreak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel launched a vaccination campaign today
after the polio virus found in sewage infected at least eight
people with the disease, the Health Ministry announced.
   Six cases of polio were confirmed in the town of Hadera, 28
miles north of Tel Aviv, health officials said. The victims include
a 26-year-old teacher and a 3-month-old boy from the Or Akiva
kibbutz and a teen-age boy from the Ein Shemer collective farm.
   Two other cases were confirmed in the coastal towns of Akko,
about 60 miles north of Tel Aviv, and Ashkelon, about 35 miles
south.
   A Health Ministry statement said about 120,000 people would be
vaccinated in the Hadera area, starting with infants and
pre-schoolers.
   The outbreak caught Israel by surprise. The European division of
the World Health Organization, to which Israel belongs, earlier
this month considered declaring polio wiped out in the country.
   No polio cases were reported in Israel last year and only a
single case was reported in 1986.
   Dr. Avraham Morag of Hadassah Hospital, head of the Health
Ministry's advisory committee on contagious diseases, said that
besides the eight confirmed cases, two more possible cases were
under observation.
   He said health officials also were studying whether to expand
the immunization campaign to other areas.
   Morag said the outbreak was caused by overflowing sewage and the
fact that some people were not vaccinated against polio. He said
``massive amounts'' of the virus were detected in sewage in Or
Akiva and the nearby Arab village of Umm El-Fahm, both in the
Hadera area.
   There have been no polio cases among Arab villagers but they
have been included in the new immunization campaign, Morag said.
   Morag said 95 percent of the Israeli population already has been
immunized against polio.
</TEXT>
