<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Dressed-DownProsecutor     09-20 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dressed-Down Prosecutor,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Involved in Dress Controversy Fired</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor who was once told her
short skirts and designer blouses made her look like a ``bimbo''
has been fired for what her boss called professional shortcomings.
   Brenda Taylor lost her $22,000 job as a Broward County assistant
state attorney because of her handling of several drunken driving
cases, her absence or tardiness from court and her failure to
comply with paperwork, her supervisor said Monday.
   ``This is garbage,'' said Ms. Taylor, 25. ``It just shows to
what lengths they will go to get someone.''
   Ms. Taylor contended she was fired because of the complaint she
filed last month with the Broward County Human Relations Commission
against Assistant State Attorney John Countryman, one of her
supervisors.
   In it, she charged him with discriminating against her for the
clothes she wore _ designer styles rather than conservative,
blue-gray suits.
   Countryman's problems with Ms. Taylor were spelled out in five
memos.
   ``I told her that her appearance in court in a short skirt
created the impression that she was a bimbo interested only in
meeting men,'' Countryman, 38, wrote in one memo. ``I stressed that
she was not, but that, to outsiders, appearance was reality.''
   On Aug. 5, supervisors warned Ms. Taylor that her job
performance during a six-month probationary period was
unsatisfactory, and her probation was being extended a month.
   ``Since Aug. 5, nothing of a positive nature has occurred which
would change the opinion of the administrators,'' Ralph Ray, the
office's chief assistant, said in the termination notice.
   Harris Lowenthal, a former assistant state attorney helping to
defend Ms. Taylor, called the job performance criticisms absurd. He
said he doubts any prosecutor has been fired for the same reasons.
   ``I knew it would probably have an effect on my career, but I'm
a good lawyer and I know that my career as a lawyer will go on,''
Ms. Taylor said.
</TEXT>
