<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Attack, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0541,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shots Fired On Finance Ministry Official's Car</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with official saying two masked
men seen fleeing and to CORRECT that Hamburg incident occurred
Monday night sted Tuesday. Edits to tighten. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police were seeking two masked men
believed to be leftist extremists after shots were fired at a
Finance Ministry official near his home today, striking the man's
car but missing him.
   The attack on Hans Tietmeyer, state secretary for the Finance
Ministry, appeared to be an attempt to disrupt preparations for
this month's meeting of the World Bank and the International
Monetary Fund, Finance Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg said. Leftists
say industrial nations are not doing enough to help poor countries.
   Police said Tietmeyer was driving to work in the Bonn suburb of
Bad Godesberg when his car was struck by gunfire. Stoltenberg said
the attack occurred about 150 feet from Tietmeyer's house. He said
three shots were fired at the Mercedes.
   ``A shot hit the car, but Tietmeyer was uninjured,'' Bonn police
spokesman Helmut Engelke said.
   Two masked men were seen running from a nearby wooded area,
according to Hans-Juergen Forster, spokesman for the Federal
Prosecutor's office in Karlsruhe.
   Another police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said a shotgun apparently was used in the attack. Police did not
know whether more than one weapon was used.
   Tietmeyer's driver, who was not identified, also escaped injury,
police said.
   They said they were looking for the two men.
   ``This terrible incident appears to be connected with the
upcoming World Bank-International Monetary Fund meeting,''
Stoltenberg told reporters.
   The finance minister said the 57-year-old Tietmeyer had been
involved in planning for the annual World Bank-IMF meeting in West
Berlin Sept 27-29. Tietmeyer is an expert on international finance
and has accompanied Chancellor Helmut Kohl at world economic
meetings.
   On Monday, about 30 masked youths stormed a podium during
international finance talks in Hamburg and beat up West Germany's
IMF executive director, Guenther Grosche, Social Democratic
parliamentarian Ingomar Hauchler and a police officer. The attack
came during a discussion of the IMF.
   As many as 40,000 protesters are expected to be in West Berlin
during the international finance talks to demand that more be done
to help poor nations that are burdened with huge foreign debts.
   West German security officials have warned in recent weeks that
leftist militants among the protesters could cause trouble during
the West Berlin talks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
