<DOCNO> AP880920-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 1045EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Patients-AIDS     09-20 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Patients-AIDS,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>County Board OKs AIDS Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cook County Board has voted to adopt a policy
allowing county hospital patients to refuse to be treated by people
with the AIDS virus, but the hospital has not developed a way to
make the policy work.
   The county board, which also serves as the hospital board of
directors, voted 15-2 Monday to adopt the policy that would make
the hospital the first in the nation to give patients that right,
officials said.
   ``Our reaction is one of dismay,'' Dr. Lonnie Bristow, a trustee
of the American Medical Association, said last week, after the
board's Health and Hospital Committee approved the policy.
   ``There has been no case in this country of a patient
contracting the AIDS virus from a health-care worker,'' Bristow
said.
   No effective date was announced for the policy, which the
hospital must still determine how to put into practice.
   The policy covers hospital workers who ``routinely provide
direct patient care,'' including doctors and nurses.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome destroys the body's defenses
against disease, leaving a person prey to life-threatening
infections and certain cancers. AIDS has struck more than 72,000
people in this country since 1979 and killed more than 40,000 of
them, according to the national Centers for Disease Control in
Atlanta.
   The virus that causes the incurable and fatal disease is
believed to be spread through sexual intercourse, shared hypodermic
needles and from infected mothers to their infants before or during
birth.
</TEXT>
