<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon 3rdLd-Writethru a0489 09-20 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0489,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Killed, 25 Wounded in Car Bomb Blast in Christian East
Beirut</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: NEW throughout with details of injuries, political situation
in Lebanon. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb exploded today in Christian
east Beirut, killing three people and wounding 25, destroying
dozens of cars and touching off a fire, police and news reports
said.
   Among those wounded was former Information Minister Joseph Skaff
and three of his bodyguards. They were driving through the Dora
district at the time of the 9 a.m. blast, officials said.
   A police spokesman, insisting on anonymity, said Skaff, a
Christian paliamentarian, suffered cuts and burns but that neither
he nor his companions were seriously injured.
   The other casualties were pedestrians, motorists or shopkeepers.
   Voice of Lebanon, the main radio station in east Beirut run by
the Christian Phalange Party, said the bomb-laden automobile was
parked near the Mercedes-Benz car dealership by a young man who
escaped before it blew up.
   The radio station interrupted regular programming to report the
explosion during the morning rush hour. It said 43 cars parked in
the street were destroyed, most of them by a ``huge fire'' that
burned many of the autos before being extinguished an hour later.
   The blast, so powerful it was heard across the Lebanese capital,
was the 13th car bombing in Lebanon this year. By police count, 104
people have been killed and 378 wounded in previous attacks.
   Today's explosion took place an hour before Christian
parliamentary deputies were scheduled to meet in Bkirki north of
Beirut to name a presidential candidate after vetoing a
Syrian-American agreement to nominate deputy Mikhail Daher.
   Skaff, a 50-year-old Greek Catholic, was en route to Bkirki at
the time.
   Daher, a pro-Syrian Maronite Christian, did not attend the
meeting at the seat of the Maronites' patriarch, Nasrallah Sfeir.
   A spokesman for Sfeir said he expected the Christians to name
Raymond Edde as their candidate. Edde, 75, has been living in
self-imposed exile in France since 1976, when he fled Lebanon after
surviving three attempts on his life.
   The conferees met for four hours but postponed a decision until
Wednesday, when another session was scheduled.
   Under the Lebanese constitution, presidential elections must
take place before President Amin Gemayel's six-year term ends Sept.
23.
</TEXT>
