<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Chicago Mayoral,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alderman Enters Chicago Mayoral Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alderman Lawrence Bloom, a longtime independent
who represents the Hyde Park ward that includes the University of
Chicago, has announced his candidacy for mayor.
   Bloom, a three-term alderman who was a close ally of the late
Mayor Harold Washington, said Monday he would bring together a city
left floundering by Washington's death last November.
   ``In the Bloom administration, there will be no forgotten
neighborhoods,'' said the alderman, who had Washington's backing in
an unsuccessful bid in the 1984 Democratic primary to unseat Cook
County State's Attorney Richard M. Daley.
   The election is set for 1989, with a primary in February, but
could be put off until 1991, depending on the outcome of a state
Supreme Court case.
   The only other announced candidate is Alderman Danny Davis, but
expected to join the race are Mayor Eugene Sawyer, Alderman Timothy
Evans and Alderman Edward Burke. Evans, Davis and Bloom often vote
together in City Council, while Burke and Sawyer _ elected by the
council after Washington's death _ are allied on many issues.
</TEXT>
