<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 1122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EPA-Smog     09-20 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-EPA-Smog,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Order To Clean Up Air Could Mean Lifestyle Changes,
Officials Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court order that takes the first step
toward cleaning up Southern California's polluted air could lead to
stronger auto emission controls and a reduction in the number of
freeway commuters, officials said.
   U.S. District Judge Harry Hupp on Monday ordered the
Environmental Protection Agency to draft a plan to reduce pollution
in the South Coast Air Basin, which includes Los Angeles, Orange,
Riverside and San Bernardino counties.
   Hupp's order was expected after the EPA acknowledged in July
that it is required by federal law to take over smog control
enforcement in the basin after the local air quality management
district missed a deadline for meeting ozone and carbon monoxide
health standards. The order doesn't set a deadline for EPA's plan.
   EPA officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, told the Los
Angeles Times they hope Congress will extend compliance deadlines
before the EPA is forced to impose stringent restrictions on the
area.
   EPA Administrator Lee M. Thomas said the agency is legally
required to draft a plan that would reduce smog by 1993.
   That five-year deadline would require curtailing rush-hour
traffic.
   ``I think 20 years is by far the more realistic time frame, and
even with that, it will require tremendous change on everybody's
part, and even new technology to accomplish it,'' Thomas said.
   But he said, ``the law won't let me go beyond five years.''
   Mark Abramowitz, a spokesman for the Coalition for Clean Air,
said the organization, along with the Sierra Club, believes that a
five-year deadline would force such strict control measures that
the public would oppose it. He said the environmental groups hoped
for a 12- to 15-year plan.
   The basin has some of the worst air in the country despite auto
emissions standards and controls over industrial polluters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
