<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoyScouts-Hunger     09-20 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boy Scouts-Hunger,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scouts Will Go Door-To-Door Nationwide To Get Food</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boy Scouts of America is putting its members
to work in the fight against hunger, hoping they will collect 100
million cans of food for the needy in a door-to-door campaign this
fall.
   ``Hunger is a problem we can do something about by working
together,'' Ben H. Love, chief executive of the Scouts, said Monday
at a Chicago news conference.
   The ``Scouting for Food'' program calls for Cub Scouts, Boy
Scouts and Explorers to go to homes in the next two months and drop
off bags. A few weeks later, the bags will be collected and the
cans of food distributed to various relief agencies.
   The United Way and the National Guard will be aiding the effort.
Many others, like food chains, civic and religious groups, fire
departments and various local agencies, also are cooperating.
   ``It is an example of scouting's long-standing commitment to
community service,'' Love said.
   Frank J. Morgan, president and chief operating officer of
Chicago-based Quaker Oats Co., is the volunteer chairman of the
food drive.
   Dr. J. Larry Brown, head of a hunger task force at Harvard
University, said much of the hunger problem in the United States
often goes unnoticed.
   ``It's not like the Third World where we can look at swollen
bellies,'' Brown said.
   The scouts hope to collect the food by Nov. 19 and announce
results of the drive on Dec. 16.
</TEXT>
