<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Congressman-Vandalism     09-20 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congressman-Vandalism,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Congressman's Home Target Of Vandals</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Language in 7th graf, ``My son ...,' may be offensive to
readers.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RON HARRIST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vandals carved racial slurs on doors and
splashed paint on an entry-way floor at the home of Mississippi's
first black congressman since Reconstruction, who is running for a
second term this fall.
   An upset Mike Espy took time off from his 2nd District campaign
today to repair the damage to his home in this town a few miles
north of Jackson.
   ``Sure, it makes you angry,'' he said. ``We've come a long way
in Mississippi, but cases like this remind you how far we've got to
go.''
   Espy, a Democrat who faces Republican Jack Coleman in November,
said his major concern was for his family.
   ``I'm the congressman. I have the record and I have my
performance to defend and I can defend it,'' Espy said. ``I'm the
congressman, not my wife, my brother or my children.''
   Espy said his wife discovered the vandalism when she returned
home with her children late Monday.
   ``My son is 5 and my daughter is 8 and I had to explain to them
the history of race relations in Mississippi,'' he said. ``They had
carved the word `Nigger' on two doors and I had to tell my children
what that meant and why somebody would do that. It was not an easy
thing to do.
   ``If someone wants to come after me, let them come, but I want
them to leave my family alone.''
   The congressman said the racial slurs were carved on doors in
the covered entry-way leading into the house and a garage area. He
said the letters were cut into the doors near the top, along with
``U.S. Con'' _ apparently referring to congressman.
   He said plants in the entry-way had been uprooted and paint
dashed on the floor and on some of the plants.
   Espy said both doors were locked when his family arrived, and
there apparently had been no attempt get inside. He said police
were called and were investigating.
   Madison Police Chief Jimmy Dukes said his officers had filed a
report on the vandalism and an investigation was under way.
   Ed Cole, chairman of the state Democratic Party, called for a
full investigation of the incident.
   ``I hope this campaign does not degenerate into that level of
activity,'' he said. ``I think Mississippi has gone a long way in
erasing a negative image it has had outside the state.
   ``Mike Espy has been a good congressman for this state and he
has done a whole lot to improve Mississippi's image,'' he said. ``I
hope we are not going to allow a few narrow-minded people to take
us back to a period we have gone through.''
   Espy said he had received threatening calls in the past, ``but
you always expect those. There has not been an increase in those
calls, and this is the first time something like this has
happened.''
   ``I think most Mississippians would be upset to hear something
like this has happened,'' he added, ``but we all realize there are
still some ignorant people running around. We also realize that in
public life, we are prone to attack.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
