<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Democrats-Oil 1stLd-Writethru a0437 09-20 0846</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Democrats-Oil, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0437,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precedes HOUSTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bentsen Calls White House Energy Policy ``Dry Hole''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 7 grafs with Bentsen today, picking up in 3rd
graf pvs, The energy</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONGVIEW, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential nominee
Lloyd Bentsen, campaigning in East Texas oil country, said today
that on energy policy the Reagan administration ``has drilled a
real dry hole.''
   Bentsen reiterated presidential nominee Michael Dukakis' promise
to take government action to revive the petroleum industry. One day
earlier, in Houston, Dukakis outlined his energy program before an
audience of oil producers, saying he would support government
intervention if necessary to keep domestic wells in operation.
   Today in Longview, Bentsen told reporters, ``Five out of six
rigs that were active in 1981 are idle today. Two out of every five
jobs in the oil industry have been lost.''
   Standing in front of a rig hauled to the airport for the event,
with a huge American flag as a backdrop, Bentsen pointed to the
equipment as ``a sign of what's happened to Texas.''
   ``That piece of equipment shouldn't be here at the airport, it
should be out there working in the field,'' he said.
   ``George Bush will tell you he's an oilman, but when it comes to
an energy policy this administration has drilled a dry hole. It's a
real duster,'' he said.
   A day earlier, Dukakis said he would name Bentsen to head a
bipartisan energy summit as soon after the election as possible,
Dukakis said: ``With each passing month, we are becoming more
vulnerable to another oil embargo. At the rate we're going, by
1995, the United States will be 60 percent dependent on foreign
oil.''
   The energy summit is the second panel or commission to which
Dukakis has said he would appoint the Texas senator if the
Democratic ticket is elected. Dukakis has also said Bentsen would
head a council on the space program, which like oil has a definite
interest for Texas voters.
   The polls in Texas show the Democratic ticket trailing slightly
in the race for the state's 29 electoral votes.
   Dukakis, in a message Bentsen was to carry around the state
today, slammed Republican George Bush for doing nothing for the oil
industry as vice president. He said Bush's failure to appear at the
People for an Energy Policy forum, to which both tickets were
invited, was indicative.
   ``A former Texas oilman, and yet he doesn't have time to engage
in a discussion of energy,'' Dukakis said of Bush, accusing him in
his adopted home state of ignoring the important issues of the
campaign.
   ``My friends, we don't need any more speeches about the flag,''
he said. ``We need a president and vice president who are concerned
about America's energy future, and yours.''
   Dukakis said that at the same time energy demand has increased,
the domestic industry's production has gone down since President
Reagan took office. ``The last eight years in the energy industry
have been a roller coaster ride with the bottom knocked out.''
   Dukakis promised to remove barriers that have been blocking
increased use of natural gas in the country, to increase the
filling of the government's strategic oil reserve, and to boost
research on making oil fields more productive.
   He also promised to ``make Houston the EOR (enhanced oil
recovery) capital of the world,'' referring to techniques for
extracting more oil from a seemingly depleted well, and said his
program would help the oil industry more directly if necessary to
keep wells from shutting down.
   ``And when the market alone won't provide the incentive to
drill, a government led by Mike Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen will,''
he said.
   Bentsen has made a career in Congress fighting on the side of
the oil industry. Dukakis said the Texas senator would be chairman
of ``a bipartisan energy summit just as soon after the election as
possible.''
   The group would ``design a comprehensive energy policy'' to make
sure producers and consumers had fair prices, he said. Dukakis'
speech made no mention of alternative energy sources such as
nuclear power or ethanol.
   ``Unlike either George Bush or Dan Quayle, Lloyd Bentsen has
been a leader in Congress,'' Dukakis said of his running mate, who
was seated nearby. The Massachusetts governor listed Bentsen's
accomplishments _ and Quayle's votes against the oil industry.
   ``Those votes say a lot about Mr. Quayle,'' he said. ``And they
say a lot about the man who selected him.''
   Bentsen, who introduced Dukakis to the gathering of several
hundred oil industry people from Texas and neighboring states, said
the Reagan administration had ``sentenced the Southwest to a deep
and painful recession.''
   ``I know a lot of my friends in the energy business tend to vote
Republican,'' he said. ``But I want to ask them: What has this
administration done to help your industry through the toughest
period in history?''
   Dukakis, he said, was the first of the Democrats to support
repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil and was not, as
Republicans claimed, opposed to all offshore drilling.
</TEXT>
