<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSSuit     09-20 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Suit,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctor With AIDS Sues Hospital, Doctors, City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A doctor who claims she contracted the AIDS
virus after being accidentally pricked by a discarded needle in a
hospital patient's bedding is suing the hospital, the city and two
other doctors for $175 million.
   In papers filed Friday in trial-level state Supreme Court,
Veronica Prego, 30, claims she was infected in January 1983 at
Kings County Hospital in Brooklyn. The syringe needle had been used
to draw blood from an AIDS patient, she said.
   At the time, Prego, a native of Argentina and a graduate of a
medical school there, was working as an unsalaried aide to a
hospital intern, Dr. Joyce Fogel, who is one of the defendants.
   Prego alleges that Fogel, who was treating the AIDS patient,
``negligently and improperly'' put three discarded needles on the
patient's bedding _ one of which stuck Prego as she was cleaning up.
   She charges that Fogel, and later hospital officials, assured
her they didn't know of any cases ``where a health care worker
contracted AIDS by means of a needle stick.'' Such contamination
recently has been shown to be possible.
   Prego also claims that the city's Health and Hospitals Corp. did
not supply any puncture-resistant disposal units for the
contaminated syringes and needles.
   The suit also names Sheldon Landsman, a doctor who had conducted
a state-sponsored survey of health and hospital employees working
with patients suffering from acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
She said Landsman violated her right to confidentiality by
informing hospital administrators about her condition.
   Janice Kabel, a lawyer representing the city, the HHC and Fogel,
said her clients have denied all substantive charges. She declined
to comment further.
   The state attorney general's office, which is representing
Landsman, also declined to comment.
</TEXT>
