<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Bennett     09-20 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bennett,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On Last Day in Office, Bennett Endorses Local School Control</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA ENGLERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHUA, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On his last day in office, Education
Secretary William Bennett today praised the tradition of strong
local control in New Hampshire schools and downplayed the
importance of kindergarten for youngsters.
   ``It would be a shame for New Hampshire to veer toward state
control of education when we are telling other states to emulate
New Hampshire,'' Bennett said at a news conference.
   He cited just-released national statistics on Scholastic
Aptitude Tests as evidence that local control works. Average scores
for New Hampshire students were tops nationally among the 22 states
in which 40 percent or more of the students took the tests, which
are widely used in college admissions.
   Bennett, who appeared at the news conference with Republican
gubernatorial candidate Judd Gregg, was asked to comment on New
Hampshire's status as the only state not to require kindergarten
and Gregg's opposition to state-mandated kindergarten.
   Bennett did not answer directly, but said, ``There is no
research that conclusively proves that kindergarten gives kids a
jump.
   ``Yes, kindergarten is desireable,'' he said, ``but a good
first, second and third grade is more important than a good
kindergarten.''
   He added: ``No one suggests that New Hampshire's education
system is perfect. The general decline in education seen in the
United States is seen in New Hampshire, but New Hampshire, more
than many other states, is on the right track'' trying to reverse
the trend.
   Bennett went from Nashua to Hollis, where he was to briefly
teach reading and speak to an assembly at the Hollis Elementary
School, one of 287 winners nationwide in the Education Department's
school recognition program.
   He was also scheduled to go to Boston today for his last
official appearance as education secretary. Afterward, he planned
to go hiking in New Hampshire's White Mountains.
</TEXT>
