<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Cavazos     09-20 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cavazos,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Confirms Texan As Education Secretary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted 94-0 today to confirm Lauro
Cavazos as education secretary after members called the son of a
Texas cattleman an ``authentic American success story'' who is
committed to federal education programs.
   Cavazos, who was scheduled to be sworn in later this afternoon
at the White House, will be the first Hispanic member of a
president's Cabinet.
   ``He is an authentic American success story and an inspiration
to millions of young students,'' said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy,
D-Mass.
   Other Democrats and Republicans praised the Texas Tech
University president's credentials and commitment to federal
education programs.
   ``Dr. Cavazos has a strong commitment to ensuring excellent
educational opportunities are available to all Americans,'' said
Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, calling him ``living proof of the
American dream.''
   ``The Labor Committee held a confirmation hearing for Dr.
Cavazos and all of us were impressed with his commitment to federal
education programs,'' said Kennedy, chairman of the panel.
   ``For the last seven years, members of Congress from both sides
of the aisle have worked hard to ensure that the federal goverment
will continue to have a role in education. It is apparent that Dr.
Cavazos will be an ally in these efforts in the future,'' Kennedy
said.
   Cavazos, 61, is taking a leave of absence as president of the
medical school at Texas Tech. He is not a medical doctor, but has a
doctorate in physiology from Iowa State University.
   Cavazos was born on the fabled King Ranch of South Texas and
worked his way through undergraduate and graduate school after
serving in the Army.
   Prior to his appointment at Texas Tech in 1980, he was dean of
the Tufts Medical School in Boston.
   Cavazos is replacing outgoing Education Secretary William J.
Bennett.
</TEXT>
