<1ST_LINE>u i PM-WesternSahara     09-20 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Western Sahara,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Independence Referendum For Western Sahara Annnounced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Security Council unanimously voted
today to approve an independence referendum for Western Sahara,
where Marxist guerrillas haven been battling Morocco's occupation
forces for 13 years.
   The 15-0 Security Council vote approved the appointment of a
special representative of the secretary-general to monitor a
referendum that would result in Western Sahara's independence or
affiliation with Morocco.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar reminded the members
of the council that on Aug. 30, representatives of the Polisario
independence movement and Morocco met with him in Geneva to approve
the referendum and peace plan, with certain reservations.
   ``The proposals aimed at the restoration of peace in the region
provide a framework for the conclusion of a cease-fire and the
establishment of conditions necessary for the organization of a
credible referendum,'' said the U.N. chief.
   ``The referendum will be organized and monitored by the United
Nations in cooperation with the Organization of African Unity,'' he
said. The organization has played a major role in arranging the
dialogue between Polisario and Morocco.
   Perez de Cuellar said a special representative from his office,
a civilian unit, a military unit and a security unit would work for
peace in the area.
   ``The proposals also provide that the Kingdom of Morocco will
carry out an appropriate, substantial and gradual reduction of its
troops in the Western Sahra,'' with remaining soldiers to be
barracked under the supervision of U.N. military observers.
   Polisario's fighters would also be quartered under U.N.
supervision.
   The Marxist-led Polisario movement of about 8,000 fighters has
been battling for the independence of Western Sahara since Spain's
colonial administration withdrew in 1975-76, and Moroccan
occupation troops took over the phosphate-rich desert territory in
northwest Africa.
   More than 10,000 people have died in the nearly 13-year-old
guerrilla war, which has cost Morocco up to $2 million a day to
fight.
   Western Sahara covers about 110,000 square miles. Its population
was set at 76,000 in 1974, during the last Spanish colonial census.
   Under the U.N. plan, only people born in the territory may vote
in the referendum.
   Determining who is eligible will be a major chore for the
referendum monitors. Polisario claims about 165,000 eligible
Western Saharans live in its refugee camps near Tindouf in Algeria,
which funds and shelters Polisario, but Morocco says they are not
eligible.
   Morocco claims that 90 percent of the 150,000 residents of
Moroccan-occupied sections of Western Sahara are eligible, but
Polisario says two-thirds of them are Moroccan immigrants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
