<1ST_LINE>r a AM-APAppointments     09-20 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Appointments,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AP Names Nairobi Bureau Chief, Newark Assistant Bureau Chief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reid G. Miller, roving correspondent for The
Associated Press in Central America, has been named chief of bureau
in Nairobi, Kenya, succeeding Jerry Gray, named assistant chief of
bureau in Newark, N.J.
   The appointments were announced Tuesday by Louis D. Boccardi,
president of the AP.
   Miller, 54, is a native of Medford, Mass., who graduated from
Arizona State University and joined the AP in Phoenix in 1956. He
was news editor in Salt Lake City and Miami, correspondent in
Pittsburgh, chief of bureau in Salt Lake City and Miami, and
assistant chief of bureau in Washington.
   He was named to the roving correspondent post in 1984. In May of
that year he was wounded in a bomb explosion at the jungle
headquarters of Nicaraguan rebel leader Eden Pastora. Four
reporters were killed and 20 people injured.
   Gray, 38, a native of Greenwood, Miss., graduated from Memphis
State University in Tennessee and worked for the Memphis
Commercial-Appeal before joining the AP in Memphis in 1975. He
transferred to the World Services Department in New York in 1983,
was named correspondent in Nairobi in 1985, and bureau chief there
in 1986.
</TEXT>
