<2ND_LINE>PM-Colombia-Consul Shot,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Venezuelan Diplomat Wounded</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEDELLIN, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two gunmen firing from a taxi wounded
a Venezuelan diplomat as he drove to work today in Medellin, Mayor
Juan Gomez Martinez said.
   The Venezuelan consul for Medellin, Luis Alberto Altubel Lopez,
was slightly wounded by a bullet that hit him in a lip, Gomez said.
   The gunmen pulled up next to the consul's car as it was stopped
in traffic, leaned out the taxi's windows and opened fired, the
mayor said.
   Altubel was on his way to the consulate when he was shot, the
mayor said in a broadcast interview with the Colombian radio chain
Caracol.
   After the attack, Altubel managed to drive to the consulate,
Gomez told radio Caracol. The taxi used by the gunmen was found
abandoned a few blocks from the scene of the shooting.
   The motive for the attack was not known.
   Right-wing death squads have killed more than 50 people in
Medellin in the last two years, and left-wing guerrillas have been
active in the area for a decade.
   Medellin also is the headquarters for Colombia's biggest cocaine
traffickers. A war between Medellin's cocaine traffickers and those
in another Colombian city, Cali, has claimed more than 80 lives
this year.
</TEXT>
