<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-PeaceTalks     09-20 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Peace Talks,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Ready To Meet Leaders Of All Namibian Factions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations chief has
invited leaders of all political parties in South-West Africa to
meet him when he comes to discuss independence for the territory,
an official said Tuesday.
   Louis Pienaar, South Africa's senior representative in the
territory commonly known as Namibia, said the U.N. leader had set
aside more than two hours Thursday for these consultations during a
visit to South Africa.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar was to arrive at
a Pretoria air force base late Wednesday on his first visit to
South Africa since 1983.
   He is scheduled to meet Friday with President P.W. Botha to
discuss the U.N.'s plan for Namibian independence.
   Pienaar said Namibian political leaders had until Wednesday
morning to say whether they wished to see Perez de Cuellar. There
was no immediate response from the South-West African People's
Organization, which has waged a pro-independence insurgency since
1966.
   South Africa governs Namibia in violation of U.N. resolutions
calling for its independence. It has agreed to end its 73-year rule
and allow U.N. observers to oversee the transition to independence,
but only if Cuban troops withdraw from neighboring Angola.
   U.S.-mediated talks involving Angola, Cuba and South Africa have
made progress toward a regional settlement, but there has been no
agreement on a timetable for withdrawal of the more than 50,000
Cuban troops. The talks are expected to resume next week in
Brazzaville, Congo.
   South Africa wants the Cubans out in one year, the span of time
that Resolution 435 specifies for Namibia's transition to
independence.
   Cuba and Angola have demanded a longer withdrawal period. South
Africa claims they are seeking a chance to crush the anti-Marxist
rebel movement UNITA now that South Africa troops supporting the
guerrillas have left Angola.
   Perez de Cuellar is scheduled to visit Angola on Saturday.
   His trip coincides with a flurry of reports of broader peace
intiatives.
   Zaire's pro-Western president, Mobutu Sese Seko, has been quoted
as saying he, Botha and Angolan leaders have agreed to participate
in talks aimed at achieving reconciliation in Angola. He did not
indicate whether UNITA would participate in such talks. Angola says
it will not negotiate with the rebels.
   On Tuesday, the Financial Times of London said there were
tentative plans for a meeting between Botha and President Kenneth
Kaunda of Zambia, one of Africa's most prominent statesmen.
Possible topics included Namibia, reconciliation in Angola, and the
recent improvement of relations between South Africa and
Mozambique, the Financial Times said.
   Botha visited Mozambique on Sept. 12 for talks with President
Joaquim Chissano, whose Marxist government has long accused South
Africa of backing anti-government guerrillas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
