<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 1311EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PsychologistFraud     09-20 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Psychologist Fraud,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Psychologist Pleads Guilty To Falsifying Research Data</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A psychologist who studied drug therapies for
hyperactive mentally retarded children has pleaded guilty in
federal court to falsifying research data in order to obtain
federal funds.
   Stephen E. Breuning, 36, pleaded guilty Monday to two counts of
making false statements to the National Institute of Mental Health
in Bethesda.
   As part of a plea agreement, prosecutors will recommend that
Breuning be barred from working as a research psychologist for 10
years and that he make $20,000 restitution to his former employer,
the University of Pittsburgh, which has repaid the federal
institute more than $163,000.
   They also agreed to drop a charge that Breuning obstructed the
institute's investigation of his data's authenticity.
   Breuning claimed to have done the research while working at a
psychiatric clinic affiliated with the university's medical school
from 1982 to 1984. But while he claimed that 99 patients
participated in the studies, only 25 students received the drugs,
according to E. Thomas Roberts, an assistant U.S. attorney.
   U.S. District Judge Frank A. Kaufman set sentencing for Nov. 10.
The maximum possible sentence is 10 years in prison and $20,000 in
fines. Breuning remains free on bond.
   According to the mental health institute, Breuning had a
significant impact in the field of drug therapies for hyperactive
retarded children, finding that stimulants such as Ritalin and
Dexedrine helped control such children with fewer adverse side
effects than the tranquilizers previously used.
   Breuning was employed at the Polk Center in Polk, Pa., a
state-run residential center for the mentally retarded when he was
indicted April 9. He no longer works in his field and has been
living in Michigan, said his attorney, Charles S. Lazar.
</TEXT>
