<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 1318EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mongolia-US     09-20 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mongolia-US,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Ambassador To Mongolia Presents Credentials _ Then Leaves</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States' first ambassador to the
Mongolian People's Republic flew in this month, presented his
credentials and hopped a train back out, heading for his office in
Washington.
   ``It's a beautiful country,'' Ambassador Richard Williams told a
news conference Tuesday in Beijing, where he stopped en route.
   It also could become a useful post for tracking developments
inside Mongolia's huge socialist neighbors, China and the Soviet
Union, as they move slowly to heal their rift of more than two
decades.
   But he has no plans to move there. When the United States
established relations with Mongolia in 1987, the State Department
decided the remote, frigid country was too harsh a post for
permanent residence.
   Instead, Williams will be the only American ambassador working
out of a State Department office. He will continue holding his
previous post, as head of the department's China affairs office,
and make periodic trips to Mongolia.
   Two junior U.S. diplomats have been stationed in the capital of
Ulan Bator for six months, working out of an apartment building,
but they will leave for the winter, Williams said.
   During his 10-day visit to Ulan Bator, Williams said he
discussed with the Mongolians possibilities for finding permanent
facilities for an embassy and staff. But he said the prospect of
living there himself ``would take some thinking about.''
   ``The winters go down to 40 to 50 below zero,'' he said. ``It's
a little daunting.''
   Mongolia has been closely allied to the Soviet Union since
declaring its independence from China in 1921. Mongolia has ties
with 100 countries, but only 18 maintain embassies in Ulan Bator,
most of them East bloc nations.
   Many have supplies sent in from relatively luxurious Beijing to
supplement the Mongolian diet of mutton and sour milk.
   Williams said his main concerns are to aid Americans who travel
in Mongolia and develop U.S.-Mongolian trade, which averages $3
million annually, mostly in cashmere and camel's hair exports to
the United States.
   But he acknowledged the new relationship ``can provide us with
an interesting additional view of the state of Mongolian-Soviet,
Mongolian-Chinese and Sino-Soviet relations.''
   The Soviet Union stations nearly 50,000 troops in Mongolia,
Williams said, and their presence is one of several key problems
blocking normalization of Chinese-Soviet relations. The Soviets
pulled an estimated 12,000 soldiers out in 1987, but have not
scheduled further withdrawals.
   Mongolia took the Soviet side in the bitter Soviet-Chinese split
of the early 1960s, but recently has followed Moscow's lead and
improved ties with China. A Mongolian parliamentary delegation
visited Beijing this month for the first time.
   Williams said the United States considered establishing ties
with Mongolia in the 1960s but did not want to offend the
Nationalist Chinese government on Taiwan, which claims Mongolia as
part of China. The United States broke ties with the Nationalists
in 1979 and recognized the government in Beijing.
   U.S. and Mongolian diplomats discussed establishing ties in the
1970s, but Mongolia broke off the talks unexpectedly and new
efforts began only in 1986, Williams said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
