<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Somalia-HumanRights     09-20 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Somalia-Human Rights,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amnesty: Hundreds of Unarmed Civilians Executed in Somalia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Embargoed until 9 p.m. EDT _ time set by source.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces in Somalia have executed hundreds
of unarmed civilians during anti-rebel operations this summer, and
political prisoners are systematically tortured, a human rights
group said in a report Wednesday.
   The Amnesty International report says human rights have been
``persistently violated'' during President Mohamed Siad Barre's 19
years in power and that violations have intensified recently in
countering rebel groups.
   ``Between several hundred and as many as 1,000 people have been
summarily executed'' by government forces in northern regions since
heavy fighting began in May, said Martin Hill, a spokesman for the
international organization.
   The killings, sometimes during house-to-house searches for
Ethiopian-backed rebels, appeared aimed at terrorizing civilian
sympathizers, he said.
   An estimated 200 prisoners also have been executed after summary
trials in the last three years, he said.
   The London-based organization said it had compiled evidence of
``a consistent pattern'' of torture, arbitrary arrests and unfair
trials of suspected government opponents.
   Torture victims said they were subjected to electric shocks and
sexual assault, wounded with knives, suspended upside  conducted house-to-house
searches and
``arbitrarily killed many people,'' it said.
   Foreign relief agency workers reported 21 people were dragged
from their homes and shot to death in separate incidents on May 31
and June 1, it said.
   ``These were all deliberate extrajudicial executions of alleged
political opponents as distinct from the indiscriminate heavy
casualties caused by the battle in the town or subsequent
bombardment by the government forces,'' the report said.
   Hill said the 600,000 people of Hargeisa ``by and large were
fleeing and the town is now virtually empty.''
   ``There seem to be deliberate attacks on civilians (in urban
areas), but the security forces aren't sufficiently organized to
sweep through the countryside,'' he said.
   Hill said a British reporter accompanying government troops
during anti-rebel offensives this summer estimated that between
30,000 and 50,000 people have been killed in mainly aerial
bombardments.
   The report said many prisoners held solely for the non-violent
expression of their beliefs have been kept for years in deplorable
conditions, often incommunicado and without proper medical aid.
   Yusuf Osman Samantar, a lawyer and former member of Parliament,
has been in prison without charge for nearly 19 years, while Safia
Hashi Madar, an employee of a U.S. relief agency and a former
science lecturer, was jailed for life in 1986 for ``membership of a
subversive organization,'' the report said.
   Others include parliamentarians, doctors, clerics, businessmen,
students and refugees, it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
