<DOCNO> AP880920-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 1323EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-YomKippur     09-20 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Yom Kippur,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Tight As Israelis Fast On Yom Kippur</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Large contingents of police were deployed in
mixed Jewish-Arab areas Tuesday as Israelis started the 25-hour
fast of Yom Kippur, the day of atonement and the most sacred
holiday on the Jewish calendar.
   Traffic on the nation's highways came to a halt, commercial
flights were suspended and the border with Egypt and bridges to
Jordan were closed.
   State-run Israel radio and television and Israel army radio
stopped transmitting, the only day of the year they do so.
   Yom Kippur came during a period of unprecedented conflict
between Israel and the 1.5 million Palestinians in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Over the past nine months, more than 265 Palestinians and six
Israelis have been killed in what has come to be known as the
intefadeh, Arabic for uprising. To prevent violence, police stepped
up security in Jerusalem's mixed neighborhoods and other
Jewish-Arab areas of the country.
   The army announced that as a security precaution Palestinians
from the occupied territories would be barred from entering Israel
between 2 p.m. Tuesday and 8 p.m. Wednesday.
   Yom Kippur ends the ``Ten Terrible Days'' during which,
according to Jewish faith, God decides who will live through the
coming year and who will die.
   During this period from the onset of the Jewish New Year until
Yom Kippur, Jews bless each other with the greeting ``Gmar Hatima
Tova _ May you be inscribed in the book of life.''
   Before sundown, religious Jews shed leather shoes and belts and
don white robes to prepare for the Kol Nidre service, the special
prayer for forgiveness and life, which begins Yom Kippur.
   Early Tuesday, many Jews went to stores and markets to carry out
the ancient rite of kapparot. Waving the chickens over their head,
the penitents prayed that their sins would be transferred to the
sacrificial chickens. Afterwards, the chickens were slaughtered.
   Stores, commercial and government offices, and public
transportation shut down early to give workers time to prepare for
the fast.
   A survey by the Hadashot daily indicated that 69 percent of
Israeli Jews would fast even though the regularly observant portion
of the population is estimated at only about 20 percent.
   In a reflective article on Yom Kippur in the left-wing daily
``Davar,'' columnist Amnon Dankner wrote:
   ``For many free and wild souls, Yom Kippur is their last link
with Judaism, in which not only the religious intent is important.
It is more like taking part in a sporting event which measures
willpower, restraint, and even spirituality.''
   Tuesday also marked the 15th anniversary of the 1973 Middle East
war which began on Yom Kippur when Egyptian and Syrian armies
thrust through Israeli lines in the occupied Sinai Desert and Golan
Heights and briefly threatened to invade Israel itself.
   On the eve of Yom Kippur, bereaved families layed wreaths and
flowers at the gravesides of the 3,000 Israeli troops who died in
the 1973 Middle East war.
   Israeli newspapers printed reminiscences and commentaries about
the war.
   Davar's editor, Hanna Zemer, recalled that Egyptian President
Anwar Sadat had offered Israel a territorial settlement in 1971 and
drew parallels between those days and today.
   ``Before the Yom Kippur war, Israel did not agree to withdraw
from the Suez Canal. And that was not the only instance which
showed that Israel knows how to compromise...only after paying the
price for the stubborness which preceded it. We always come to the
right conclusions too late.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
