<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BRF--Dukakis-Tank     09-20 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Dukakis-Tank,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll Indicates Dukakis Lost Ground With Tank Ride</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis
lost ground among voters when he wore army gear and rode around in
a tank a week ago, according to a new poll.
   A national telephone survey of 1,002 registered voters last
Friday through Sunday found that 25 percent said they were less
likely to vote for Dukakis based on what they had seen or heard
about the tank ride.
   Seven percent said the ride made them more likely to vote for
Dukakis. More than 60 percent said that they had not seen or read
anything about it or that it had no impact on how they would vote.
   Dukakis donned a military helmet and jump suit last Tuesday and
took a spin in a 60-ton M-1 tank as part of an effort to counter
Republican portrayals of him as weak on defense.
   The poll, taken for the Boston Herald and WBZ-TV of Boston, had
a 3 percent margin of error.
</TEXT>
