<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RecycledPlane     09-20 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Recycled Plane,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flight Simulator Company Buys Cockpit from Damaged Aloha Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROKEN ARROW, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cockpit from the Aloha Airlines
Boeing 737 that lost part of its fuselage during a flight between
two Hawaiian islands will be turned into a training simulator, an
official of the company that bought it said.
   Paul Hancock, director of marketing for FlightSafety
International, said Monday that the company, which makes flight
simulators used to train pilots, was searching for a 737 cockpit
when it discovered that the salvaged Aloha aircraft was being sold.
   ``We recently launched a program to build a 737 simulator and in
order to do that, we have to duplicate the cockpit of the
aircraft,'' Hancock said. ``That can be done a number of ways, but,
if possible, we look for a salvage cockpit. We heard about this
cockpit and jumped on a plane to go see.''
   A section of the upper fuselage of the 19-year-old plane tore
away during an inter-island hop April 28, but the pilot managed to
bring the crippled plane to a safe landing on Maui. Officials said
it was miraculous that only one person was killed in the accident,
although 69 of the 95 passengers were injured.
   During the next two years, FlightSafety workers will remove
every piece from the cockpit and refurbish it. Using the aluminum
structure as a mold, workers will construct a fiberglass shell that
will eventually be the simulator.
</TEXT>
