<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 1345EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-HomelessReport Bjt   09-20 0726</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless Report, Bjt,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Homeless Panelists Wanted Stronger Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A report that termed homelessness a ``national
disgrace'' was watered down and should have contained even stronger
language and more specific recommendations, say members of the
group that worked on the study for the National Academy of Sciences.
   Bruce C. Vladeck, president of the United Hospital Fund of New
York and head of the 13-member committee that prepared the study,
said the academy refused to include a strong supplemental statement.
   ``The report, as it now stands, basically, was rejected by a
majority of the committee because they felt it was not strong
enough,'' Vladeck said.
   The edited final report ``did not allow us to express our
outrage, our anger and our dismay at what we studied,'' complained
Phyllis Wolfe, a panel member and the head of Health Care for the
Homeless, Inc., in Washington.
   ``Those who served on the panel ... were a little disturbed that
we were not able to go into more detail on the problems of the
homeless and some of the corrective measures that should be
taken,'' added Nathan Stark, a Washington lawyer and panel member
who joined in signing a six-page supplemental statement issued by
Vladeck's office in New York.
   Despite the complaints, Vladeck raised the prospect that the
material in the supplemental statement actually generated more
attention by being left out of the official report than if it had
been included.
   Faced with a choice of leaving out their strongest comments and
issuing no report at all, the majority chose to permit the Academy
to issue the bulk of the study and then make public their
supplement independently, he explained.
   ``And frankly,'' he added, ``I think we wound up getting more
publicity than we would have if it was buried in the report.''
   The supplemental statement called for a restoration of federal
support for low-income housing to 1981 levels, criticising the
sharp cuts in these programs in recent years.
   It also urged a minimum wage at a level which would make decent
housing possible in most cities and called for the federal
government to be the guarantor of last resort in health care.
   ``The way you do away with homelessness is to provide homes,''
commented Stark, a former undersecretary at the Department of
Health and Human Services.
   The panelists were ``concerned that not enough emphasis was put
on the plight of homelessness, in terms of just a statistical
study,'' Stark said.
   ``I think the Academy is right in one sense,'' he added. ``They
want all their reports to be as scientific and objective as
possible.''
   But, he said, once he had visited shelters and met the homeless
and people who work with them, he realized that more was needed in
this report.
   The group ``felt that the tone was important, as well as the
substance, and this was not an issue where one can be comfortable
being as bland as such reports tend to be,'' said Vladeck.
   Dr. Frank Press, former science adviser to President Carter and
head of the independent Academy of Sciences since 1981, was quoted
in The New York Times as saying the supplementary statement had
been rejected because it was ``polemical and emotional.''
   Press' office said he was not available Tuesday and referred
calls to the Academy's Institute of Medicine, which organized the
study as requested by Congress.
   At that Institute, Dr. Fred Solomon termed the official report
``strong,'' but said some of the specific recommendations were
``not sufficiently scholarly and documented to be included.''
   The panel members ``were appalled at what they saw'' in their
research, Solomon said.
   He said academy reviewers agreed with many of the panel's
opinions, but felt they needed more detailed economic analyses
before they could be published officially.
   ``The committee members endorsed the (official) report, and were
at liberty to release their own statement elsewhere, which they
have just done,'' he added.
   The official 242-page report portrays a homeless population not
only of alcoholics and former mental patients, but one with growing
numbers of children and families scraping out a dismal existence in
rural communities.
   It calls children under 18 the fastest growing group among the
nation's homeless and says this is ``nothing short of a national
disgrace that must be treated with the urgency that such a
situation demands.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
