<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Wives-Hitman     09-20 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wives-Hitman,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother, Daughter Plead Innocent To Hiring Hit Man To Kill Husbands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman and her daughter pleaded innocent to
charges they tried to hire a hit man to kill their ex-husbands in
alleged schemes that prosecutors say each woman undertook without
the other's knowledge.
   Municipal Court Judge Nicholas Kasimatas set bail at $50,000 for
Judith Lynette East, 45, of Paradise Hills, and at $30,000 for her
daughter, Venise Lynette Morris, 27, of La Mesa.
   ``They apparently were not working together in the solicitation
for murder,'' Deputy District Attorney Robert Eichler said.
   Police say criminal-intelligence unit investigators heard that
each woman was looking for a hit man, so an undercover officer
telephoned each separately.
   East allegedly offered the officer $10,000 to kill her husband,
saying she would pay for it from his insurance policy, worth about
$100,000, Eichler said. Morris gave the officer a $1,000 personal
check as a down payment on a $5,000 fee to kill her ex-husband, he
said.
   ``Miss Morris' ex-husband was accused of molesting her young
daughter, which was the alleged motive in that case. It's very
clear ... that both defendants together fabricated evidence in that
(alleged molestation) case,'' Eichler said.
   The solicitation charge carries a maximum prison term of six
years, while a conspiracy charge could mean life in prison.
Kasimatis scheduled a preliminary hearing Oct. 3.
</TEXT>
