<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--NewOrleansDeficit     09-20 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--New Orleans Deficit,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deficit Means Unfilled Potholes, Police and Sheriff's Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Potholes won't be filled and parks won't get
money they expected for the rest of 1988 as New Orleans works to
eliminate a $19 million deficit.
   Mayor Sidney Barthelemy on Monday released a list of $6.9
million in planned cuts.
   Barthelemy is pushing a $125 flat fee to be charged on each
piece of property and a hiring freeze to eliminate the rest of the
deficit. Business leaders opppose the service charge, which would
raise $10 million.
   Criminal Sheriff Charles Foti's office and the police department
will lose $500,000 each.
   The sheriff said he could not discuss the cut in detail. Most of
the police cut will be from car maintenance, Assistant Chief
Administrative Officer Leonard Simmons said.
   A $460,000 cut to the Streets Department came with an order that
potholes be filled only in emergencies.
   City and Audubon parks and the New Orleans Museum of Art are
losing their fourth-quarter appropriations from the city _ $37,500
for City Park and $75,000 each for Audubon Park and the museum.
</TEXT>
