<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MissileDestruction     09-20 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missile Destruction,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cruise Missiles to be Destroyed Next Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States next month will destroy the
first of the ground-launched cruise missiles it agreed to eliminate
under the U.S.-Soviet Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces treaty, the
Pentagon announced Tuesday.
   Forty-one cruise missiles and canisters and seven launchers are
to be destroyed on Oct. 18-19 at Davis-Monthan Air Force Base near
Tucson, Ariz., the Defense Department said.
   On Sept. 8, as Vice President George Bush and Soviet observers
watched, U.S. officials burned off two Pershing rocket motors at
the Longhorn Army Ammunition Plant in Karnack, Texas, the first two
of the 867 U.S. missiles to be destroyed under the pact. The treaty
was signed last December in Washington.
   Under the treaty, Soviet officials are entitled to send up to 20
observers to watch the destruction in Arizona, according to
Pentagon officials.
   As of Aug. 30, the Soviet Union had destroyed 22 medium- and 50
shorter-range missiles. It must destroy a total of 1,752 SS-4,
SS-12 and SS-20 missiles under the treaty.
</TEXT>
