<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 1423EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Iran     09-20 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Iran,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Germany Building On Decades Of Good Ties With Iran</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Building on decades of good ties
with Iran, West Germany is seeking a greater business and
diplomatic role in the country now that a cease-fire has been
declared in the Iran-Iraq war.
   West German optimism toward Iran _ which sends its students to
be educated in Germany and buys more goods from this country than
any other _ grew after the recent release of West German hostage
Rudolf Cordes from his pro-Iranian Lebanese kidnappers on Sept. 12.
   
   Germans have long felt what one expert calls a ``post-Romantic
interest'' in Iran. A sector of the West German popular press
provides constant coverage of the doings of Soraya Bakhtiary, once
married to the shah of Iran.
   Unlike the United States and other countries that broke off or
curtailed ties with Iran after Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini came to
power in 1979, West Germany kept its relations active.
   Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher credited those contacts
with success in gaining the release of Cordes and promised to use
that goodwill to try to win freedom for other Western hostages in
Lebanon held by pro-Iranian kidnappers.
   ``Since the time of the German kaisers at the end of the 19th
century, there have been good relations, politically, economically
and culturally (with Iran),'' said Dieter Vogel, the Economics
Ministry spokesman in Bonn.
   Less than two days after Cordes' release, the Economics Ministry
announced that its No. 2 official, Dieter von Wuerzen, was heading
to Tehran for a four-day visit to explore further business
possibilities.
   ``But the announcement was just a coincidence,'' Vogel said in
an interview with The Associated Press, adding that the trip had
been planned in advance.
   ``West German companies have a good chance of taking part in
construction and reconstruction projects after the war with Iraq,''
Vogel said.
   The Welt Am Sonntag newspaper cited the Middle East Economic
Survey as saying reconstruction contracts for Iran could total $50
billion.
   ``When the weapons in the Persian Gulf went silent, German
businessmen began to make their calculations,'' the newspaper added.
   Vogel cautioned that Iran's hard currency shortage would make
foreign payments difficult.
   He said West Germans respect Iranians as trading partners _
despite the country's radical and sometimes fanatic image.
   Despite a trading decline due to the Iran-Iraq war, Iran
continues to import more goods from West Germany than from any
other country, according to the West German Economics Ministry.
   In 1987, West Germany sold $1.5 billion of goods to Iran,
including motor vehicles, heavy machinery and electronic products.
West Germany also imported $500 million worth of goods from Iran.
   While West German law strictly forbids the shipment of weapons
to areas of conflict, there are occasional reports of such material
reaching Iran.
   In May 1987, the Hamburg-based Der Spiegel magazine said a
government-owned factory near Wiesbaden was exporting machines used
for making ammunition to Iran and Iraq.
   A book published in July alleged that Frankfurt airport had
become a transfer hub for shipment of weapons to the Persian Gulf,
including Iran. Airport officials quickly denied the allegations,
which were in a book written by West German journalist Juergen Roth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
