<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Church-Powwow     09-20 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Church-Powwow,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Bars Indian Powwow As Anti-Christ</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Evangel is cq in 2nd and 5th grafs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WATERTOWN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A church will no longer allow a group of
American Indians to use its property for a powwow because the
pastor says the event unleashes ``spiritual forces that are
anti-Christ.''
   In a letter to the powwow organizers, David R. Powell, pastor of
the Evangel Assembly of God, wrote, ``We believe that there is a
polarity of spiritual belief between us that is irreconcilable.''
   The group had held the powwow at the church for the last two
years.
   The letter said the church believes it ``permitted some
spiritual forces that are anti-Christ and anti-Yahweh to operate on
our facility during the days of the powwow.'' The letter was not
more specific.
   A secretary at the Evangel Assembly of God said Tuesday the
pastor would not comment further.
   The church's decision had ``nothing to do with you as a nation
or race of people or a reflection of your personal or corporate
conduct or courtesy,'' Powell told the American Indians.
   Powwow organizers said they were puzzled and saddened.
   ``It's a complete misunderstanding of our culture,'' said Jim
Roaix Sr., of Naugatuck, editor of The Eagle, an Indian-affairs
newspaper published by Eagle Wing Press. Eagle Wing is a co-sponsor
of the powwow.
   More than 95 percent of American Indians are Christians, Roaix
said.
   ``I find it sad that in the 20th century there are religious
groups still operating on an 18th-century type of attitude,'' said
Patricia Benedict, executive director of American Indians for
Development of Meriden, the other sponsor.
   ``Powwows are basically social events,'' Benedict said.
   Karen Cooper, editorial writer at The Eagle, said Tuesday the
powwow also educated people about the Indian culture. ``It's like
going to a fair,'' she said.
   The festival, to be held this weekend, has been moved to Black
Rock State Park. It will include American Indian arts and crafts,
singers and dancers, a replica of New England bark-covered wigwam,
storytelling and cooking demonstrations.
   Last year's event drew more than 3,000 visitors, with the church
receiving a share of the proceeds, Roaix said.
</TEXT>
