<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LandlordSentence     09-20 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Landlord Sentence,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Landlord Begins House Arrest In Rundown Apartment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A landlord convicted of multiple
housing violations strapped on an electronic ankle bracelet and
began a sentence of house arrest in an apartment without hot water,
refrigerator, stove or air conditioning.
   George C. Fogarty began serving the 30-day sentence Monday,
forced to stay in the apartment from 10 p.m. until 7 a.m. Monday
through Saturday and all day Sunday. His ankle bracelet triggers a
police alarm if he attempts to leave at the wrong times.
   ``As far as I'm concerned, if he has a toilet, he's lucky,''
said Broward County Court Judge June Johnson, who sentenced Fogarty
after he pleaded guilty in August to at least 40 housing code
violations. ``I visited apartments there where some people had
holes in the floor for a bathroom.''
   The charges against Fogarty included claims that raw sewage
spilled out on tenants' floors and that apartments were infested
with rats and roaches. The judge also ordered him to pay a $5,000
fine and placed him on probation for one year.
   Fogarty no longer owns the property that he is staying in for
the month. The new owners agreed to rent him an apartment.
   Fogarty, 36, said he was being made a scapegoat and that the
apartment he was sentenced to was in worse condition than when he
rented it out. ``I'm so mad,'' he said. ``I need a punching bag to
take out my frustrations.''
   But city prosecutor Scott Walker said, ``Fogarty has fought us
all along. He has never showed a willingness to comply with the
building codes. He is an excuse-giver.''
   If Fogarty violates his house arrest, he could be sentenced to
up to 11 years in prison.
</TEXT>
