<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HorseSlaughter     09-20 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Horse Slaughter,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carcasses Of 73 Wild Horses Found In Nevada Desert</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carcasses of 73 wild horses have been
discovered in an isolated section of central Nevada and authorities
believe they were gunned down, a Bureau of Land Management
spokesman said Tuesday.
   Federal investigators were tipped by a person who was questioned
about an earlier rifle slaughter of 44 horses. The two sites are 30
miles apart.
   Bob Stewart, bureau spokesman, said a helicopter crew Monday
identified 73 piles of bones and other evidence.
   The spokesman said ground crews were headed into the remote area
to verify the cause of death of the horses but the evidence so far
``leads us to believe they were shot.''
   He said the carcasses and bones of the horses were strewn along
an area one to two miles wide and about eight miles long,
apparently gunned down over a six-month period starting about one
year ago.
   Stewart said the person who led investigators to the grisly
discovery isn't being identified. He also declined to comment on
whether there are any firm leads in either of the horse slaughters.
   He said local authorities, the U.S. attorney and the FBI have
been notified about the latest case, and land management employees
have been told to ``increase their looking and try to spot any
similar tragedies.''
   Stewart said the carcasses weren't spotted immediately because
crews who fly the area making horse counts ``fly at higher
elevations and watch for dust clouds and movement.''
   He said the maximum penalty for shooting a wild horse is a fine
of $2,000 and a year in prison for each killing.
   More than 38,000 wild horses now run the open range of 10
western states, up from about 17,000 when Congress in 1971 made it
a crime to harrass or kill wild horses on public lands. Nevada has
up to 28,000 wild horses, according to estimates.
   At the turn of the century there were some 2 million wild horses
in the West, but they were relentlessly hunted by cowboys and
``mustangers'' in trucks and airplanes. The animals were
slaughtered for pet food and glue.
</TEXT>
