<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PhonyAd     09-20 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Phony Ad,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prankster Places Ad For Phony Car Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of people were snookered by a bogus
classified ad and showed up at a pier Tuesday for a non-existent
automobile auction of 600 cars, ``Audis to Mercedes,'' for $50 to
$700.
   ``The situation is frought with humor and everybody was joking
about it,'' said Victor Ross, spokesman for the City Department of
Transportation, the agency responsible for disposing of towed and
confiscated vehicles that are not claimed.
   By noon, nearly 70 people had arrived at the pier, ``including a
couple from Philadelphia, clutching about $5,000 in their fists,''
Ross said. ``They figured they could pick up five Audis at a $1,000
each, sell them at $2,000 and double their money. I don't know how
they planned to drive five cars back.''
   The ad, which appeared in The New York Times classified section
Monday, said a ``once-a-year liquidation'' auction would be held
Tuesday at Pier 76 in Manhattan by the ``New York City Parking
Authority.''
   There is no such authority. And while Pier 76 is where impounded
and confiscated cars are stored, auctions are held every Friday at
Pier 24. There is no annual clearance sale.
   Ross said about 400 cars are auctioned by the city each month,
either cars that have been towed away because the motorist
disobeyed parking regulations, or cars confiscated from scofflaws.
   The ad was placed by someone claiming to be Neil Rosen of the
Department of Transportation, who ordered the $403.90 bill sent to
the department.
   ``With the millions of ads that we run, this occasionally
happens,'' said Times spokeswoman Nancy Nielsen. ``We'll do
everything we can to straighten this out with the city.''
</TEXT>
