<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DanceBan     09-20 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dance Ban,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Board Appeals Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Don't start up the band just yet. The
Purdy School Board says it will appeal a judge's order that it
allow school-sponsored dancing.
   The school board also has asked that the judge stay his order
pending their appeal.
   U.S. District Judge Russell Clark ruled Aug. 1 that Purdy High
School's century-old dance ban was unconstitutional because it
promoted the values of those who oppose dancing for religious
reasons.
   Clark later awarded the 21 Purdy students and their parents who
began lobbying for a dance two years ago $1 in damages _ all they
requested _ and nearly $80,000 in attorney fees.
   But school board officials, in announcing late Monday that they
would appeal, insisted the ban was not religiously grounded.
   In a statement, Schools Superintendent Sheldon Buxton cited
concerns about policing and paying for school-sponsored dancing
that board members say led them to support the ban.
   William Fleischaker, the Joplin attorney who represented the
pro-dancers, said Tuesday that he would advise the students to
contine with plans for a dance by asking the school board's
permission to hold on.
   ``I expect that we will have a formal request here fairly
quickly,'' Fleischaker said.
</TEXT>
