and alcohol and other consumption taxes as preferable to raising
individual income tax rates.
   Strauss said the panel probably will make some recommendations
on reforming the budget process, examining such issues as whether a
two-year budget would improve Congress' ability to meet deadlines
and whether a line-item veto or a constitutional amendment to
balance the budget should be adopted.
   The 12-member commission, appointed by President Reagan and
congressional leaders, is split evenly between Democrats and
Republicans. Other members include Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee
Iacocca, AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland, and former Defense
Secretary Casper Weinberger.
