<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SpokaneRacism     09-20 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spokane Racism,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Council Bans Videotape After Black Leaders' Complaints</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council banned use of a police
videotape on drug-trafficking gangs after black leaders complained
a profile of gang members promoted racist stereotypes.
   The council on Monday also agreed to establish a task force to
plan with police strategies for keeping gangs out of Spokane, and
unanimously approved a resolution condemning a recent series of
racially motivated assaults and vandalism.
   Police Chief Terry Mangan, who had been ordered by City Manager
Terry Novak to stay away from the meeting to avoid confrontations,
defended the videotape.
   ``We support the task force's efforts, and hope it will be
successful,'' Mangan said. ``I just hope this delay, this possible
change of direction, does not work to the advantage of drug gangs.
That would be a real tragedy.''
   A group of black leaders said the videotape, which depicts gang
activity in other cities, unfairly blames black youths for the drug
problem and has caused a backlash by police and racist groups.
   The tape had been shown to school and civic groups and on a city
cable television station.
   ``It is one of the most racist pieces of propaganda I have ever
seen,'' said Jerry Harvey, a Spokane School District employee. ``If
there had been proper input and consultation, this tape would have
never gone out.''
   ``The bad guys come in all colors and wear all kinds of hats,''
said Carl Boston, president of the Spokane Chapter of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
   Police have repeatedly stopped black youths for minor offenses,
sometimes with guns drawn, the black leaders complained.
   ``We think it's undue harassment,'' said the Rev. Ezra Kinlow.
``The police department is there to protect us, but we do feel they
are overreacting.''
   Mangan said the videotape was prepared mostly from network
documentaries and ``based on the best advice we were able to obtain
from a number of cities which have gone through what we are just
starting to go through.''
   The task force will be comprised of five black people chosen by
Mayor Vicki McNeill, two members of the Interstate Task Force on
Human Relations, and council members Sheri Barnard and Joel Crosby.
</TEXT>
