<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-News Conference,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Unlikely To Hold News Conference Before Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan probably will not hold a
formal news conference before the Nov. 8 election but ``very
likely'' will have one after his successor is chosen, a White House
spokesman said Tuesday.
   Marlin Fitzwater did not say why it is doubtful Reagan will have
a news conference before Election Day.
   Reagan has committed himself to an ambitious schedule of
out-of-town trips on behalf of Republican presidential nominee
George Bush and GOP congressional candidates.
   Asked at his daily news briefing when Reagan will hold a formal
news conference, Fitzwater said, ``We do not anticipate one before
the election.''
   Asked whether one is likely after Nov. 8, he said, ``Very
likely.''
   The president's last news conference was at the seven-nation
economic summit in Toronto on June 21.
   Fitzwater said that an article written by Reagan will appear in
a forthcoming issue of International Affairs Magazine, published by
the Soviet Foreign Ministry, and he said it was likely Reagan would
be granting individual interviews to various news organizations in
the coming months.
   The spokesman said Reagan presented the article to Boris
Piadyshev, spokeman for the Foreign Minister, when Piadyshev
visited him in the Oval Office on Monday.
   Fitzwater said the issue of the magazine will be published on
Nov. 1. He said the subject of the president's article would be
``peace, freedom and world affairs.''
