<1ST_LINE>r p AM-MarilynQuayle     09-20 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marilyn Quayle,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marilyn Quayle Denies Husband Chosen For His Good Looks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD GREEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marilyn Quayle on Tuesday characterized as
``totally insulting'' speculation that Republican nominee George
Bush selected her husband as his running mate because Dan Quayle's
good looks might attract female voters.
   ``George Bush wouldn't have selected someone who could not stand
in his stead for president,'' she told reporters during her first
solo campaign tour.
   Mrs. Quayle said her husband has established a reputation as an
expert on defense and arms control issues as a 12-year Senate
veteran, and has met with many foreign leaders.
   ``The women of Indiana have elected him, and it's certainly not
because of his looks,'' she said.
   During a series of brief interviews with local television
reporters, Mrs. Quayle blamed the media for the controversy
surrounding the GOP vice presidential candidate's academic
performance and military service.
   ``He's never been a person who kowtowed to the media, stroked
them, had them in our home,'' she said. ``The Washington media
elite didn't know him and they were struck off guard.''
   In an earlier interview with ABC-TV's Barbara Walters, Mrs.
Quayle said the media is overwhelmingly liberal and was pursuing
her husband because he is conservative.
   Mrs. Quayle, who met her husband in 1972 when both were
attending night classes at Indiana University Law School, is
considered one of the stronger assets of her husband's campaign and
his most trusted adviser.
   A senior campaign official said that in recognition of her
campaign skills, she has been asked to travel independently on
behalf of the GOP ticket. She will join the Indiana senator for one
or two days each week.
   Mrs. Quayle, 39,is a practiced campaigner who often pulls her
husband away from reporters when he begins to respond to impromptu
questions and tends to make misstatements or garble his words.
   She insists she is ``not trying to protect him'' but is
reminding him to cut his conversation short and keep up with his
campaign schedule.
   Quayle, 41, told one news conferent that his wife ``is my best
adviser, my strongest supporter, the person that I love more than
anybody else in this world.'' He called her ``a very strong,
independent-minded woman'' with whom he has a very close
relationship.
   They have three children, Tucker, 14; Benjamin, 11, and Corinne,
9.
