<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Kitty'sFaith Bjt   09-20 0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kitty's Faith, Bjt,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prospect Of Being First Jewish First Lady Not Lost on Kitty
Dukakis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Never one to mince words, Kitty Dukakis
has been particularly outspoken at times when questioned about her
Jewish faith or world events affecting the Jewish state of Israel.
   She was quick to express her outrage when Pope John Paul II
embraced Austrian President Kurt Waldheim, who was accused of
complicity in Nazi war crimes.
   On the other hand, she hasn't been afraid to criticize Israeli
efforts to force Soviet Jews to emigrate to Israel instead of the
United States.
   Most recently, she spoke forcefully when asked about the
resignations of a handful of volunteers and a ranking George Bush
adviser who were mentioned in allegations of anti-Jewish
activities. One volunteer who resigned had praised a researcher who
has denied the existence of the Holocaust during World War II.
   ``For anyone to suggest the Holocaust was a hoax is very
painful,'' Mrs. Dukakis said. ``Six million Jews and millions of
others lost their lives. ... One has to wonder why these people
were attracted and recruited to the campaign of my husband's
opponent.''
   The prospect of being the nation's first Jewish first lady is
not lost on Katharine Dickson Dukakis, the wife of Democratic
presidential nominee Michael Dukakis.
   She returned to Brookline on Tuesday afternoon from a trip to
Rhode Island so she could spend the holiest of Jewish holidays, Yom
Kippur, at home. She was attending Temple Israel in Brookline
Tuesday night before returning home for the traditional fast.
   She has been an active and aggressive campaigner for her husband
and referred to her faith frequently during appearances before the
primary in New York, where Jews are an important voting bloc. She
traces her vigorous lobbying on behalf of refugees from around the
world to the lessons of the Holocaust.
   ``I feel a great deal of pride in my ethnic and religious
background,'' Mrs. Dukakis, leaning back in her chair and breaking
into a broad smile, said in a recent interview at her home.
   She said at the outset of the campaign she feared she would
encounter anti-Semitism but has said since that that hasn't
happened. But both she and her Greek Orthodox husband have been
criticized by conservatives for their interfaith marriage.
   James Jatras, an aide to Sen. William L. Armstrong, R-Colo.,
circulated a letter in May denouncing Dukakis for his marriage to a
``non-Christian'' and said Dukakis was therefore not a Christian in
good standing. Mrs. Dukakis also was targeted by a conservative
columnist who questioned her commitment to Judaism by citing her
marriage to a non-Jew.
   The Dukakises have said little about either incident, choosing
to ignore instead of publicize them. Their children, John, born
during Mrs. Dukakis' first marriage, and daughters Andrea and Kara,
observe the holidays of both the Jewish and Greek Orthodox faiths
with their parents.
   But in other public statements, Mrs. Dukakis has said she is
``fiercely proud'' of her faith and also has promised to host a
Passover Seder in the White House if her husband is elected
president.
   Mrs. Dukakis is the daughter of Harry Ellis Dickson, associate
conductor of the Boston Pops Orchestra, and the late Jane Goldberg
Dickson, who met her future husband when both were studying music
and the arts in Berlin prior to World War II.
   They left Germany as Hitler was coming to power. While she was
raised in a Jewish home in a predominantly Jewish community, Mrs.
Dukakis has said she did not come to fully appreciate her heritage
until a 1976 visit to Israel and the Holocaust Memorial Yad Vashem
in Jerusalem.
   ``That visit changed everthing for me,'' she recently told
Haolam Hazeh, a Jewish weekly newspaper. ``I was brought up on this
memory but I don't think I understood the full significance until I
visited Yad Vashem.''
   Mrs. Dukakis was a member of a presidential commission on the
Holocaust until 1986, when President Reagan declined to appoint her
to a new term.
</TEXT>
