<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Witness-Firebomb     09-20 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Witness-Firebomb,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arsonists Get Maximum in Firebombing of Drug Witness' Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge handed down maximum sentences Tuesday to
two arsonists for firebombing the house of a Guyanese immigrant who
had taken a stand against drug dealers invading his neighborhood.
   State Supreme Court Justice Thomas Demakos sentenced Robert
Webster, 17, to 50 years to life in prison for two first-degree
arson convictions. Claude Johnson, 28, received the maximum of 25
years to life on a single arson count.
   Sentences for criminal mischief and intimidating a witness were
ordered to run concurrently with the arson terms, so the men will
serve no extra time for those crimes.
   Johnson and Webster were convicted last month of throwing
Molotov cocktails into a house in Queens. The house was owned by a
man who went by the single name of Arjune, a recent immigrant who
had complained to police about drug dealing near his home.
   The case achieved national notoriety when a police officer
assigned to guard Arjune's house after the firebombing was shot to
death as he sat in his patrol car. Police said the shooting of
Officer Edward Byrne was ordered by high-level drug dealers who
controlled the neighborhood's crack trade.
   The case led to a major police offensive against drug dealers in
the area.
   Arjune, has since been given a new home and identity under the
federal witness protection program, testified at the trial that his
house was firebombed twice early in the morning of Nov. 10, 1987.
   Johnson was arrested after the first of two attacks, which were
a couple of hours apart, but Webster participated in both, Arjune
said.
</TEXT>
