<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CitadelChaplain     09-20 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Citadel Chaplain,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Citadel Reaches Settlement With School Chaplain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Citadel has reached an out-of-court
settlement with its head chaplain, who had sued the state-supported
military school accusing it of interfering with worship services,
the school's lawyer said Tuesday.
   Details of the settlement with the Rev. Gordon E. Garthe will be
spelled out in a federal order in the next week or so, said M.
Dawes Cooke Jr., a Citadel lawyer. He said the settlement reached
Monday ``redefines and clarifies the job description for the
position of chaplain'' but does not include payment of damages.
   Garthe, a United Methodist minister and retired Navy chaplain,
has been director of chaplain activities at The Citadel since 1983.
He claimed in his suit that the school violated the constitutional
guarantee of freedom of religion and the prohibition of a state
religion.
   The school denied the charges, but said it had been ``critical
of (Garthe's) lack of support and general acceptance by the Corps
of Cadets.'' Garthe claimed that church attendance had nosedived
after 1973 court ruling that it could not be mandatory, but that it
had actually increased after he was hired 10 years later.
   Efforts to reach Garthe for comment on the settlement were
unsuccessful. A person answering the telephone in his office said
he would not be in Tuesday.
   In his suit, Garthe also claimed he was threatened with firing
after he complained that offerings collected at Protestant worship
services on Sundays went to the state's general fund.
   The chaplain accused the military college of controlling such
things as the choice of speakers at services, uniform requirements,
seating, flag display, the bearing of arms in the chancel and
selection of music.
</TEXT>
