<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Congressman-Vandalism     09-20 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congressman-Vandalism,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Mississippi Congressman's Home Target Of Vandals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON HARRIST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police stepped up patrols near the home of
Rep. Mike Espy on Tuesday after the black congressman expressed
concern for his family in the wake of vandalism at his home that
included racial slurs.
   ``I'm the congressman, not my wife, my brother or my children,''
Espy said as he cleaned paint poured on an entrance-way floor at
his home in suburban Madison. ``I can defend myself but I want them
to leave my family out of it.''
   Espy said his wife returned to home late Monday to find a racial
slur on doors in the entrance-way. He said the words, at the top of
each door, appeared to have been scratched into the wood by ``a
pencil or a pen without ink. They had started the words `U.S. Con'
on one door but it appeared the point of what they were using had
broken.''
   Madison Police Chief Jimmy Dukes said he sent officers to the
house. ``And, of course, we are going to have extra patrols in that
area _ that goes without saying,'' Dukes said.
   ``Sure it makes you angry,'' Espy said. ``We've come a long way
in Mississippi but cases like this remind you how far we've got to
go.''
   Espy, a Democrat and the state's first black congressman since
Reconstruction, is being challenged in the November election by
white Republican Jack Coleman. Espy has been leading polls in the
district. His brother has been his campaign manager.
   Espy said he would immediately return to the campaign but was
concerned for his family.
   ``My son is 5 and my daughter is 8 and I had to explain to them
the history of race relations in Mississippi,'' he said. Referring
to the scratched epithet, he said, ``I had to tell my children what
that meant and why somebody would do that. It was not an easy thing
to do.''
   Espy said plants in the entry-way had been uprooted and paint
dashed on some of the plants.
   ``Something like this should not be a part of the American
political process,'' said Coleman, contacted by telephone as he
headed to Belzoni for a day of campaigning. ``We should talk about
the issues and beat each other on top of the head with those.''
   ``I can't imagine any of my people doing that,'' Coleman said.
``Who knows why someone would do something like this. It may not
have had anything to do with politics but no matter why it was
done, it was totally wrong and I regret to see it.''
   Espy, 34, said he had received threatening calls in the past,
``but you always expect those. There has not been an increase in
those calls and this is the first time something like this has
happened.''
   ``I think most Mississippians would be upset to hear something
like this has happened but we all realize there are still some
ignorant people running around,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
