<1ST_LINE>r p AM-FlagFactory     09-20 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Flag Factory,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flag Maker Prospers in Reagan Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM KRATTENMAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLOOMFIELD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan years have been great for the
flag business, says a member of the family that owns the nation's
largest flag-making company.
   ``The flag market usually has ups and downs, but it's been a
steady incline since the Reagan administration came aboard,'' said
C. Lee Beard, vice presidant of Annin & Co.
   The fourth-generation co-owner and his brother, Randolph, opened
one of their New Jursey factories Tuesday to Vice President George
Bush, who has mentioned the company often in contending that the
administration has revived patriotic fervor.
   ``My friends, flag sales are doing well and America is doing
well,'' Bush said in front of a crowd of about 250, many of them
Annin employees, in a flag-waving rally across the street from the
old brick factory.
   C. Lee Beard, whose brother joined Bush on the rostrum, said the
company has enjoyed a sales increase of roughly 25 percent in the
Reagan years. Annin is one of a handful of major companies making
the stars and stripes.
   Beard said he could not provide exact sales figures.
   He credited Reagan for the steady growth of his company, which
has expanded from three to five plants during Reagan's term.
   ``I think his patriotism has stirred flag sales,'' Beard said.
``He's increased pride in America.''
   While Annin has supplied flags for inaugurations, the Apollo 11
moon flight, the United Nations and the armed forces, everyday
citizens still account for the bulk of sales, Beard said.
   He said the Bloomfield factory each week makes about 30,000 of
the small flags that have lately become common fare at patriotic
celebrations.
   In addition, about 7,000 to 10,000 of the 3-by-5-foot flags
commonly displayed by homeowners are produced each week at the
factory, where women operate machines by hand, starting at minimum
wage.
   In another flag-interest indicator, the federal government last
year satisfied more than 109,000 requests to briefly fly flags over
the nation's Capitol and then ship them to people.
   The requests numbered just 43,011 in 1979, a clerk said.
   While Reagan deserves credit for the sales trend, Beard said
this year's unusually strong September might also have something to
do with Bush's campaign.
   Labor Day usually marks a fast drop in flag buying, but demand
has held steady in 1988, Beard said.
   The company found out about Bush's visit about a week ago, and
quickly arranged five buses to haul in employees from its three
other New Jersey locations, Beard said. Annin also has a plant in
Ohio.
   Despite the good business of recent years, Beard said he's
spotted a less-welcome trend: an influx of the red-white-and-blue
from factories in Korea, Hong Kong and Taiwan.
   Those countries' lower labor costs enable them to sell flags at
a lower price and American producers are starting to feel the
pinch, Beard said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880920-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 1825EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Pesticides     09-20 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pesticides,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Approves Eight-Year Pesticide Safety Deadline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House approved stepped-up pesticide
regulation Tuesday, voting to set an accelerated, eight-year
deadline for completion of safety reviews of hundreds of chemicals
used by farmers to protect crops.
   The measure, approved and sent to the Senate on a voice vote,
amounts to a bare-bones bill without groundwater-protection and
other contoversial features urged by environmentalists.
   ``This is the art of the possible, this will not satisfy hardly
anyone but this is what we can do at this point,'' House
Agriculture Committee Chairman E. ``Kika'' de la Garza, D-Texas,
said in urging approval. He said lawmakers could return to the
tougher issues in the future.
   The bill calls for completion of hundreds of safety reviews by
the Environmental Protection Agency within eight years. The process
is designed to end use of the most hazardous chemicals and limit
utilization of others that present health dangers.
   The reviews have been in progress since the mid-1970s but
without a deadline. The General Accounting Office estimates that at
the current pace of about two dozen a year the task would not be
completed until 2024.
   The bill would largely end indemnities to pesticide makers whose
products have been ordered off the market for safety reasons. Thus
far, the EPA has been forced to pay $20 million to buy up supplies
of banned pesticides.
   Provisions of the bill call for fees paid by manufacturers
ranging from $50,000 to $150,000 to finance the reviews. The
industry and the agency would share the cost of storage and
disposal under the measure, which would reauthorize for three years
the 1947 Federal Insecticide, Fungicide and Rodenticide Act.
   Environmentalists say the EPA has been dragging its feet on the
safety reviews because it lacks the money to pay the indemnities.
   The act has been due for reauthorization since 1983 but
squabbling among environmentalists, labor and the farm lobby have
frozen action.
   ``We have had difficulty in times past in trying to make this
happen,'' Rep. Tony Coelho, D-Calif., told the House.
   Farmers have been highly suspicious of legislation they fear
would ban or raise the cost of pesticides, which arose out of World
War II chemical warfare research and now represent a fundamental
element of U.S. agriculture.
   ``Certainly with regard to agriculture, the efficient and
judicious use of pesticides is crucial to the safety of the food
supply that we enjoy today,'' declared Rep. Fred Grandy, R-Iowa.
   Government research, however, has shown that some pesticides can
cause cancer and other severe health problems. Environmentalists
have been calling for tighter regulation since 1962 when naturalist
Rachel Carson spotlighted the problem in her bestselling ``Silent
Spring.''
   Most environmentalists have been saying the current bill is
better than nothing or, at least, would not make the situation
worse. But they point to a lack of any component that would step up
monitoring of groundwater, which provides the basic drinking supply
for half of all Americans.
   A report issued last week by the U.S. Public Interest Research
Group, an organization founded by Ralph Nader, said a search of EPA
records showed that 73 pesticides have been found in groundwater in
34 states.
   Moreover, some environmental groups were opposed to the
legislation.
   ``We're not willing to put pesticide regulation on the back
burner for three to four years,'' said Jay Feldman of the National
Coalition Against the Misuse of Pesticides. ``That's not any kind
of message to be sending out across the country to people who are
facing chemicals in their drinking water, chemicals in their
workplace and chemicals in their food.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
