<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Politics     09-20 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Politics,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Iran Ministers: Ex-Guerrilla, U.S. Embassy Occupier; U.S.
Students</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The five new Cabinet ministers approved
by Iran's parliament Tuesday include an ex-guerrilla who fought
against the Shah, a former student who occupied the U.S. Embassy in
Tehran and two ministers with graduate degrees from American
universities.
   Tehran Radio said the 270-seat Majlis, or parliament, rejected a
sixth appointee, the prospective minister of commerce Majid
Hedayatzadeh, in the second vote of confidence in Prime Minister
Hussein Musavi's government in eight days.
   The Iranian news agency IRNA, monitored in Cyprus, said the new
Revolutionary Guards minister, Ali Shamkhani, 33, was a senior aide
of Commander-in-Chief Hashemi Rafsanjani. Shamkhani also was
Rafsanjani's deputy for operations and information at military
command headquarters, IRNA said.
   Shamkhani takes over from Mohsen Rafiqdoust, the victim of a
no-confidence vote in the first parliament session on Sept. 12.
That session was held amid criticism of the Revolutionary Guards,
blamed for several battlefield defeats that led Tehran to accept a
cease-fire in the Persian Gulf war in July.
   The radio said Hedayatzadeh could not muster the necessary
votes, with only 94 deputies supporting him.
   No one was given that portfolio in the first Cabinet Musavi
presented. It was not clear if the Majlis objected to
Hedayatzadeh's credentials or to the post itself.
   In the previous round, the ministers of agriculture and
education were rejected. On Tuesday, Issa Kalantari was installed
as agriculture minister and Mohammed Ali Najafi as minister of
education.
   The Majlis approved Bijan Namdar Zangeneh, 36, construction
minister until he resigned in July, as energy minister. Gholamreza
Forouzesh, one of Zangeneh's aides, was installed as new minister
of construction.
   IRNA said Shamkhani was a guerrilla in the underground campaign
against Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi before the 1979 revolution that
brought Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini to power.
   Shamkhani commanded the Revolutionary Guards along the southern
front after the gulf war started in 1980 and later rose to the post
of deputy commander of the guards. IRNA said two of his brothers,
Mohammad and Hamid, died in the war.
   An Iranian political analyst, speaking in Nicosia on condition
of anonymity, said Shamkhani was at one point entrusted with
chasing dissidents opposed to Khomeini's fundamentalist regime,
known as the Mujahedeen Khalq.
   IRNA said Forouzesh, 33, was one of the students who took over
the American Embassy in November 1979. The report did not say
whether he was involved in keeping U.S. officials hostage for 444
days.
   Kalantari, 36, has a doctorate in agriculture from Iowa
University and a masters degree from the University of Nebraska.
His brother Mousa, then minister of roads and transportation, died
in a 1981 bomb blast that killed numerous top officials, IRNA said.
   Najafi, 37, has a masters degree in mathematics from the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, IRNA said. Since 1984 he has
worked as head of training at the Islamic Republic of Iran
Broadcasting Corp.
</TEXT>
