<1ST_LINE>r w AM-U.S.-Greece     09-20 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-U.S.-Greece,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meeting Could Lead to Resumption of Base Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Resumption of suspended negotiations on the
future of U.S. military bases in Greece could depend on the Greek
foreign minister's planned talks here Wednesday with Secretary of
State George Shultz, a senior Shultz aide said Tuesday.
   Foreign Minister Carolas Papoulias is scheduled to meet and
lunch with Shultz in his capacity as current representative of the
European Common Market, but U.S.-Greek relations also will be
covered, Assistant Secretary of State Rozanne Ridgway told a
congressional panel.
   Negotiations in Athens on American military bases were suspended
Sept. 5 when Ambassador Alan Flanigan, the U.S. negotiator,
returned to Washington for instructions on a ``major element'' in
the Greek position. That was identified as a demand for U.S. forces
to vacate Hellenikon air base at Athens International Airport, Ms.
Ridgway said.
   Resumption was tentatively scheduled for October, but the date
is undecided and ``whether it takes place'' depends partly on talks
with Papoulias, she told the House Foreign Affairs subcommittee on
European and Middle Eastern Affairs.
   ``The disposition of Hellenikon will have to be resolved ... how
it is going to be dealt with affects the whole negotiations,'' she
said.
   Ms. Ridgway did not disclose the U.S. response to the demand for
its planes to leaveHellenikon. She said in answer to a question
that if agreement cannot be reached, ``we have procedures for
leaving'' but ``we are not at any stage of starting that at this
time.''
   Subcommittee Chairman Lee Hamilton asked if the illness of Prime
Minister Andreas Papandreou, reported to be facing heart surgery,
would affect the base negotiations. The Greek government has said
repeatedly that foreign policy is unaffected by Papandreou's
illness and officials have been instructed to carry on their
functions, Ms. Ridgway replied.
   As to whether the base negotiations would be completed before
parliamentary elections, she said this was uncertain because
setting of the election date is linked to the prime minister's
health.
</TEXT>
