<1ST_LINE>r w AM-IndianInvestigation     09-20 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Indian Investigation,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arizona Newspaper-inspired Probe Gets Additional Money</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Rules Committee voted Tuesday to
appropriate an additional $108,000 for the special committee
investigating the Bureau of Indian Affairs and alleged
mismanagement of natural resources such as gas and oil.
   Last November, the committee unanimously authorized a yearlong,
$740,000 investigation into alleged fraud, mismanagement and
malfeasance in the administration of housing, education and health
programs.
   Sen. Daniel K. Inouye, D-Hawaii, chairman of the Select
Committee on Indian Affairs, said the investigation ``is the most
professional I have seen,'' even more so than the Iran-contra of
which he was the co-chairman.
   He said the special committee headed by Sen. Dennis DeConcini,
D-Ariz., had issued 130 subpoenas and interviewed or taken
depositions from over 300 individuals.
   Inouye said there have been allegations of malfeasance,
negligence and criminal activity in which the dollar sum may exceed
$11 billion.
   DeConcini said the special committee would not be rushed in its
investigation. He said hearings would be held early in 1989.
   When the DeConcini committee was formed last year, Inouye said
the allegations of mismanagement ``extend to almost ever aspect of
the administration of Indian affairs, and include the development
of Indian trust resources, and the management of housing programs,
health programs, education programs, economic development
initiatives, and the administration of law enforcement on Indian
reservations.''
   The special investigation was prompted by a series of articles
in The Arizona Republic last October. The newspaper reported that
multi-million dollar federal Indian programs are plagued by fraud,
incompetence and deceit.
   As an example, Inouye said 34 reports of the Interior
Department's inspector general and an equal number of reports
issued by the General Accounting Office, the congressional
investigative arm, since the early 1970s estimate that the Interior
Department has failed to collect approximately $5.7 billion in oil
and gas royalties from oil companies.
   Inouye said the Interior and GAO reports also document another
$5.8 billion worth of oil and gas that has been illegally siphoned
off of Indian and public lands.
   An Arizona Republic account, he said, indicates that the
resulting ``windfall to oil companies has been placed at more than
$1 billion a year in studies by the Interior Department's inspector
general, the General Accounting Office and congressional panels.''
</TEXT>
