<HEAD>Bangkok Hotel World's Best in Survey for Eighth Year Running</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS in 4th graf, `The top...' that Carlyle was No. 12
sted No. 11</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the eighth year running, the Oriental Hotel
in Bangkok, Thailand, has been rated the world's best hotel in a
survey conducted by Institutional Investor magazine.
   Taking the next three spots were the Regent of Hong Kong, the
Vier Jahreszeiten of Hamburg, West Germany, and the Mandarin
Oriental of Hong Kong, all holding the same rankings they had in
1987.
   The financial monthly magazine polls about 100 senior bankers
from around the world who do a lot of traveling and asks them to
rate their favorite hotels on a scale of 1 to 100.
   The top U.S. hotel was the Carlyle of New York, rated No. 12.
Five U.S. hotels were in the top 25.
   The Connaught of London moved up to fifth place from eighth last
year and the Shangri La of Singapore advanced from ninth to sixth.
   The Okura of Tokyo moved down from sixth to seventh and the Ritz
of Paris fell to eighth from fifth. The Bristol of Paris, unrated
in 1987, took ninth place, and the Peninsula of Hong Kong once
again held 10th place.
   The top-ranked Oriental, under German manager Kurt Wachtveitl,
has a staff of 1,000 and has completed a $20 million renovation,
Institutional Investor says in its September issue.
   Rounding out the top 25 hotels are:
   _Plaza Athenee, Paris.
   _Carlyle, New York.
   _Claridge's, London.
   _Dolder Grand, Zurich, Switzerland.
   _Stanford Court, San Francisco.
   _Baur au Lac, Zurich, Switzerland.
   _Imperial, Tokyo.
   _Hassler Villa Medici, Rome.
   _Atlantic Hotel Kempinski, Hamburg, West Germany.
   _Berkeley, London.
   _Regent, Sydney, Australia.
   _Vier Jahreszeiten, Munich, West Germany.
   _Pierre, New York.
   _Four Seasons, Washington.
   _Ritz-Carlton, Chicago.
