<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Licenses-Farmers     09-20 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Licenses-Farmers,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmers, Firefighters Need No Special Licenses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Transportation Department on Tuesday
excluded farmers and firefighters from a federal requirement that
drivers of large trucks have a special license, saying these groups
do not have a poor traffic safety record.
   The announcement came after several months of public hearings
and protests from the farm community over new federal requirements
that are aimed at anyone driving a truck weighing more than 26,000
pounds or any vehicles carrying hazardous cargo.
   Farmers have complained that the special license requirement as
enacted by Congress would cover drivers of large trucks carrying
grain and hay, even some pickup trucks, bulk fuel and fertilizer
tanks and firefighters driving emergency vehicles.
   The law provides for the department to allow exemptions.
   Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley said the states are being
notified that they may exempt farm-to-market truck operators as
long as the vehicles are used to transport agricultural products,
farm machinery or farm supplies no more than 150 miles from home.
   ``Generally these vehicles have a better accident record than
`non-farm' vehicles of similar size,'' the department concluded. In
1982, the most recent year cited, the accident rate for farm
vehicles was less than half the rate for non-farm vehicles, it said.
   Additionally, the department said, the states may exclude
drivers of firefighting equipment operated by municipalities or
volunteer fire departments as well as military personnel, including
National Guardsmen, who drive military vehicles.
   Congress enacted the law in 1986 to tighten control over drivers
who drive large commercial trucks from state to state. It is aimed
at ending the practice by some commercial drivers of obtaining
licenses from a number of states to conceal traffic violations. The
law also requires minimum standards for commercial drivers and a
testing program.
   Both the licenses and testing continue to be administered by the
states.
   At the same time, the department said it was rejecting requests
for similar waivers to transit operators, railroad employees and
public utility employees.
   Sen. John Danforth, R-Mo., principal author of the 1986 law
requiring the special licensing, said he agreed with the
department's decision.
   ``The law ... was not intended to unduly burden farmers as they
transport their grain to the silo or their crops to market,''
Danforth said in a statement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
