<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bennett-Dukakis     09-20 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bennett-Dukakis,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bennett, In Last Day As Education Secretary, Bashes Dukakis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Education Secretary William J. Bennett spent his
last day in office Tuesday berating Michael Dukakis and contending
Dukakis advisers ``tend to look down their noses at the basic and
instinctive patriotism of a lot of the American people.''
   Bennett also criticized Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor and
Democratic presidential nominee, for vetoing legislation that would
have penalized teachers unless they led their students in the
Pledge of Allegiance.
   But in attacking the Dukakis veto, which followed advisory
opinions from the state attorney general and supreme court that the
bill was unconstitutional, Bennett also agreed with Dukakis that
any student who objects should not be required to recite the pledge.
   Dukakis supporters turned out in force to greet Bennett, terming
him a hypocrite for criticizing Dukakis at a time when state
spending on education has increased significantly and the Reagan
administration had tried to cut programs and eliminate the
Education Department.
   Bennett, appearing at a news conference on behalf of Republican
presidential nominee George Bush, said Dukakis had at best an
average record on education and called his veto of the pledge bill
``his most famous educational act.''
   Bennett said he would oppose such a law at the federal level
because education is a state issue. But he said he supported state
laws that required the pledge while excusing students who object on
religious or other grounds.
   Dukakis believes recitation of the pledge should be a voluntary
tradition in schools, while Bennett called for state laws that
require recitation but do not penalize students who object.
   ``If you don't like the Pledge of Allegiance you're going to
hate the Declaration of Independence,'' Bennett said.
   In a 1986 assessment, Bennett praised improvements in SAT scores
that moved Massachusetts into the top third of states which
administer the tests and also credited the state for putting ``in
place important reforms to improve teacher quality through testing
of new teachers, performance incentives and alternative
certifications to attract the most qualified candidates into
teaching.''
   After being read those comments Tuesday, Bennett said, ``Check
the record and see what belongs to Dukakis and what belongs to
King,'' a reference to former Gov. Edward J. King. When told the
teacher-quality legislation was part of a package Dukakis supported
in 1985, Bennett said, ``that may well be ... the governor's record
itself is not distinguished.''
   Bennett, during a recent television appearance, said most
Dukakis advisers come from Brookline and Cambridge, communities
where he said many residents have ``disdain'' for patriotism.
   Bennett, whose tenure was marked by such outspoken and
controversial comments, refused to apologize Tuesday but said he
was referring specifically to Dukakis advisers.
   ``A lot of the Dukakis crowd, the Dukakis advisers, do have, I
think, a sense of intellectual superiority and do tend to look down
their noses at the basic and instinctive patriotism of a lot of the
American people,'' Bennett said.
   At the earlier meeting with reporters, Brookline state Rep.
Eleanor Myerson invited Bennett to visit her town, where Dukakis,
the Democratic presidential nominee, grew up and still lives.
   ``If Mr. Bennett thinks Brookline disdains basic American
values, he should visit our town and visit the Civil War, World War
I, World War II, Korean War and Vietnam veteran memorials honoring
Brookline citizens who died to protect his freedom to insult their
memory,'' Myerson said.
</TEXT>
