<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PinkSuits     09-20 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pink Suits,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS-Infected Inmates Sue Sheriff Over Pink Uniforms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four inmates who were issued pink prison
uniforms to show they have been exposed to the AIDS virus are suing
the sheriff, contending the outfits stigmatize them and constitute
cruel and unusual punishment.
   The complaint filed Monday was part of an amendment to a lawsuit
the Orleans Parish Jail inmates already filed alleging they are
kept segregated in cramped quarters and denied regular exercise,
counseling and adequate medical care.
   Sheriff Charles Foti said he is not singling the inmates out for
punishment or humiliation. Color-coded uniforms are used at the
jail to designate the sections to which inmates are assigned, he
said.
   Light pink, or rose colored, scrub suits are the color in the
jail's infectious-disease unit, he said.
   ``If they were in white or green, would that make a
difference?'' he said. ``What is pink? I wear pink all the time.
Pastel colors _ that's a very soothing type of color.''
   Foti said he recently adopted the color code because the cotton
scrub suits and jump suits are lighter and easier to clean and keep
track of.
   Federal prisoners wear blue, inmates who are housed in the tents
in the prison yard wear white, and inmates in the prison's general
medical ward wear green, Foti said.
</TEXT>
