<2ND_LINE>AM-Multiple Slayings,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Dead in Execution-Style Slayings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men and a woman, their nude bodies
found bound and gagged, were shot to death execution-style Tuesday,
apparently in drug-related violence, authorities said.
   Escambia County Sheriff Vince Seely refused to comment on
reports that a woman survived the shootings, which occurred at 1
a.m. at a duplex in the unincorporated community of Pleasant Grove
just west of Pensacola, on the Florida Panhandle.
   But neighbor who didn't want to be identified said her son saw a
woman in the middle of the highway, calling for help, just as an
ambulance and sheriff's deputies arrived.
   There were several suspects but no arrests by midafternoon,
Seely said. The bodies had not been positively identified.
   Police agencies across the state were alerted to watch for two
cars believed to be heading toward Miami, possibly traveling
together. The notice said the occupants were to be considered armed
and dangerous.
   A third car, a tan Buick sedan registered to a 24-year-old woman
who lived at the address where the shootings took place, was found
at the scene with blood stains on it.
   Seely said all the victims were in their early 30s and each was
shot at least once.
   ``All of the victims were found nude, hands and feet tied and
gagged,'' Seely said. ``All victims were shot in the head with a
medium caliber pistol.''
   Seely said there was no forced entry, but could not say if the
victims knew the attackers.
   He had no comment on reports that at least one victim also was
stabbed.
   He also would not identify the person who reported the shooting,
and declined to say whether drugs or other evidence of narcotics
dealing were found at the scene.
   But authorities said the slayings are believed to be
drug-related because they were done execution-style.
   The neighbor said residents of both units in the duplex where
the shooting occurred often went from one to the other. She said
they had lived there about a year and kept to themselves.
   The people in the unit adjacent to where the shooting took place
had children, the neighbor said. Seely refused comment on that
report as well.
</TEXT>
