<2ND_LINE>AM-Dead Crow,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen's Crow Confiscated And Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>APACHE JUNCTION, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State game officials confiscated
and killed a crow that was being kept illegally by a teen-ager who
nursed the animal back to health after it lost a wing.
   Arizona law prohibits keeping migratory birds as pets.
   Steve Luenz Jr., 13, was given the bird 2{ years ago by a
neighbor who said vacationers picked it up along the highway after
it collided with a tractor-trailer rig. Another family took the
bird to a veterinarian, who amputated a mangled wing.
   Luenz said game warden Dana McGehee told him in July the crow
would be confiscated and taken to the state Game and Fish
Department sanctuary at Adobe Mountain.
   ``He told us he would be taken care of out there and that we
could go out and see him whenever we wanted to,'' Luenz said.
   The bird was killed ``because we had no place to put it and it
couldn't be returned to the wild,'' said Robin Spahr, a worker at
the Adobe Mountain facility.
   McGehee was not available for comment Tuesday, but his
supervisor said it was unlikely McGehee would have made such a
statement.
   ``We don't have control over what they do with the animals,''
said McGehee's supervisor, Ray Kohls. ``I wasn't aware it was
killed.''
