<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 2011EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AssaultWeapons     09-20 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Assault Weapons,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Gun Group Says Semiautomatic and Automatic Assault Weapons on
Increase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The popularity of semiautomatic or automatic
assault weapons is increasing dramatically among criminals,
especially among those trafficking in illegal drugs, an anti-gun
group said Tuesday.
   The group said police officials across the country are concerned
about how frequently criminals are found to possess high-powered
automatic assault rifles or shotguns _ some capable of firing 30
rounds in a few seconds.
   ``The number of assault weapons in civilian hands _ both
criminal and law abiding _ is estimated to be in the hundreds of
thousands, perhaps millions,'' said a report by the Education Fund
to End Handgun Violence, which keeps track of the firearms industry
and favors tighter controls over the sale of guns.
   The group said there are no nationwide statistics available on
the misuse of such assault weapons, but that police organizations,
government agencies and pro-gun control groups agree the number of
such weapons has increased dramatically in recent years.
   Assault weapons are characterized by having the capability of
firing a large number of rounds on a single magazine, great muzzle
velocity and compact design often including folding stocks that
make it easier for the weapon to be concealed.
   The assault weapons ``are quickly becoming the leading topic in
America's gun control debate and will most likely remain the
leading gun control issue for the near future,'' the report said.
   It said automatic and semiautomatic weapons such as the AR-15,
AK-47 and Uzi are among the most popular weapons of drug dealers
and are readily available in most states.
   ``For criminals, the weapons look intimidating, have increased
firepower, and can be purchased under the same controls as a
hunting rifle or shotgun,'' the report said. It said the weapons
are popular not only among criminals, but also survivalists and
``rank-and-file gun aficionados.''
   While the group said no national statistics were available on
how many such weapons are in circulation, it said in 1987, almost
one-third of the weapons seized by the Drug Enforcement Agency were
semiautomatic and 16 percent were fully automatic.
   Of the 388 guns seized by the Washington D.C. police department
during the first six weeks of this year, ``the vast majority were
either semiautomatic or fully automatic,'' the report said.
   The study was conducted in conjunction with the New Right Watch,
a group which monitors right wing organizations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880920-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 2011EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-UN-Iran     09-20 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-UN-Iran,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Members Make Appeal to UN For Political Prisoners in Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One hundred members of Congress have signed an
appeal to U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar in an
effort to halt ``mass executions of political prisoners'' in Iran,
a spokesman said Tuesday.
   ``The dramatic increase in mass executions of political
prisoners and public hangings of innocent people in Iran, as
reported by the international press as well as the (opposition)
People's Mujahedeen of Iran, has shocked the world,'' the letter
said.
   It said the government of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini had
``extensively violated'' the Charter of the United Nations, the
Universal Declaration of Human Rights and the International
Covenants on Human Rights, staging 70,000 executions since 1981,
and that a further 140,000 lives were in danger.
   ``We urge you immediately do everything possible to halt the
continuing arrests and executions (and) to send a mission to
Iranian prisons and torture chambers to investigate these reports
... ,'' it added.
   A spokesman for Rep. Mervin Dymally, D-Calif., said 60
Democratic and 40 Republican House members had signed the appeal by
Tuesday afternoon but said that it was possible more would sign
before the letter was sent on Thursday.
