<1ST_LINE>u w AM-MOVE-Justice 1stLd-Writethru a0706 09-20 0724</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-MOVE-Justice, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0706,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Federal Indictments To Be Sought In 1985 Philadelphia
Confrontation</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 1 graf of reax from Philly mayor after 4th graf, It
was</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department announced Tuesday there
is insufficient evidence to seek indictments in the investigation
of action taken by Philadelphia city officials and police in the
1985 MOVE confrontation, which left 11 people dead and nearly two
square blocks in flames.
   The investigation examined whether the officials or police
violated the civil rights of those who died in the bombing and
ensuing fire, said Assistant Attorney General William Bradford
Reynolds.
   ``We ... just found insufficient evidence to go forward with an
indictment of anybody,'' Reynolds, head of the department's civil
rights division, said in an interview.
   It was the second time a criminal probe of Philadelphia Mayor
Wilson Goode and others in connection with the MOVE incident has
been concluded without indictments. A local grand jury in
Philadelphia earlier this year strongly criticized city officials
for their handling of the confrontation.
   Refraining from extensive comment, Goode said he was happy that
the investigation was over, adding: ``Two grand juries have fully
investigated this matter and have reached a point of no criminality
involved. For that I am pleased.''
   The local grand jury discounted assertions that police gunfire
in an alley behind the MOVE compound kept people from fleeing the
burning rowhouse and Reynolds said the federal probe also had
examined that aspect of the matter.
   In a three-paragraph statement announcing the end of the federal
probe, the department said no report will be issued by the fderal
grand jury in Philadelphia which has been looking into the matter
since April 1987.
   The panel based its inquiry on the work of an FBI investigation
launched in July 1985.
   ``It is a very positive thing ... to look forward rather than to
look back ... and it really serves no purpose to go back and
revisit and re-churn those waters,'' Reynolds said when asked why
the government had decided not to press for a grand jury report on
the matter. ``I feel quite strongly that the proper way for a
prosecutor to proceed is to make his or her decision,'' announce it
and ``nothing (is) to be served by any commentary after that.''
   Reynolds praised the FBI, said the statements of more than 250
witnesses had been carefully considered and that ``we are satisfied
... there is no basis for a criminal indictment based on our
thorough review of all the evidence.''
   Five children and six adults died inside the barricaded west
Philadelphia rowhouse on May 13, 1985, when police dropped a bomb
on the dwelling in an attempt to evict MOVE followers. Philadelphia
Mayor Wilson Goode approved the use of a bomb, which contained the
powerful military explosive C-4 and was dropped from a helicopter.
   The police bomb touched off a rooftop fire that soon raged out
of control while fireman held back, afraid they would be hit by
gunfire that had echoed through the neighborhood. The fire engulfed
almost two square blocks and destroyed 61 rowhouses.
   Members of the mysterious MOVE group, whose name did not stand
for anything in particular, championed back-to-nature rituals,
lived in filth, refused to send their children to school, and
openly disobeyed health and safety laws.
   Neighbors had complained to city officials and threatened to
take matters into their own hands if nothing was done about MOVE.
   An investigating commission said the group ``had evolved into an
authoritarian, violence-threatening cult.''
   Philadelphia District Attorney Ronald Castille said at the time
the local grand jury report came out that it ``laid to rest the
MOVE commission's finding and other allegations that police gunfire
prevented MOVE members from fleeing the burning compound'' through
the back alley.
   The local grand jury said it considered but discarded charges of
conspiracy, murder, involuntary manslaughter, aggravated assault,
reckless endangerment, arson, causing or risking a catastrophe,
failure to prevent a catastrophe, criminal mischief and perjury.
   Only two people escaped from the house _ a female MOVE member
known as Ramona Africa and then-13-year-old Michael Moses Ward,
known to MOVE members as Birdie Africa. All MOVE members adopted
the surname Africa and most of them were black.
   A Philadelphia policeman was killed in a 1978 confrontation with
MOVE members.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
