<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Europe     09-20 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Europe,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Official Concerned By Anti-Nuclear Sentiment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western opinion polls showing hostility toward
nuclear weapons and rising popularity for Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev present a challenge for NATO to better explain and sell
its basic defense policy, U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Rozanne
Ridgway said Tuesday.
   ``For all of these (NATO) countries, it means a requirement for
explaining defense policy and ... the approach to dealing with the
Soviet Union'' from a position of strength, she told a
Congressional hearing. ``Arms control negotiations to achieve a
proper defense at the lowest possible level require a very long and
elaborate public presentation.''
   Ms. Ridgway termed startling and a matter of concern the results
of an opinion survey two months ago by a leading European
newspaper, West Germany's Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung.
   Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., told the House subcommittee on
European and Middle Eastern Affairs that the poll showed Gorbachev
was popular with 70 percent of the West Germans questioned, that 79
percent opposed nuclear weapons in Europe and 51 percent rejected
the idea of nuclear deterrents.
   ``We are also seeing the results of other polls that were very
hostile,'' Ms. Ridgway said, adding that such sentiments seem not
limited to particular age groups. ``It creates problems for all of
us. Some of those attitudes are present in our own country,
probably in the same proportions,'' she said.
   Hamilton gave no information on the number polled or margin of
error in the July 22 opinion survey. He also said 68 percent of the
West Germans questioned opposed modernization of nuclear forces and
only 14 percent favored it, that ``mistrust of the Soviet Union has
almost vanished and there is growing acceptance in Germany of
Gorbachev's claims that Soviet military power is for defense rather
than offensive purposes.''
</TEXT>
