<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MayorSchools     09-20 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mayor Schools,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Advisory Panel Formed on School Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Raymond L. Flynn announced the formation of
an advisory panel Tuesday, a move School Committee members charge
is an attempt by City Hall to take over operation of the city's 120
public schools.
   The mayor denied the panel is a power play for control of the
system, which has come under criticism.
   The commission includes educators, business community leaders,
two city councilors, and state Higher Education Commissioner
Franklyn Jenifer. The panel will advise Flynn on such issues as
educational policy, a student assignment plan, teacher morale and
school governance, the mayor said.
   School Committee President John Nucci said the mayor, considered
a likely candidate for governor in 1990, is moving to take over the
schools and enhance his image for a possible gubernatorial bid.
   ``I don't think anyone should kid themselves into thinking this
isn't politically motivated,'' Nucci said. ``The mayor is looking
to a governor's campaign, and he would like to crisscross the state
and say he did something about schools.''
   The mayor denied the accusation.
   ``I don't think there's anybody in the city of Boston who's
satisfied with the level of the education,'' Flynn said. ``Public
education is not the domain of the school committee or the
superintendent of schools alone, it's a city problem. ... We all
have a vested interest in public education in Boston.''
   Committee member Juanita Wade, who has been invited to sit on
the panel, said public concerns that the school system is not doing
all it can to improve education are not new, ``So this blue-ribbon
panel is not sending any different message than isn't out there
already,'' she said.
</TEXT>
