<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HotTrick     09-20 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hot Trick,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Magic Trick Nearly Brings Down The House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Notre Dame instructor says he will
continue using his flaming-hand magic trick as an audience
attention-grabber even though he set a small blaze in a classroom.
   ``When was the last time you set your audience on fire?''
adjunct professor G. Herb True joked Tuesday.
   No one was hurt in the incident Monday in a classroom at the
University of Notre Dame Center for Continuing Education.
   He was giving a seminar to a group from the American Amusement
and Music Operators Association when, to liven things up, he used
his magic skills to produce a small ball of fire in the palm of his
hand.
   Someone distracted his attention, his hand got burned and he
accidently hit a flip chart. The pages caught fire, and flames
reached the ceiling before the fire was extinguished.
   Aside from a small area of burned carpet and a light film of
smoke inside the building, there was no damage, said Michael
Garvey, assistant director for public information.
   ``I have a number of magic tricks,'' True said in a telephone
interview. ``And I have this thing that I flip with my finger and
this flame comes out of my hand. At least it looks like it.
   ``It wasn't much of a fire, really. But a guy comes in and tries
to put it out and he starts fanning the flames.''
   The fire was finally put out with the aid of a pitcher of water
and a fire extinguisher.
   True said he plans to do the trick twice Wednesday at seminars
in Indianapolis.
</TEXT>
