<HEAD>Honduras Deports American Priest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN PEDRO SULA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic priest who was
arrested on suspicion of distributing subversive literature was
deported to the United States, police sources said Tuesday.
   The Rev. Albert Reymann, 70, who had worked in Honduras for
seven years, left for Miami on Monday following his arrest Sept. 14.
   ``I am being watched since they arrested me illegally and I
don't want any other problems,'' newspapers quoted Reymann as
telling reporters at the airport.
   Reymann said military authorities had told him not to make any
public statements. He gave a victory sign before boarding a
commercial flight to Miami, newspapers said.
   Honduran authorities held the Maryknoll priest for 10 hours
before releasing him to the bishop of San Pedro Sula. He was kept
under house arrest. No details on the charges against him were
given.
   Sources said Reymann was arrested as he left a union meeting in
San Pedro Sula, but no other details were available.
   The sources said his case is not related to the arrest of 16
Americans in Honduras following protests Sept. 14 in front of the
U.S. Embassy in Tegucigalpa and the U.S. air base in Palmerola. The
protesters were demonstrating against U.S. military policy in
Central America and were deported last Saturday.
   The protests were organized by a group called Project
Independence and held one day before Central American countries
celebrate the anniversary of their independence from Spain in 1821.
