<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Pearson     09-20 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Pearson,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stanford Classics Professor Emeritus, Guggenheim Fellow Dies At 80</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lionel I.C. Pearson, a classical scholar
who won a prestigious Guggenheim fellowship and wrote more than a
dozen books, has died of pancreatic cancer. He was 80.
   Pearson, professor emeritus of classics at Stanford University,
died Sunday at Sharon Heights Convalescent Hospital in Menlo Park.
   He was a graduate of Trinity College, Oxford, and Yale
University and taught at Stanford from 1940 to 1973, except for a
three-year stint with the British Army Intelligence Corps ending in
1946.
   Pearson, working with colleagues, had just completed his latest
book, ``Aristoxenus: The Elements of Harmony,'' a discussion of
ancient Greek music theory to be published by Oxford University
Press.
   ``He was among the most distinguished scholars our department
ever had,'' said professor Mark Edwards. ``His life was devoted to
the service of classics in the widest sense: teaching, research and
support of his fellow classicists.''
   Born in London, Pearson taught Greek and classics at the
University of Glasgow, Dalhousie University, Yale and the New York
State College of Teachers before moving to Stanford.
   He was named a Guggenheim fellow in 1957-58.
   Among his recent books were ``The Greek Historians of the West:
Timaeus and His Predecessors,'' published last year; ``The
Commentary of Didymus on Demosthenes,'' published in 1983 by
Teubner Press, West Germany; and ``The Art of Demosthenes,''
published by the American Philological Association in 1976.
   Pearson also wrote ``Plutarch: On the Malice of Herodotus,''
``Popular Ethics in Ancient Greece'' and ``The Lost Histories of
Alexander The Great.''
   Survivors include his brother, Michael, and two sisters, Madge
McKee and Clair Pearson, all of England. Pearson's wife, Doris, was
killed in a car accident in 1964. They had no children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
