<DOCNO> AP880920-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 2039EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CancerFamily     09-20 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cancer Family,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cancer Survivor Becomes Lawyer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who recovered from a brain tumor and the
amputation of his leg following a battle with the cancer that
claimed the lives of all his male family members was sworn in to
the Florida bar Tuesday.
   Stephen Southerland, 28, stood on one leg and metal crutches,
smiling proudly as he recited the oath of admission before U.S.
District Judge Eugene P. Spellman.
   ``I am proud to welcome you as a member of the legal
fraternity,'' Spellman said, stepping down from the bench to shake
the jubilant Southerland's hand.
   An apparent genetic defect is responsible for the cancer that
has followed the Southerlands for at least four generations, the
family's physician, Dr. Beatrice Lampkin, said earlier this year.
   Southerland's brother Jeffrey died of leukemia in 1967 at age 4.
His father, Raymond Southerland, 43, died of a brain tumor in 1981,
and his brother Michael, 16, died of a rare spinal cancer later
that year. The only other family survivor is his mother, Jane
Southerland-McMillen.
   Southerland was hopeful he had the cancer beat after his left
leg was amputated in 1974. He dreamed of becoming a lawyer and
began studying for the bar exam in 1986.
   Then he suffered a seizure and collapsed during a softball game.
Doctors found a golfball-sized malignant brain tumor lodged deep in
the left side of his brain and decided to operate.
   ``It was the best excuse in the world not to take a bar exam,''
he joked at the time.
   The operation removed any trace of cancer, doctors told him.
Southerland began working full time at a Miami law firm and lifting
weights three times a week to regain his strength. He took the bar
exam in Tampa on July 26 and 27.
   ``At 9:30 on Monday, I learned I passed the bar,'' Southerland
said after his swearing-in. ``A friend of mine who's a clerk at the
Supreme Court called me to tell me.''
   Handling his crutches with ease, Southerland hugged his mother
and his stepfather and thanked the small crowd of friends for their
support over the years.
   The judge, who like Southerland is a University of Florida
graduate, said he was impressed by Southerland's courage when they
met at a Christmas party last year. He promised then to officiate
at Southerland's swearing-in if he passed the bar.
   Southerland said his plans to practice civil law have put his
social life on the back burner.
   ``Right now all I'm concentrating on is my law career,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
