<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-GeneralAssembly 1stLd-Writethru a0717 09-20 0730</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-General Assembly, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0717,0748</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Argentine Named Assembly President, Denounces Third World Debt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with new president's speech.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Dante M. Caputo of
Argentina was elected president of the 43rd General Assembly
Tuesday and promptly denounced developed nations for their
``pitiless system'' of piling up Third World debt.
   Caputo was swiftly elected after the 159-nation world body
convened in a mood of optimism and conciliation over many
international issues, despite the bitter presidential contest
between Caputo and Barbados' ambassador to the U.N., Dame Nita
Barrow.
   In his inaugural speech, Caputo set the tone for his yearlong
presidency of the world body which is dominated by poor, developing
nations and distanced himself from much of the industrialized West.
   Caputo cited ``the contrast between political peace and economic
injustice ... the widening of the gap between rich countries and a
large part of the developing world.''
   The 47-year-old former professor and politician was elected by a
vote of 91 to 66, with one abstention in secret balloting by 158
nations. South Africa, the 159th member, is disqualified from
voting. The abstaining nation was not identified.
   The post is largely ceremonial but the president has great
prestige and can wield considerable influence in setting agendas,
limiting speeches and setting the tone for debate.
   Caputo's election was a major setback for Britain, which lobbied
against him and for Dame Nita. Britain and Argentina were foes in
the Falklands War of 1982 _ won by Britain _ and the General
Assembly consistently has taken Argentina's side.
   The race was expected to be close, but Caputo won handily over
the 71-year-old nurse and public health expert who became the
Barbados envoy in 1986.
   The United States did not disclose its secret vote.
   Diplomatic sources said Caputo, who had been courting black
Africa, won many votes in the non-aligned movement. He also won
votes of the Soviet Union and socialist countries; Cuba; Japan;
Arab nations, which need Argentine food, and some European nations
which have emigrant ties to Argentina, the sources said.
   Caputo, named foreign minister in 1983 by President Raul
Alfonsin, last month expelled South Africa's consul for organizing
a conference in Argentina without proper diplomatic clearance.
   In his speech after Tuesday's election, Caputo praised the
improved atmosphere for international cooperation betwen East and
West.
   Caputo cited U.N. achievements in the Iran-Iraq cease-fire,
Afghanistan settlement, Western Sahara and other areas. He also
denounced the continuing ``infamous practice of apartheid in South
Africa,'' refering to that country's policy of racial segregation.
   He pointed to the ``sharp deterioration of the situation'' in
Israeli-occupied territories. He called for an international peace
conference on the Middle East and supported the right of all states
in the region to exist within safe boundaries and the right of the
Palestinian people to self-determination.
   But he reserved his strongest comments to condemn the economic
gap between the industrialized and the developing world.
   Caputo noted ``the remarkable difference between all the
progress made toward ensuring world peace and the little, or
nothing we have done to prevent the widening of the gap between
rich countries, and a large part of the developing world.''
   He said one of the clearest examples ``of this impotence is the
question of the external debt of the developing countries: No
structural improvement has taken place for the debtors since the
outbreak of the the crisis in 1982.''
   The Argentine envoy warned that high interst rates, ``together
with the pitiless system of successive refinancing plans, and the
perverse outflow of financial resources of indebted countries to
credtors will end up eliminatng possibilities of investment for the
developing world.''
   Argentina has a foreign debt of $56 billion, the third highest
in the developing world.
   Of the three sources of global conflict _ East-West tension,
regional conflicts and the ``unfair relationship between North and
South'' _ a major U.N. effort must be directed toward helping the
developing world, Caputo said.
   He said Northern nations ensured their own wealth by imposing
poverty on developing nations, but emphasized that the
industrialized nations need the development of other nations to
consolidate their own progress.
   ``They need it,'' he said, ``because development guarantees
peace in the Third World and global security and because expansion
of trade of developed countries will depend increasingly on growth
of economies of the South.''
</TEXT>
