<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Greece 1stLd-Writethru a0713 09-20 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Greece, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0713,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meeting Could Lead to Resumption of Base Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 6 grafs to end to UPDATE with State Dept comments on
bases in Turkey, Cyprus, Iraqi use of poison gas</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Resumption of suspended negotiations on the
future of U.S. military bases in Greece could depend on the Greek
foreign minister's planned talks here Wednesday with Secretary of
State George Shultz, a senior Shultz aide said Tuesday.
   Foreign Minister Carolas Papoulias is scheduled to meet and have
lunch with Shultz in his capacity as current representative of the
European Common Market, but U.S.-Greek relations also will be
covered, Assistant Secretary of State Rozanne Ridgway told a
congressional panel.
   Negotiations in Athens on American military bases were suspended
Sept. 5 when Ambassador Alan Flanigan, the U.S. negotiator,
returned to Washington for instructions on a ``major element'' in
the Greek position. That was identified as a demand for U.S. forces
to vacate Hellenikon air base at Athens International Airport, Ms.
Ridgway said.
   Resumption was tentatively scheduled for October, but the date
is undecided and ``whether it takes place'' depends partly on talks
with Papoulias, she told the House Foreign Affairs subcommittee on
European and Middle Eastern Affairs.
   ``The disposition of Hellenikon will have to be resolved ... how
it is going to be dealt with affects the whole negotiations,'' she
said.
   Ms. Ridgway did not disclose the U.S. response to the demand for
its planes to leave Hellenikon. She said in answer to a question
that if agreement cannot be reached, ``we have procedures for
leaving'' but ``we are not at any stage of starting that at this
time.''
   Subcommittee Chairman Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., asked if the illness
of Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou, reported to be facing heart
surgery, would affect the base negotiations. The Greek government
has said repeatedly that foreign policy is unaffected by
Papandreou's illness and officials have been instructed to carry on
their functions, Ms. Ridgway replied.
   As to whether the base negotiations would be completed before
parliamentary elections, she said this was uncertain because
setting of the election date is linked to the prime minister's
health.
   Ms. Ridgway was also asked about the status of U.S. military
bases in Turkey, covered by an agreement that runs into 1990.
   ``We are prepared to negotiate with Turkey on the renewal of
that agreement in good order,'' she said. ``I think it is a good
agreement. We are happy with it, Turkey is happy with it as far as
I know.''
   Ms. Ridgway praised the rival Greek Cypriot and Turkish Cypriot
leaders for meeting in Geneva and Nicosia under U.N. auspices in
August and September and agreeing to meet again.
   ``We continue to support strongly a negotiated settlement of the
Cyprus problem,'' she said, declaring that U.N. Secretary General
Javier Perez de Cuellar ``enjoys our full support.''
   Asked to explain what members of Congress termed ``conflicting
U.S. and Turkish reports'' about Iraqi use of poison gas against
the Kurdish minority in Iraq, Ms. Ridgway said most of the Kurds
who managed to reach Turkey were those who escaped the attacks,
while the U.S. findings were based partly on evidence not available
to Turkey.
   Asked if Turkey were barring U.N. experts from investigating the
issue, she said the whole matter was under discussion and not yet
resolved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
