<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scattered Rain Falls In East; Cool Weather In Nation's Midsection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers were scattered across much of the eastern part of the
nation Tuesday and in parts of the Rockies as well.
   Showers, combined with a few thunderstorms, were scattered along
a warm front crossing western New England, and along a cold front
crossing the upper Ohio Valley. Cloudy skies and widely scattered
showers prevailed in the rest of the area from south-central Texas
across the central Gulf Coast states to the Atlantic Coast.
   In the West, a slow-moving cold front produced a few showers in
the Great Basin of Nevada and western Utah and the central Rockies,
and an upper-level disturbance brought a few showers to the
southern Rockies.
   Heavier rain totals for the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included
0.48 inch at Morgantown, W.Va.; 0.40 inch at Pittsburgh and at
Watertown, N.Y.; 0.32 inch at Pensacola, Fla.; and 0.30 inch at Du
Bois, Pa.
   Strong northwest winds continued to usher cool air into the Ohio
Valley, the Great Lakes region and the middle and upper Mississippi
Valley, while brisk southerly winds prevailed ahead of a cold
front, from New England to North Carolina.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 40
degrees at Cutbank, Mont., to 95 degrees at Phoenix. The
early-morning low for the nation Tuesday was 15 degrees at
Gunnison, Colo.
   The national forecast for Wednesday called for widely scattered
showers and thunderstorms across a far-flung area from the central
and eastern Gulf Coast to the southern Atlantic Coast to eastern
New York state and New England. Widely scattered showers also were
forecast across the northern Plains and from the Great Basin across
Arizona and southwestern new Mexico.
   Highs in the 90s were forecast in Florida and much of the
southern Plains and lower Mississippi Valley; in the 80s in the
central Plains to the southern and middle Atlantic Coast; in the
60s from Upper Michigan to eastern Montana, the northern Plateau,
the Great Basin and the northern and central Rockies; and in the
70s across most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
