<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PresidentialPoll     09-20 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Presidential Poll,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Still Unknown Among Voters, Survey Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis is still unknown to many voters despite more than a year of
campaigning, says an ABC News-Washington Post poll released Tuesday.
   The survey, which gave Republican George Bush a 50 percent to 46
percent lead over Dukakis, said 54 percent of the respondents
thought they did not know enough about Dukakis. That compared with
70 percent who said they think the vice president is a known
quantity.
   The survey of 1,271 likely voters, begun a week ago and
concluded Monday, also found that Bush was favored over Dukakis
among voters who consider themselves independents. The survey had a
margin of error of plus or minus three points.
   The survey also examined which issues were important to voters
and how strong they considered each candidate on those issues.
   According to the survey, six out of ten respondents considered
holding down taxes to be a very important issue, and of that group
54 percent thought Bush would do a better job while 43 percent
thought Dukakis would.
   Of the two-thirds of the respondents who thought preserving
American family values to be a ``cutting edge'' issue, 52 percent
supported Bush and 44 percent supported Dukakis.
   But on the issue of creating new jobs, which two-thirds found
important, Dukakis was favored over Bush 53 percent to 43 percent.
   Neither candidate led on fighting drugs and crime, holding down
the deficit and protecting the environment. Bush was ahead among
voters who were concerned about issues such as the Pledge of
Allegiance, the Strategic Defense Initiative and anti-abortion
legislation, while Dukakis was favored by those who consider
college aid and child care to be important issues.
   A week ago, an ABC News-Washington Post poll gave Dukakis a
48-45 lead. That survey also had a three-point margin of error.
</TEXT>
