<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0675,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: At Least 62 Killed In Rebel Rocket Attack in Afghanistan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs with eight grafs to UPDATE with Soviet
report of capture of rebel arsenal; PICKS up 8th pvs: Moslem
guerrillas...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghanistan rebels fired a rocket
into Kabul on Tuesday that killed at least 62 people and injured
104, Radio Kabul said.
   In Moscow, the official Soviet news agency Tass said two
terrorists preparing a bomb for an act of sabotage in another
Afghan city were killed when the device exploded. A 9-year-old girl
also died in the explosion, it said.
   ``As a result of the attack (on Kabul) 62 innocent people,
including women and children, were killed and 104 were wounded,''
Radio Kabul said in a report monitored in Islamabad. It gave few
other details.
   The report tended to reinforce claims by Western sources that
U.S.-backed Moslem insurgents have surrounded the heavily-fortified
Afghan capital, attacking government and Soviet-held positions.
   In another report Tuesday, Radio Kabul said 10 people were
killed when six surface rockets ``launched by extremist opposition
elements'' slammed into various parts of Kabul. It was not
immediately clear whether the 10 fatalities were included among the
62 reported killed.
   The report said since the April 14 signing in Geneva of an
accord providing for the withdrawal of Soviet troops from
Afghanistan, anti-communist rebels have rocketed the city 16 times.
The 16th attack occurred Tuesday, it said.
   Tass also reported Tuesday that Afghan soldiers captured 14
caches of arms near Kabul that contained more than 700
surface-to-air missiles.
   Afghan soldiers moved into Lalnadar Gorge, about 12 miles south
of Kabul, after they received intelligence about the arms supplies
hidden there, Tass said.
   Two battalions of Afghan soldiers, supported by Soviet
artillery, cut off roads leading out of the gorge, but most of the
rebels escaped via mountain paths, it said.
   ``In all, Afghan troops discovered 14 depots containing 724
surface-to-air missiles, 132 anti-tank and 280 anti-personnel
mines, U.S.-made remote-control explosive devices and other
weapons,'' Tass said.
   Also discovered were submachine guns, grenades, bazookas, and an
anti-aircraft gun on a rotating platform, it said.
   It said the rebels launched missiles at Kabul from a nearby
mountain ridge, and then scattered because of retaliatory strikes
that usually followed. It was not clear if the attack reported by
Tass was the same offensive reported Tuesday by Radio Kabul.
   Tass also did not say when the weapons were captured from the
insurgents, who are seeking to oust the Soviet-backed government of
President Najib.
   Tass quoted the Afghan news agency Bakhtar as saying the
accidental bombing occurred in the Khushkhal Mena district of Kabul
but did not say when. It did not say whether the terrorists were
aligned with anti-communist rebels.
   Moslem guerrillas have been fighting the ruling communists in
Afghanistan since they seized power in a 1978 military coup. Soviet
forces entered the conflict to back the Kabul government in late
1979.
   Under this year's Geneva agreement, all of the estimated 100,000
Red Army troops are to leave the country by Feb. 15.
</TEXT>
