<1ST_LINE>r w AM-IMFMeeting     09-20 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IMF Meeting,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Forsees No Changes in International Economic Policies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The annual gathering of finance ministers and
other economic officials at the World Bank and International
Monetary Fund beginning this week in Berlin is unlikely to produce
a major change in world economic policies, according to a senior
Treasury Department official.
   ``The world economy ... is in the best shape that we've seen for
a very considerable period of time,'' said the official on Tuesday,
adding that American policy will continue steady during President
Reagan's final months in office.
   ``Our principal objectives will be to assure our partners of the
continued U.S. commitment to and support for the economic policy
coordination process and the debt strategy,'' said the official. He
said U.S. officials also would try ``to build on the considerable
progress being achieved in promoting a sound world economy and a
stable financial system.''
   The Berlin meeting will be the first opportunity for new
Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady to get acquainted with his
foreign counterparts, the official noted. Brady was confirmed as
secretary earlier this month to replace James Baker, who resigned
to head George Bush's presidential campaign.
   ``Inflation remains moderate and while continued vigilance is
needed on that front, there is no evidence of generalized price
pressures emerging,'' the official said.
   He said ``external imbalances,'' like the U.S. trade deficit and
the Japanese trade surplus, ``are coming down, more quickly in fact
than many people projected, as the latest U.S. trade figures have
recently confirmed.''
   He said economic growth in the major industrial countries this
year will be approximately 4 percent, with continued expansion next
year.
   During the Berlin meeting, the wealthiest countries, known as
the Group of Seven or G-7, plan to review their coordinated
approach to the world economy to see if it can be strengthened, the
official said.
   ``We expect the participants of that meeting to reaffirm the
policy directions that have been adopted, including the
understanding on exchange market cooperation,'' the official said.
   In recent years the G-7 countries have worked together to lower
the value of the U.S. dollar and raise the West German deutsche
Mark and Japanese yen on exchange markets.
   This has lowered the price of U.S. exports and made them more
competitive in the world market, helping to narrow the difference
between what the amount of goods and services the United States
exports and imports.
   The official said the U.S. government continues to stand by its
approach to easing the Third World debt burden as fundamentally
sound and believes ``that significant progress has been and is
being achieved.''
   The approach, outlined in 1985 by Baker, called on commercial
banks and international lending agencies to increase loans by $29
billion to the poorest 15 countries of the world in exchange for
moves by those countries toward free-market economies.
   Lending by the commercial banks, however, has fallen $20 billion
short of what the Baker plan envisioned. This has prompted other
countries, most notably France and Japan, to suggest alternatives.
   The official said ``debt-for-equity'' swaps used by some Latin
American countries to reduce their indebtedness showed promise.
Under the procedure, governments grant commercial banks shares in
government-owned businesses in exchange for forgiveness of the
government debt to the banks.
   ``Debt-equity swaps have totaled $9 billion dollars by our
estimate in the last 18 months or two years,'' said the official.
``There's room for substantially more activity of this kind if
various debtor countries would further open their markets and
remove foreign-investment restrictions.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
