<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cambodia-Sihanouk     09-20 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia-Sihanouk,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sihanouk Calls For Peace Conference In France</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodian rebel leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk said
Tuesday he would ask the French government to help him organize an
international conference on Cambodia ``as soon as possible.''
   Sihanouk, who arrived in Paris from Beijing, said he would
discuss the possibility of holding such a conference in France when
he meets President Francois Mitterrand on Friday.
   The prince, considered the key figure in a settlement to the
Cambodian civil war, told reporters he and Cambodian Premier Hun
Sen planned to hold talks in Paris starting Nov. 5.
   He said he has invited the two other leaders of the Cambodian
resistance _ Khieu Samphan, head of the Communist Khmer Rouge, and
Son Sann, leader of a second resistance faction _ to participate in
the November meetings.
   Sihanouk's followers and the two groups form a resistance
coalition whose aim is to remove Vietnamese troops from Cambodia
and dismantle Hun Sen's government.
   ``There is a turning point now,'' Sihanouk said, adding that an
international conference on Cambodia should be held ``as soon as
possible.'' He did not elaborate.
   The four parties involved in the Cambodian civil war _ the three
resistance groups and Cambodia's Vietnamese-installed government _
met for the first time in July in Jakarta, Indonesia. Sihanouk did
not participate.
   Sihanouk and Cambodian Premier Hun Sen planned the Jakarta talks
at two meetings in Paris in December and January.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978 to end the three-year
reign of terror by Pol Pot, the Khmer Rouge chief. Vietnam has
promised to withdraw its troops by the end of 1990.
   Sihanouk said Tuesday he would insist that any Cambodian peace
accord include a provision for the respect fo human rights.
   Sihanouk in the past has accused his Khmer Rouge coalition
partners of killing members of his Sihanoukist National Army, and
on Tuesday claimed they recently sank 15 boats filled with food for
his men.
</TEXT>
