<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 1953EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama     09-20 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Controls Pacific Port; Strike Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The port of Balboa was under military control
Tuesday as 750 port workers kept up a strike begun last week to
demand payment of annual bonuses. They were joined this week by
government employees with the same demand.
   Military sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Defense Forces personnel are protecting Balboa, the Pacific Coast
port of the Panama Canal. They said Vacamonte port police have
taken control of that small fishing port, 30 miles from Balboa.
   Vacamonte workers are not on strike.
   Balboa workers went on indefinite strike Sept. 12, demanding the
annual bonus that was due in August.
   On Monday, the 75,000-member National Federation of Public
Employees said they would join the strike for 48 hours.
   Federation undersecretary Jose Sanchez said workers at 80
percent of the government institutions were taking part. About half
of those who collect taxes and utility payments continue to work to
make sure the government will have the revenues needed to pay them.
   Employees at several government institutions told The Associated
Press some people were working and some were not. The government
maintains public employees do not have a right to strike.
   Sanchez said many striking public employees reported to work but
did not perform their duties.
   In Panama City, private businesses operated normally.
   Schools, closed by the government Monday, were in session
Tuesday.
   The 15,000-member Defense Forces, the country's armed forces,
said in a statement it ``will guarantee that public service
continues normally.
   ``Units of the police force offered to provide necessary
vigilance to ensure that every state dependency, public service and
the public in general have the necessary protection to carry out
their functions,'' the statement said.
   Sanchez said he was trying to gain the release of five Balboa
labor leaders arrested over the weekend.
   Besides demanding bonus payments, federation members also asked
that the government be restructured, accusing it of administrative
corruption.
   The pro-government newspaper El Diario Matutino said Tuesday
that sectors of the federation rushed into ``an adventure'' by
starting a strike that ``did not reach the level they expected.''
   ``Many of the official institutions operated on time and with
full personnel. Others worked partially,'' it said.
   Another Panama City daily, La Estrella de Panama, said the
strikes ``are counterproductive at a time when the country faces
the worst economic crisis in its history and is confronted by the
implacable aggression of the most powerful nation in the world.''
   The United States has been trying to force Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega to quit as Defense Forces chief, a post that makes him
Panama's de facto leader. Noriega is under U.S. indictment on drug
trafficking charges. Among the pressures Washington applied were
economic sanctions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
