<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GangRape     09-20 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gang Rape,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness in Rape Trial Says Men at Cockfight Acted ``Like Dogs''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents, especially 10th graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Men gathered at a cockfight acted ``like
dogs'' during the gang rape of a woman near this southern Texas
town, a witness facing charges testified Tuesday.
   It was the first day of testimony in the trial of Orlando Garza,
23, who is among 10 men charged in the kidnapping and sexual
assault of a 19-year-old woman. All 10 men have entered innocent
pleas.
   Garza is the first defendant to go on trial in the case. In
addition to the 10 adults, a 14-year-old also has been charged.
   Jose Carlos Briones, one of the men facing charges in the case,
testified Tuesday that when he first saw Garza with the woman in a
car near a shed where the cockfight was being held, she and Garza
``were necking.''
   Briones said the woman later began offering resistance and that
many of the 20 or more men present sexually assaulted the woman on
the hood of Garza's car while other men held her arms and legs.
   ``They were just like dogs,'' said Briones, who was offered
probation in exchange for his testimony.
   Garza is charged with sexually assaulting the woman, and also
faces a kidnapping trial in connection with the case.
   Under state law, sexual assault is punishable by 2 to 20 years
in prison and or fine of up $10,000.
   Briones, who also was charged with sexually assaulting the
woman, said he fondled her, but denied raping her.
   He said the woman was groaning and crying while the men had sex
with her. Briones said he remembered seeing the woman being forced
to perform oral sex on Garza.
   Asked how many men assaulted the woman, he testified, ``I don't
remember because there were a whole bunch of them.''
   Under questioning by defense attorney Albert Pena, Briones said
the woman was not resisting Garza while she and Garza were in the
back seat of the car. Pena, in attacking the credibility of the
witness, also produced a court-ordered competency report produced
in June. In the report, Corpus Christi psychiatrist Laurence Taylor
wrote that Briones told him, ``She was lying there letting
everybody do it. She loved it _ no screaming from her. She was a
run-around.''
   Briones also told the psychiatrist that on March 26, the day he
said the rape took place, he had consumed a case of beer, according
to the report.
   Briones said Tuesday he did not remember telling Taylor the
woman participated voluntarily, and also said he did not remember
being promised probation in exchange for testimony.
   Assistant District Attorney Rodolfo Gutierrez said that he would
recommend probation for Briones in exchange for the testimony.
   Before testimony began Tuesday, the prosecutor apologized to the
jury in advance for sexually explicit language they would hear in
the trial.
   ``You will be hearing some language that is not dinner-table
conversation that may offend you,'' he told the jury of six men and
six women in the Duval County District Court.
   Gutierrez said the prosecution may take until Friday to present
its case. Witnesses he has said will testify include the victim and
a 12-year-old boy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
