<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 2114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-People-Warner-Wilding     09-20 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Warner-Wilding,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Passes Bill Sponsored by Warner for Ex-Wife Elizabeth
Taylor's Son</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Tuesday passed a bill by
Elizabeth Taylor's sixth husband on behalf of her second husband's
son, actor Michael Wilding, who was facing possible deportation
because of a drug conviction.
   The private relief bill by Sen. John Warner, R-Va., would exempt
Wilding, the 34-year-old son of Miss Taylor and the late British
actor, Michael Wilding, from a law prohibiting permanent resident
visas for people convicted of drug violations.
   Wilding, now living in New York City and employed as an actor on
the television soap opera ``The Guiding Light,'' was convicted in
Wales in 1974, three years after he had renounced his U.S.
citizenship, of possessing marijuana and cultivating marijuana
plants in a house that he and six others shared.
   He returned to the United States in 1981. But because of the
conviction, the Immigration and Naturalization Service has refused
to grant him a permanent resident visa.
   Warner said the INS has taken no definite steps to expel Wilding
but said the actor's attorneys anticipate the government will
commence deportation proceedings in the near future.
   ``So far as I know, and his mother knows, Mr. Wilding has lived
a drug-free, law-abiding existence since the occurrence of the
offenses during his very early life,'' Warner said in a letter to
the Senate Judiciary Committee.
   The bill, which still has to be acted upon by the House, was
approved by the Senate on a unanimous consent vote without
objection.
   ``My knowledge and respect for this man developed during my
marriage to his mother, Elizabeth Taylor,'' Warner said.
   Warner and the actress were married at his northern Virginia
estate on Dec. 4, 1976, and they were granted a no-fault divorce
Nov. 5, 1982, following a 14-month separation.
   ``I was his stepfather during that five-year period,'' when the
couple was together, Warner said. ``I can attest from my personal
knowledge, and that of his mother, that Mr. Wilding would continue
to be a law-abiding resident of the United States.''
   Wilding was married for the second time in 1982. He has a
16-year-old daughter who lives with his first wife in Portland,
Ore., and he has a 13-year-old daughter, born out of wedlock, who
lives in Wales.
   Miss Taylor's other husbands were Richard Burton, whom she
married twice, Nicky Hilton, Eddie Fisher and Michael Todd.
</TEXT>
