<1ST_LINE>x f NYBiz:ThisalsomovingA-wire     09-20 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>NY Biz: This also moving A-wire</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AM-CFTC-Chilmark,280</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A futures trading firm with 17 offices in
Florida, California, New York and Michigan has agreed to shut down
its operations as part of its settlement of fraud charges leveled
by the Commodity Futures Trading Corp.
   Chilmark Commodities Corp., without admitting or denying the
allegations, agreed to the revocation of its registration as a
broker. It also consented to an injunction barring it from ``fraud
in connection with soliciting customers to trade commodity options
on futures contracts,'' the CFTC said in a release Tuesday.
   The commission also charged Chilmark with unauthorized trading
and with failing to provide customers with the price of the option
prior to purchase.
   The consent order of permanent injunction was approved Sept. 15
by the U.S. District Court for the Southern District of Florida.
Simultaneously, an administrative complaint by the commission was
settled.
   Chilmark, founded in 1985, was a medium-sized firm operating in
New York City, but began expanding rapidly in 1986, opening seven
offices in southern Florida. By 1987, it had 250 sales brokers and
took in more than $13 million in commissions.
   The CFTC accused Chilmark of ``high pressure sales tactics
typical of a boiler room operation'' and of ``routinely (making)
false or deceptive statements in soliciting customers.''
   The complaint ``described a sales operation where the paramount
goal was to maximize commission income by maximizing the number of
options purchased by customers and misrepresenting the profit
potential,'' the agency said.
   Most of Chilmark's customers spent 40 percent to 60 percent of
their investment on commissions, it said.
   Chilmark officials could not be reached for comment at their New
York headquarters early Tuesday evening.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880920-0212 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 2115EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-SubwayFire     09-20 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Subway Fire,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>2nd Blaze In 3 Days Near Subway Station Where 31 Died Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire in a tunnel Tuesday night delayed subway
services at King's Cross station, the London fire service reported.
It was the second fire in the same spot in three days, but no
injures were reported in either blaze.
   On Nov. 18 last year, 31 people died and 80 were injured when
fire broke out under an escalator at King's Cross, the London
subway system's busiest station.
   The fire service said in a statement that in Tuesday's incident,
trash that had accumulated in the tunnel beween King's Cross and
Euston, the next subway station down the line, caught fire but was
quickly extinguished.
   It said that on Saturday, services were briefly disrupted after
a small fire broke out at the same spot. That fire burned itself
out before emergency crews arrived to tackle it.
   The statement did not say what was thought to have caused the
fires on Tuesday and Saturday.
   Investigators believe the Nov. 18 fire was started when a
lighted cigarette was dropped on a wooden escalator surrounded by
grease-soaked trash. The fire raced up the escalator and a ball of
flame exploded in the ticket lobby.
   Smoking has been banned throughout the subway system following
the Nov. 18 fire. But an independent inquiry into that fire
expressed concern last June at the end of a 91-day hearing that
senior managers of London Regional Transport, the public
corporation that runs the subway, might not accept the lessons of
that disaster.
   The inquiry's chief counsel, Roger Henderson, accused senior
managers of seeking to shirk responsibility for the fire. The
managers defended existing safety procedures but during the inquiry
announced a package of 101 new safety measures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
