<HEAD>Philadelphia Lets Ethnic Flags Fly Again</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5th graf to CORRECT spelling of Champs Elysees.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The flags of Armenia, the Ukraine, Wales,
Scotland and Puerto Rico will be returned to flagpoles lining a
downtown boulevard in an effort to end a dispute with several
ethnic groups, a city official said.
   A Latvian flag, removed for repairs, also will be restored to
the Benjamin Franklin Parkway, said city representative Gerri
Walker, who oversees Mayor W. Wilson Goode's protocol office.
   Several flags were removed over the summer when city officials
decided to adopt U.S. recognition of a government as the standard
by which nations' flags should fly.
   The Baltic nations of Latvia, Lithuania and Estonia are regarded
as republics in exile, even though they have been absorbed by the
Soviet Union. Lithuanian and Estonian flags are already in place.
   The tree-lined parkway modeled after the Champs Elysees in Paris
has been decorated with more than 70 flags every summer since the
bicentennial celebrations of 1976.
   ``But there have been constant questions about why some flags
were there and some weren't,'' Ms. Walker said.
   About 60 people of Armenian, Ukrainian and Latvian descent
rallied Sept. 2 outside City Hall to protest the removal of their
homelands' banners.
   Ms. Walker said the flags will fly until late autumn, when all
flags are taken down to protect them from winter storms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880920-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 2211EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-Earthquake     09-20 0135</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Earthquake,0139</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strong Quake Rattles Northern Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake rocked the Pacific coastal area
on Japan's northernmost island of Hokkaido Wednesday, the Central
Meteorological Agency said.
   Local police said they had no reports of damage or injuries.
   The quake registered a preliminary reading of 5.1 on the Richter
scale and happened at 7:43 a.m. (6:43 p.m. EDt Tuesday), the agency
reported.
   It said the tremor was centered 30 miles under the ocean floor
off Hokkaido's eastern port city of Kushiro, 556 miles northwest of
Tokyo.
   The open-ended Richter scale measures the magnitude of an
earthquake, according to ground motion as recorded on seismographs.
An earthquake of 5 on the Richter scale is considered very strong,
while one measuring 6 is severe and capable of causing widespread
damage near the epicenter.
</TEXT>
