<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-Contras 1stLd-Writethru   09-20 0667</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Contras, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0710,0682</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government, Rebels Blame Each Other For Talks Breaking Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS three grafs with foreing minister saying Nicaragua hopes
to open talks with new U.S. administration after November
elections.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sandinista government officials and
Contra rebels blamed each other Tuesday for the breakdown of talks
aimed at stabilizing a cease-fire in the 7-year-old civil war.
   The two sides held talks Monday in Guatemala City in an attempt
to reopen peace negotiations to end the war that has claimed more
than 28,000 Nicaraguan lives.
   ``The interest of Managua is to agree on a definitive
cease-fire, which the Contras have rejected,'' Victor Hugo Tinoco,
deputy foreign minister and Sandinista negotiator, told the
pro-goverment newspaper El Nuevo Diario on Tuesday.
   Last week the Contras accepted the leftist government's proposal
to hold the talks in Guatemala. But the U.S.-backed rebels said
they would enter formal negotiations only after the release of 40
opposition leaders jailed in July during anti-government protests.
   The Sandinistas and the Contras on March 23 signed a pact, which
provided for a temporary truce and high-level talks in Managua. But
the Contras say they will participate in talks anywhere but the
Nicaraguan capital, where they say their movement is restricted.
The Sandinistas insist that Managua be the site of negotiations.
   ``This is a clear demonstration of the lack of Sandinista desire
to establish or take measures and set up reforms that permit a
democratic opening,'' said Roberto Ferrey, one of seven Contra
leaders. He spoke Tuesday on the rebels' clandestine Radio
Liberation.
   A series of meetings to set a timetable for the rebels to lay
down their arms permanently and for the Sandinistas to institute
democratic reforms ended in stalemate June 9.
   President Daniel Ortega, speaking on state-run radio Monday
night, said the goal of the rebels was to make it appear the
government was unwilling to bend so that the U.S. Congress would
resume military funding for the Contras.
   The Congress cut off military aid to the rebels Feb. 29. The
Contras, citing Soviet supplies to the Sandinistas, claim they need
such aid to act as a bargaining chip in negotiations.
   ``The Yankees are interested, through the Contras, to try to
show that Nicaragua has an intransigent position ... to approve
military aid for the counterrevolutionaries,'' Ortega said.
   ``We should speak with those who pay the gunslingers and not
talk with the gunslingers,'' the Sandinista leader said, referring
to the repeated Nicaraguan call for bilateral talks with the Reagan
Administration.
   Ortega said Reagan's ``obsession'' with Nicaragua has opened the
possibility of a direct military invasion of his country by
American troops. He said the number of American surveillance
flights over Nicaragua have increased after the March truce.
   The president also charged the U.S. government has continued to
supply the Contras and the ``unarmed Contras,'' an expression used
to describe internal opposition groups.
   Ortega cited the U.S.-government linked National Endowment for
Democracy, which he said provided more than $600,000 for opposition
political parties and groups, including $47,000 for the La Prensa
opposition newspaper.
   As many as 10,000 Contras fled from Nicaragua in the past five
months to base camps in eastern Honduras. Congressional aid
approved in March provides only for non-lethal goods to be
distributed in Honduras.
   Contra sources say no more than 2,000 rebels remain inside
Nicaragua.
   In a related development, Nicaraguan Foreign Minister Miguel
D'Escoto Brockmann said Tuesday that his government hopes to open
direct talks with the United States after a new U.S. president is
elected in November.
   ``Until now this has been impossible, but we hope that with a
new administration we can do this,'' D'Escoto told reporters in
Caracas, Venezuela.
   ``The future is black if the U.S. does not decide seriously to
redefine its vital interests in Latin America to exclude the need
to interfere in internal affairs,'' said D'Escoto, who is among
delegates from 26 Latin American and Caribbean nations meeting in
Venezuela to discuss regional economic issues.
</TEXT>
