<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DrugAgentSlain 1stLd-Writethru   09-20 0628</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Agent Slain, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0737,0643</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Clashes With Defense As Judge Prepares To Submit Case
to Jury</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE that case went to jury; DELETES
outdated material; picks up 6th graf pvs, ``Special agent...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The case of three men charged in the
kidnap-murder of a U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration agent slain
in Mexico went to a federal court jury Tuesday.
   The jury got the case against the trio 3{ years after the death
of DEA agent Enrique Camarena, whose battered body was discovered
at a ranch in the Mexican countryside.
   The defendants are alleged to have acted at the behest of
Mexican drug baron Rafael Caro Quintero. Prosecutors contend Caro
ordered Camarena's slaying to wreak vengeance for DEA assaults on
his drug empire.
   Two defendants are charged with kidnap, murder and conspiracy,
and one with being an accessory after the fact in the murders of
Camarena and his pilot.
   Defense attorneys argued the three are scapegoats of a
government intent on closing the books on the politically volatile
case, which disrupted relations between the U.S. and Mexico.
   Jurors who heard eight weeks of testimony were instructed by
U.S. District Judge Edward Rafeedie, then received the case. They
selected a foreman then retired until Wednesday to begin
deliberating.
   Earlier in the day, a prosecutor delivered his final statement,
denouncing defense lawyers for ``outrageous and obscene''
arguments. He called for conviction of all defendants.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Roel Campos, in a rebuttal that drew a
barrage of objections from the defense and an unsuccessful motion
for mistrial, said the lawyers had stooped to unwarranted personal
attacks on the prosecution team.
   He denounced ``this tactic of personal slander.''
   ``They have accused us of somehow presenting perjured testimony,
of somehow coaching witnesses,'' said Campos. ``Ladies and
gentlmen, did the prosecution in this case do anything improper?
I'm here to tell you we did not.''
   ``Special agent Camarena died in the service of his country,''
Campos told jurors. ``He died in the same way a Marine on a foreign
shore would die for his country.''
   Camarena was abducted in the Mexican city of Guadalajara on Feb.
7, 1985. His body and that of his pilot, Alfredo Zavala Avelar,
were found buried at a remote ranch in Mexico several weeks later.
They were severely beaten and Camarena's skull was crushed.
   Campos drew the loudest objections from defense attorneys when
he reviewed the evidence against Rene Verdugo Urquidez, 36, and
Raul Lopez Alvarez, 28, both charged with Camarena's murder. Lopez
is a former Mexican state police officer. Verdugo is an admitted
drug trafficker. Their lawyers said Campos was misstating evidence
against them.
   A third defendant, Jesus Felix Gutierrez, 38, is charged with
helping Caro escape from Mexico after Camarena's brutal murder.
   Lopez's attorney, Yolanda Barrera, moved for a mistrial after
Campos told jurors that the defendants do not face the death
penalty. He said he was responding to a defense statement that the
defendants ``are fighting for their lives.''
   They face a possible maximum of life imprisonment.
   Rafeedie, who denied the mistrial motion, nevertheless
instructed jurors to disregard the subject of penalties, which he
said was ``entirely taboo.''
   ``Your job,'' the judge said, ``is to reach a verdict regardless
of what the consequences might be.''
   The case stirred bitter feelings between Mexican and American
officials after Mexican police officials were linked to the killing
and to Caro's escape to Costa Rica.
   Nine men were indicted in Los Angeles in connection with the
Camarena slaying, but only three are standing trial here. Caro, 33,
and three other defendants are in custody and awaiting trial on
related charges in Mexico. An eighth man has died and another is a
fugitive.
</TEXT>
