<2ND_LINE>AM-Bolivia, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0794,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bolivian Cabinet Resigns As Elections Near</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-8 UPDATE with new Cabinet, Picks up 7th graf pvs,
The government ....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER MCFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Victor Paz Estenssoro
reorganized his Cabinet Tuesday evening to allow ministers who will
run in the May 1989 presidential and congressional elections to
campaign for office.
   All 17 ministers resigned earlier Tuesday. Paz Estenssoro
subsequently renamed 13 to their former posts.
   Foreign Minister Guillermo Bedregal said in a letter presented
to Paz Estenssoro that ``the beginning of intense political
activity motivated 17 ministers to resign.''
   The most important change in the new Cabinet is the planning
minister. Paz Estenssoro replaced Gonzalo Sanchez de Lozada, an
architect of the government's economic stabilization program, with
Fernando Romero, a prominent businessman who was running the Social
Emergency Fund.
   The fund is financed by Western governments and the United
Nations. It has created jobs for tens of thousands of workers.
   Sanchez de Lozada was nominated for the presidency this month by
the governing Revolutionary Nationalist Movement Party. He
indicated he could not campaign while holding a minister's
portfolio.
   Paz Estenssoro also replaced the ministers of health, industry
and commerce. The Cabinet is named by the president and does not
have to be ratified by Congress.
   Paz Estenssoro said Tuesday evening that he would continue his
economic program.
   The government program has lowered inflation from 24,000 percent
four years ago to 20 percent estimated for 1988 in this nation of
6.4 million people.
   The program included liberalizing the economy, ending all price
supports, a 95-percent currency devaluation and a tenfold rise in
gasoline prices.
   The U.S.-educated Sanchez de Lozada will campaign against former
military strongman General Hugo Banzer Suarez, whose party won the
largest share of voters in last year's municipal elections, and
Jaime Paz Zamora, head of the Revolutionary Leftist Movement party.
</TEXT>
