<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Denmark-Shevardnadze     09-20 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Denmark-Shevardnadze,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Foreign Minister Stresses Ecological Threat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Visiting Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard A. Shevardnadze warned Tuesday that the ecological threat
now facing mankind could be as dangerous as the nuclear arms race.
   He said upon arriving for a 24-hour stay in Denmark that he
expected ecology to be among issues he will discuss with officals
here. He said European issues, arms reductions and Danish-Soviet
topics were also on the agenda.
   ``The ecological threat is mounting with the same speed and
scope as the nuclear threat,'' Shevardnadze told reporters at
Copenhagen's Kastrup International Airport.
   ``There are really many problems in the modern world. There are
hundreds of thousands of tons of chemical weapons, and conventional
arms systems ... and not the least the ecological situation, which
is also a great danger.''
   His official visit to Denmark is the first by a Soviet foreign
minister since Andrei Gromyko, now president, came here in 1976.
   In a prepared statement, Shevardnadze said: ``We live in an
interdependent world, and that implies that we are all equally
concerned about it, try to find ways to enhance general security,
abolish nuclear and chemical weapons, reduce miltary confrontation
and act together to save the world from ecological catastrophe.''
   The 32-member Soviet delegation will proceed on to United States
Wednesday, where Shevardnadze is to have talks with Secretary of
State George P. Shultz in Washington and attend the opening of the
United Nations General Assembly in New York.
</TEXT>
