<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Kinnear     09-20 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Kinnear,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Comedy Actor Dies In Filming Accident In Spain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Popular British stage, film and television comedy
actor Roy Kinnear died Tuesday night 24 hours after falling from a
horse while filming near Madrid, Spain, Press Association reported.
   The British domestic news agency quoted an unidentified
spokesman at the Ruber International Hospital in the Spanish
capital as saying:
   ``We can confirm that Mr Kinnear ... is dead. He fell from a
horse during filming, suffered head injuries and died ... in our
intensive care unit.''
   Press Association said it understood work on the film, ``The
Last Return Of The Three Musketeers'' co-starring Michael York and
Oliver Reed, was suspended because of the death of the roly-poly,
54-year-old actor.
   It said York took Kinnear to the hospital after the fall and
that Kinnear's wife, actress Carmel Cryan, was at her husband's
hospital bedside.
   Kinnear was a veteran of Joan Littlewood's pioneering Theatre
Workshop in London in the 1950s and 1960s, of The Royal Shakespeare
Company and of The National Theatre.
   He became nationally known through his appearances in ``That Was
The Week That Was,'' the British Broadcasting Corp.'s innovative
former TV satire show that helped set the pace for the so-called
``Swinging '60s'' in Britain.
   One of his main screen partnerships was with director Richard
Lester who would insist on a role for his favorite comedian. Their
output included ``The Knack,'' ``Help,'' which starred the Beatles,
``A Funny Thing Happened On The Way To The Forum,'' and ``The Three
Musketeers.''
   In 1967, Kinnear was invited to join the Royal Shakespeare
Company where his roles included Touchstone in ``As You Like It.''
   Kinnear's recent stage work included The Common Man in the
recent London revival of Robert Bolt's play ``A Man For All
Seasons'' starring Charlton Heston; and parts in ``The Duchess of
Malfi,'' ``The Real Inspector Hound'' and ``The Critic.''
   His TV appearances included ``Inside George Webley,''
``Cowboys,'' ``Alice's Adventures in Wonderland'' and Tom
Stoppard's TV movie ``Squaring the Circle.''
   Broadcaster Ned Sherrin, who directed ``That Was The Week That
Was,'' said: ``He was a most dear and caring man. All of us liked
him. He suffered fools gladly. Above all, he was a great clown and
a very considerable actor with wonderful range.''
   Kinnear and his wife had three children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
