<HEAD>Schlumberger To Buy Back 11 Percent Of Its Common Shares</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Schlumberger Ltd. said Monday its board had
approved a plan to buy back 30 million of its common shares at a
cost that could top $975 million.
   The giant oilfield services company said shareholders will be
invited to tender shares in a ``Dutch auction,'' in which
stockholders specify the price they want for their shares, between
$32.50 and $37 per share.
   Based on the prices sought for the tendered shares, the company
will select a single purchase price and will pay that price for 30
million shares tendered at or below that level.
   The program begins Tuesday and ends Oct. 18, unless extended.
   Schlumberger shares closed at $32.25 on Monday, down 62{ cents
in New York Stock Exchange trading. The company has 272.2 million
common shares outstanding.
</TEXT>
