<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   09-20 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0554</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate has approved a landmark free-trade
agreement with Canada, clearing the way for America's part in
phasing out tariffs on $131 billion in merchandise that crosses the
border each year.
   ``This agreement is positive for both nations and it is a boost
for the world trading system,'' Sen. Daniel P. Moynihan, D-N.Y.,
said Monday as the Senate approved the measure 83-9.
   The bill, which now goes to President Reagan's desk, would open
the door for a 10-year phase-out of tariffs and a number of other
trade curbs, but political problems on the Canadian side must be
resolved first.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dart Group Corp., known for a series of
unsuccessful takeover bids for retailers, has offered to buy Kroger
Co., one of the nation's largest supermarket companies, for $4.32
billion.
   Kroger said it was reviewing the offer, which was made Monday in
a letter from Dart Chairman Herbert Haft.
   The bid followed Kroger's announcement last week that it was
considering a $3.8 billion restructuring plan. The plan was being
explored as a defensive move, partly because of the Haft family's
interest in the Cincinnati-based supermarket company.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CSX Corp. says it will buy back up to 60
million of its common shares and sell off two natural gas units in
a billion-dollar restructuring that will allow the company to
concentrate on its transportation business.
   CSX said it would begin repurchasing shares this week through a
``Dutch auction,'' in which shareholders are invited to offer their
holdings at a price between $28 and $33 per share.
   At $33 a share, the restructuring would cost CSX a total of
$1.98 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investor group trying to acquire Interco Inc.
for $2.6 billion has warned the manufacturing company of
``unfortunate consequences'' if it proceeds with an anti-takeover
restructuring that includes asset sales.
   Steven and Mitchell Rales, the brothers leading the takeover
group, complained Monday that Interco had refused to communicate
with them for nearly two months.
   St. Louis-based Interco said its restructuring could include the
sale of assets such as its Ethan Allen furniture company.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Arabia is intentionally exceeding its oil
production quota in response to the breakdown in discipline within
OPEC and in hopes of influencing an upcoming price committee
meeting, a respected oil industry newsletter says.
   The Petroleum Intelligence Weekly said Monday that Saudi Arabia
is trying to force other quota violators to stop overproduction.
   The newsletter said the Saudis are expected to offer to return
to their quota only when other OPEC members do so.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York, New England and Southern California have
the highest ratio of housing costs to wages in the nation and are
facing a severe labor shortage because of it, a new study shows.
   The Harvard Business Review said that as a result of the housing
crunch, companies are abandoning big cities, unions are fighting
for wage increases tied to the cost of housing, and managers are
refusing transfers to places with high housing costs.
   The study appears in the magazine's September-October issue.
</TEXT>
