<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for Kodak customers are supporting a deal
in which at least 3.4 million people who bought discontinued Kodak
instant cameras would get cash and coupons worth $50 to $70.
   Cook County Circuit Judge Thomas Rakowski, who presided over a
hearing Monday, will decide if the proposed $150 million plan
should take effect.
   The cameras were rendered virtually useless in 1985 when a
federal court said the company had violated patents held by
Polaroid Corp. That court ordered Kodak to stop producing film for
its line of instant cameras.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Brotherhood of Teamsters is
postponing its already once-delayed endorsement of a presidential
candidate until mid-October, a union spokesman says.
   The spokesman, Duke Zeller, predicted Monday there would not be
an endorsement until the next board meeting Oct. 17.
   Zeller said the 1.6 million-member union had extended from Sept.
16 until Sept. 30 the deadline for the rank and file to return poll
ballots on presidential preferences.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tax dollars should help bail out
insolvent thrift institutions and their struggling insurance fund,
a banking leader says.
   Charles Pistor, president of the American Bankers Association,
said Monday it would be unfair to require the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp., which is financed by banks, to bail out thrift
institutions.
   Pistor estimated the bailout would cost $50 billion to $100
billion. The General Accounting Office last week put the bill at
$45 billion to $50 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says it has approved a
joint venture that will permit the sale of the soft drink
Pepsi-Cola in India.
   Food Processing Minister Jagdish Tytler said Monday the project,
which also envisions production of food products, was cleared after
a meeting of the cabinet committee on economic affairs.
   The project with Pepsico Inc. involves setting up agricultural
research facilities, a potato and grain processing plant, a fruit
and vegetable processing unit and a plant to manufacture soft-drink
concentrate.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. has announced the sale of its
Godfather's Pizza unit to the restaurant division's management.
   Terms of the agreement were not announced, Pillsbury said in a
prepared statement Monday.
   Godfather's Pizza, which will remain based in Omaha, Neb., has
542 restaurants, 178 of which are company-owned. It is the nation's
fifth-largest pizza restaurant chain.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices declined in quiet trading Monday. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials fell 17.07 to 2,081.08.
   Bond prices fell in light trading.
   The dollar weakened marginally Monday and gold prices dropped.
   Soybean futures prices dropped, while livestock and meat were
mixed and energy futures prices were mixed.
</TEXT>
