<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 0323EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     09-20 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More bad news about an oversupply of oil on
world markets overshadowed a mixed performance in energy futures.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the October contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, settled
16 cents higher at $14.73 a barrel Monday after a late-afternoon
rally in anticipation of the contract's expiration on Tuesday.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for October delivery gained 0.02
cent to close at 44.24 cents a gallon.
   The October wholesale heating oil contract lost 0.01 cent to
settle at 41.36 cents a gallon.
   Analysts said the market opened lower, influenced by a report
that Saudi Arabia intentionally was violating its production quota
in a direct challenge to the 12 other nations of the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   The Petroleum Intelligence Weekly, a respected industry
newsletter, said the quota violation was a Saudi strategy ahead of
next week's meeting of the cartel's price monitoring committee to
bring other quota violators back in line with OPEC pricing policy
by competing with them for market share.
   The meeting is scheduled for Sept. 25 and 26, either in Vienna
or on the Indonesian island of Bali, according to reports.
   Saudi Arabia is OPEC's largest oil producer and once was
considered the swing producer, and in a position to influence other
OPEC members. But recently, some analysts have questioned Saudi
Arabia's leadership role.
   Iraq, for example, has refused to abide by an OPEC-imposed
quota, saying it needs the oil revenue to rebuild its war-torn
country. Other member nations also have admitted violating output
limits.
   Analysts said the market interpreted the Saudi report
negatively. They said last week's optimism that an OPEC price
meeting could lead to production limits and higher oil prices has
now turned mixed.
   Analysts also said Monday that gasoline futures were
surprisingly weak after last week's rally brought on by the threat
of a hurricane disrupting production in the Gulf of Mexico.
   ``I guess it was an overbought market,'' said Richard Kane, an
oil broker with Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
