<DOCNO> AP880920-0247 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 0326EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-WorldBank-IMF Bjt   09-20 0737</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-World Bank-IMF, Bjt,0762</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Of Seven To Meet Prior To Annual World Bank-IMF Gathering</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World finance officials begin arriving this week
for the annual World Bank-International Monetary Fund meeting,
which is expected to be more a forum for discussion of economic
ailments than a producer of any historic policy decisions.
   Finance ministers, central bankers and other officials from 151
countries are expected to attend the joint meeting, the first ever
held in Germany.
   Representatives of the countries will present their nations'
positions on various economic issues at a plenary session scheduled
for Sept. 27-29.
   Preliminary talks that include a meeting of officials of the
world's seven largest industrial democracies _ the so-called Group
of Seven _ begin Thursday.
   Coincidentally, Thursday is the three-year anniversary of the
so-called Plaza Agreement in New York, in which the United States,
Japan, West Germany, Britain and France agreed to depress the
dollar's foreign exchange value to help curb the U.S. trade deficit.
   Since then, the dollar has declined by nearly 45 percent against
the Japanese yen, a move cited as a key factor in cutting the
deficit over that time.
   Also during the West Berlin discussions, the G-7 nations are
slated to review their economic coordination policies. The Group of
Seven comprises the United States, West Germany, Japan, Canada,
France, Britain and Italy.
   Observers say the Group of Seven likely will reaffirm its
intention to keep the dollar steady at around current levels and
restate its belief that an excessive rise or fall of the dollar
would be counterproductive to world economies.
   World Bank and IMF officials and private economists say the
importance of the Berlin meeting is not its results, but the new
ideas it produces.
   ``I don't think there will be any major decisions, but there
should be a lively exchange of new ideas,'' Peter Pietsch,
economist for the Commerzbank in Frankfurt, said in an interview.
   Helmut Hartmann, an IMF spokesman, told reporters last week:
``We expect no historical decisions.''
   Also scheduled to meet this week on Thursday are deputy finance
ministers of the Group of 24 developing countries.
   The plight of heavily indebted developing nations is expected to
be a major topic during the Berlin talks.
   According to IMF annual report released Sept. 14, the industrial
nations are in good financial health but the overall situation
among developing countries remains far from satisfactory.
   The IMF report said total debt of the developing countries
increased 10.4 percent in 1987 from the previous year to $1.2
trillion, while their average growth rage fell to 3.4 percent in
1987 from 4.2 percent in 1986.
   The Third World debt issue likely will be dramatized in West
Berlin by protests expected to be staged concurrently with the
finance meetings. About 40,000 protesters have said they will come
to West Berlin to denounce what they see as unfair treatment of the
developing nations by richer industrialized lands and calling for
general Third World debt relief, according to organizers.
   Industrialized nations and private banks have been encouraging
developing countries to undertake economic reform in exchange for
help with their debts. Pietsch, the West German economist, says
that strategy continues to show the most promise.
   However, some indebted nations have called for more sweeping
solutions to their problem, including partial or whole debt
forgiveness.
   ``A general debt relief would not help to stabilize economies
and societies,'' Pietsch said.
   ``We need to be flexible and look for new instruments (to help
reduce developing countries' debts). The debt countries are also
creating lots of innovations in order to overcome their problems,''
he said.
   French Economics Minister Pierre Beregovoy has indicated that
during the West Berlin discussions he plans to unveil a proposal
aimed at encouraging banks to step up their lending to
middle-income debtors.
   Other topics likely to be discussed during the meeting are the
U.S. trade and budget deficits, protectionism and high inflation in
Latin America.
   The United States, represented by its newly appointed Treasury
Secretary Nicholas Brady, is expected to stress that the next U.S.
president would continue the nation's cooperation with the rest of
the G-7 countries.
   There also could be discussion of a possible Soviet entry in the
IMF.
   Hans Klein, West Germany's minister for economic cooperation,
said last week he would be ``extremely happy'' with such a move,
which he said likely would speed up structural economic reform
within the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
