<DOCNO> AP880920-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 0327EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BabyBag Bjt   09-20 0819</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baby Bag, Bjt,0845</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Entrepreneur Warmed By Baby Bag Profits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEN O'QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CUMBERLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Its inventor says the Baby Bag was born
of desperation.
   In years past, Elizabeth Andrews would have to grit her teeth
and try stuffing her 4-month-old daughter Jesse into a snowsuit
while the child twisted, kicked and screamed until her veins bulged.
   Bundled and ready, Jesse needed a diaper change; once outdoors,
her mittens fell off, creating another trauma.
   This was no way to enjoy winter, Andrews thought.
   Some type of bag-like outfit would be more convenient and more
protective of the baby's face. So Andrews stitched together a cozy
little bunting sack to replace the traditional snowsuit, called it
Baby Bag and began selling the insulated outfit in stores. It was
an immediate success.
   ``It's a good product to sell because it's a very simple design,
and the (promotional) pictures are always cute because the babies
are cute,'' Andrews said during a recent interview at her office in
this Portland suburb.
   In 1980 _ a year after she began selling the bunting suits _
Andrews and husband Ben Ellison formed Baby Bag Co. They sold 681
bags that winter.
   The company now sells more than 30,000 bags a year and has
recorded annual revenue over $500,000. Andrews also has expanded
the company's facilities in Maine, expanded her product line, added
a manufacturer in Seattle and begun to set up marketing in Europe.
   The bag _ which retails for $30 to $40 _ is displayed in several
catalogs nationwide and sells in about 800 stores in the United
States and Canada. It has been written up in Good Housekeeping and
Parents magazines, and was displayed among several new consumer
products on ABC's ``Good Morning America'' program.
   Using the bag is relatively easy. Parents can slide a child in
and out of the bag without the pushing and pulling associated with
tight-fitting snowsuits.
   The baby is warmed by its own body heat, which rises from the
bottom of the bag. Loosening the strings at the top of the suit
provides ventilation without having to undress a baby, as with
traditional snowsuits.
   Andrews, 39, says the outfit was born of desperation. Just the
sight of a snowsuit coming out of the closet sent her daughter into
a 15-minute tantrum.
   ``I needed something to pop her in and get outside quickly
because once she was outside she was fine,'' Andrews said.
   Andrews' sewing experience was limited to repairing a few sails
on the sloop she and her husband operated as a charter boat.
Undaunted, she stitched a prototype one-piece suit that drew
favorable comments from people who noticed the curious attire.
   She hired a Camden tent company to make the bags she distributed
to friends, who encouraged her and her husband to open a business.
   They patented the bag and tried to persuade the outdoor
outfitter L.L. Bean, based in nearby Freeport, to buy their idea
and manufacture the product. But the company turned them down,
saying Andrews and her husband should develop the product
themselves.
   With a few magazine advertisements, a $5,000 bank loan and 500
baby bags manufactured by a local sportswear company, the couple
began a mail-order business at home in 1980. Telephone orders
poured in day and night from around the country.
   Soon after, a product buyer at L.L. Bean helped Andrews improve
her idea, and the outfitter finally agreed to carry the bag in a
December 1983 mail-order catalog. The backing from L.L Bean,
coupled with a few magazine ads and displays at trade shows, pushed
annual sales to $350,000 by the spring of 1984. While her business
succeeded, Andrews' marriage fell apart. She sold the mail-order
division to another Maine company, Good Gear For Little People, but
was frightened by the prospect of managing a wholesale business
alone.
   ``I was a child of the 60's who never thought I would ever have
to be serious about anything,'' she said. ``I had never been a
person with a purpose or a goal.''
   The warm and cheerful Andrews says she adopted a slightly
sharper edge following her divorce, quickly realizing that
companies took her product more seriously once they saw she was
assertive and persistent.
   Last year, she moved the business to Cumberland, where she lives
with Jesse, now 10, and her second husband, Leonard Krill.
   They renovated their barn into offices where Andrews, dressed in
jeans and running shoes, scurries around with her three employees
managing a line of products that now includes mittens, booties,
snowcuffs for ankles, hooded jackets and pants.
   The products are made in Fryeburg by stitchers for a sportswear
company who work part-time for Andrews. They can produce about
7,000 Baby Bags a month and thousands of the other accessories.
   Andrews chuckles at her success, calling it ``a real story about
how people who don't know anything about anything can do
something.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880920-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 0328EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NYSEFirms-Profits     09-20 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NYSE Firms-Profits,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NYSE Member Firms Report Drop in Second-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 41 percent of the New York Stock
Exchange member firms doing public business lost money during the
second quarter, even though overall the firms' profit rose by 26.7
percent during the period.
   The exchange reported Monday that the investment companies had
after-tax earnings of $365 million, compared with a profit of $288
million in the same period of 1987.
   The 226 profitable companies had aggregate pre-tax earnings of
$813 million, while the 160 unprofitable firms lost an aggregate
$261 million, the report said.
   Revenue of the 386 companies was down slightly, dropping to
$12.449 billion from $12.603 billion a year ago. The firms had
revenue of $13.015 billion in the first quarter.
   Jeff Schaefer, senior vice president at the Securities Industry
Association, said inflation pressures and concerns about higher
interest rates had a negative effect on the securities business.
   ``In addition to lower volume, there was a lowering of
securities prices in both the fixed income and equity markets,''
Schaefer said. ``And that's very important, because what determines
commissions and trading profits are security prices.''
   The NYSE said the after-tax profit in the second quarter
represented a 4.0 percent annual return on member firms' average
net worth of $36.66 billion.
   Commission revenue amounted to 17.9 percent of total revenues in
the second quarter, down from 18.6 percent in the first quarter,
the report said. Member firms' assets rose 5.7 percent to $456.4
billion from $431.6 billion in the first quarter.
   Capital, which includes ownership equity and subordinated
liabilities, rose 2.1 percent from the previous quarter to a record
$37.04 billion. First quarter capital was $36.275 billion.
   The exchange said its specialist firms, which make markets for
the stocks traded on the NYSE floor, saw their aggregate after-tax
profit drop to $30 million in the second quarter. That was down 36
percent from $47 million in the same period last year and off 55
percent from $55 million in the first quarter.
   The NYSE said the specialists had a 12.3 percent after-tax
return on capital in the quarter, compared with 17.7 percent in the
same period last year and 22.3 percent in the first quarter.
</TEXT>
