<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CSXRestructuring     09-20 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CSX Restructuring,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CSX Restructuring To Return to Railroad Roots</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CSX Corp.'s decision to sell some of its
major holdings and repurchase up to 38 percent of its outstanding
stock is designed to return the company to its railroad roots, CSX
officials say.
   ``The restructuring program evidences our continued commitment
to increasing stockholder value by concentrating our resources on
our core transportation businesses,'' said Hays T. Watkins,
chairman of the Richmond-based transportation holding company.
   Watkins said Monday that CSX believed the firm's common stock
was an attractive investment, but said ``the repurchase plan will
permit stockholders who desire to sell their stock an opportunity
to do so at a premium over the current market price.''
   CSX, parent company of CSX Transportation, CSX Energy, CSX
Properties and CSX Technology, will repurchase up to 60 million
shares of common stock beginning this week.
   Each CSX shareholder will be invited to tender shares at prices
specified by the shareholder, ranging from $28 to $33 per share.
The company will select a single purchase price and will pay that
price for up to 40 million shares tendered at or below that level.
   The stock repurchase will be funded with cash and short-term
borrowings, CSX said.
   CSX also will sell its natural gas transmission and natural gas
liquid processing businesses, Texas Gas Transmission Corp. of
Owensboro, Ky., and CSX NGL Corp. of Houston, Texas.
   The company said also it might consider selling some of its
resort properties, including the Greenbrier hotel in West Virginia.
   The CSX announcement triggered positive investor reaction. Its
stock closed Monday at $30.62{ per share, up $3.75 on a volume of
almost 3.5 million shares in New York Stock Exchange trading.
   Standard & Poor's Corp. responded to the announcement by placing
certain CSX securities on its CreditWatch with negative
implications, a possible prelude to lowering the company's credit
rating.
   S&P said even though CSX had cash and short-term investments of
$1.1 billion at mid-year, the company would need to borrow money to
finance its announced intention to trim 8,200 jobs from its
railroad payrolls.
   CSX's decision to unload the pipeline and possibly certain
resort properties marked a major move away from the diversification
strategy that CSX has embraced in recent years, said George T.
Williamson, director of reserch for Financial Corp. of Virginia.
   ``I think what it shows is almost a restlessness at the senior
management and board level with the price of their stock,'' he
said. ``They obviously consider it very much undervalued.''
   The pipeline and resorts should bring CSX more than $1 billion,
said Andrew Geller, a senior investment officer for Provident
National Bank in Philadelphia.
   When combined with the existing cash and short-term investments,
he said, the company will have more than $2 billion that can be
used to repurchase stock.
   CSX earlier this year agreed to sell its CSX Ol and Gas Corp.
subsidiary for $612 million to a major French energy concern, Total
Compagnie Francaise des Petroles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
