<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-GNP     09-20 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-GNP,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's GNP Declines In Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's economy contracted during the second
quarter due mainly to lower demand for exports and declining
investment in private housing, the government reported Tuesday.
   Overall economic growth, as measured by the gross national
product, declined at an annual rate of 3.9 percent during the April
to June period, the Economic Planning Agency said. On an adjusted
basis, the GNP fell by 1 percent, the agency said.
   During the first quarter, Japan's GNP grew 2.7 percent, or at an
annual rate of 11.3 percent, according to the government report.
   The decline in the total value of goods and services produced in
Japan during the period was the first quarter-on-quarter
contraction in the country's economy since the January to March
1986 period, when the economy briefly declined under the impact of
the sharply rising yen.
   The government's GNP growth rate target for the current fiscal
year is 3.8 percent.
   Agency officials said a 1.5 percent decline in foreign demand
for Japanese products and services and a downturn in private
housing investment over the previous quarter's levels more than
offset a modest growth in domestic personal consumption and private
capital investment.
   The greatest declines were in the yen value of exports of
televisions, video tape recorders, radios and motor vehicles, they
said. The Japanese yen has risen by about 83 percent against the
U.S. dollar in the past three years, making Japanese products more
expensive overseas.
   But despite the downturn from healthy GNP growth levels in
previous months, agency officials said Japan's economy remained
fundamentally strong.
   ``It's still showing a positive progression overall,'' said one
official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``There's no reason to think that Japanese economic expansion
has ended,'' said Kenji Ito, senior economist for the Industrial
Bank of Japan. ``The fall in housing investments is a little
steeper than expected, but on the whole we thought the numbers
would be in this range.''
   The Economic Planning Agency had predicted earlier that the
second quarter's GNP would remain unchanged or decline slightly
from the previous quarter after statistics showed housing starts in
Japan were peaking.
   Housing construction had boomed because of low interest rates
and huge government expenditures in public works, which indirectly
stimulated construction and other industries.
</TEXT>
