<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Lawson-G-7     09-20 0172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Lawson-G-7,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chancellor Says G-7 Is Comfortable with Exchange Rates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Group of Seven finance ministers are generally
satisified with recent currency exchange rates and probably will
reaffirm their intent to cooperate on economic policy, Chancellor
of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson said Tuesday.
   ``I think most of us are comfortable with the rates where they
are at this time,'' Lawson said at a news briefing ahead of the
International Monetary Fund's annual meeting and a G-7 meeting in
West Berlin this weekend.
   ``We are back in the Louvre rates and have been for some time,''
Lawson said.
   He was referring to a February 1987 meeting at the Louvre Palace
in France in which the G-7 agreed to keep the dollar steady.
   Lawson said he did not expect any new initiatives at the weekend
gathering of the finance ministers of the United States, Japan,
West Germany, France, Great Britain, Italy and Canada.
   However, he said he expected to see a ``full-hearted
reaffirmation of the cooperation we have been pursuing.''
