<1ST_LINE>r f PM-WPPSSTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0497 09-20 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-WPPSS Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0497,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Richland Agrees To Settlement In WPPSS Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS first name of judge from Robert to William in 4th
graf, `Under the ....'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This city approved a tentative $6.5
million settlement in the massive Washington Public Power Supply
System lawsuit, leaving 18 defendants on trial over a record $2.25
billion bond default.
   ``I feel fantastic, very relieved,'' Councilman Lane Bray said
after the City Council approved the settlement Monday as the
federal trial continued in Tucson, Ariz.
   Plaintiffs in the case, including more than 24,000 bond buyers,
sued over WPPSS' 1983 bond default, which came after it abandoned
two nuclear power plants under construction. The default was the
biggest ever in the municipal bond market.
   Under the settlement, which is subject to approval by U.S.
District Judge William Browning, Richland will pay WPPSS
bondholders $6.5 million, of which $3.725 million will be paid by
Twin City Fire Insurance Co.
   The remaining $2.775 million comes from 1982 bonds Richland sold
to cover WPPSS plant termination costs and some capital
improvements, said City Manager Neal Shulman. The bond issue was
factored into past city electric rate hikes, Shulman said.
   The city also agreed to testify on bondholders' behalf.
   Richland, which has more than 30,000 residents, had a 1.965
percent interest in the scrapped nuclear plant projects.
   The settlement leaves 15 public utilities, two engineering firms
and a financial company as defendants in the trial, which was moved
to Tucson from Seattle because of pretrial publicity. Seven other
utilities settled with the plaintiffs before the trial began
earlier this month.
   Defendants argued in opening statements Monday that a 1983
Washington state Supreme Court ruling was to blame for the default.
The high court invalidated agreements that 88 utilities signed to
participate in building the nuclear plants financed by the bonds.
   ``The cause of the loss here is almost like an act of God, an
act of the Supreme Court of Washington,'' said Ralph Nickerson,
attorney for the Klickitat County Public Utility District.
   The ruling stemmed from a lawsuit by some utilities questioning
the agreements' validity. By nullifying them, the court removed the
guarantee that the bonds would be paid even if the plants were
never built.
   Although the ruling applied to them, none of the utilities was
part of that lawsuit.
   In opening arguments last week, bondholders' attorneys said the
defendants lied about power needs in the Northwest, rising costs
and construction delays. They contended that if the truth had been
told, the bond would not have gone on the market.
   Defense attorneys argued Monday that their clients revealed all
the information they were supposed to provide and did their best to
estimate costs and construction schedules.
   ``The evidence will show that these official statements were as
complete and accurate as people could make them, and they were not
filled with misstatements,'' said attorney James Hagan,
representing financial consultant Blyth Eastman Paine Webber Inc.
   Hagan and Nickerson said public utility commissioners and Blyth
employees were so confident in the information that they also
bought bonds.
   Testimony is scheduled to begin Thursday after a two-day recess.
   WPPSS was formed by public utilities to build and operate major
electric plants in Washington, Idaho and Oregon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880920-0259 </DOCNO>
