<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Higher In Technical Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened modestly higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade in a technical rebound after
several days of falling prices, including Monday's sharp drop,
analysts said.
   ``We had a little technical bounce here but I don't know if it's
going to last,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc.
   He noted a lack of sell orders at the opening bell and said the
buying was led by investment firms and commodity funds, the major
sellers on Monday.
   Rumors of new export sales also supported the grain markets,
Lespinasse said.
   The Soviet Union supposedly was set to buy 1 million metric tons
of U.S. corn and 500,000 metric tons of Argentine soybean meal.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat. or soybeans.
   In early trading, wheat was 1} cents to 3{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.99 a bushel; corn was 1}
cents to 3\ cents higher with September at $2.74{ a bushel; oats
werer 2 cents to 3\ cents higher with December at $2.61{ a bushel;
soybeans were 4 cents to 5{ cents higher with September at $8.25 a
bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were higher in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .22 cent to .42 cent higher with October at
69.35 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .30 cent higher
with September at 80.15 cents a pound; hogs were .20 cent to .73
cent higher with October at 38.40 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .50 cent to .73 cent higher with February at 50.25
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures finished mixed on Monday.
