<1ST_LINE>a f BC-PersonalFile-Scallen Adv23   09-20 0842</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Personal File-Scallen, Adv 23,0864</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Friday Sept. 23 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Scallen: A `Mini-Disney' Pumps Life Into Ice Capades,
Globetrotters</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leave it to show business veteran Thomas
Scallen to team the forces of Olympic silver medal figure skater
Elizabeth Manley and the Harlem Globetrotters.
   Canada's superstar on ice won't suit up with the magicians of
basketball, but she is performing under the same flag: Scallen's
International Broadcasting Corp.
   Scallen's company purchased the Hollywood, Calif.-based
Globetrotters and Ice Capades for $30 million in December 1986 from
Metromedia Inc. Signing Manley to the Ice Capade's fall tour is one
of many moves the former public defender, banker and motion picture
executive has made to revitalize the skating troupe.
   He also has added a second squad to the Globetrotters and hired
female players Sandra Hodge, Nancy Lieberman and Joyce Walker to
draw more women to the games.
   What's more, Scallen recently acquired the Boblo Island
amusement park near Detroit for $19.5 million. He says the 272-acre
island in the lower Detroit River will generate cash flow during
the summer months when the Globetrotters and Ice Capades are idle.
   ``What we are is a mini-Walt Disney,'' said the 62-year-old
Scallen. ``We want to expand within the concept of quality family
entertainment.''
   Besides the Ice Capades, Globetrotters and Boblo Island,
Scallen's company owns a controlling interest in Century Park
Pictures, a Hollywood production company that made the movie
``Shoot to Kill,'' starring Sidney Poitier and Tom Berenger. A
second film, ``South of Picasso,'' is in the works and will feature
Tom Hanks.
   Scallen also has his eyes on more regional amusement parks and
some television stations. It was Scallen's sale of Big Country TV
of Abilene, Texas, for an after-tax profit of $4.9 million that
allowed him to purchase the Ice Capades and Globetrotters.
   ``Let's say John Kluge (chairman of Metromedia Inc.) and Walt
Disney are my role models,'' Scallen said.
   So far, Scallen has transformed International Broadcasting from
an obscure penny stock company, which lost $1.2 million on sales of
$2 million in 1986, to a $34 million company that expects to post
net earnings this year of more than $2 million. International
Broadcasting stock now trades in the range of $10 a share on the
national over-the-counter market.
   The business seems to fit Scallen's colorful past.
   There was the law degree from the University of Denver that
allowed him to work in that city as a public defender before
returning to his hometown of Minneapolis, where he acquired his
love of skating. He said he returned to Minnesota to join a law
firm in which his father was a partner.
   From there he turned to a banking career, starting the Bank of
Minneapolis and helping to finance Joe Robbie's purchase of the
Miami Dolphins professional football team. But he quit that to
launch his show business career that eventually had him running
Shipsteads & Johnson Ice Follies, Holiday on Ice, and the Clyde
Beatty-Cole Bros. Circus. He also worked briefly in a top executive
post at 20th Century Fox.
   His darting moves through the entertainment world were briefly
derailed in the early 1980s when Scallen ran afoul of Canadian
securities laws. He was convicted _ but later pardoned _ for
distributing a false prospectus on a loan he arranged to help
finance his acquisition of the Vancouver Canucks hockey team.
   In typical style, Scallen emerged from the episode relatively
unscathed. He was paroled after serving nine months of a two-year
prison sentence and was pardoned in 1982 by the solicitor general
of Canada. Later, he even sold the Canucks for a profit, he says.
   ``There's no way of telling how painful an experience like that
(prison term) was,'' Scallen said after receiving the pardon.
``Particularly when I believed then as I do now that I didn't do
anything wrong.''
   As IBC has grown from two employees in 1982 to 2,000 employees
this year, the demands on Scallen have increased. But he says he
loves it and he has refused to dilute his control over the company.
   ``This company is my life and it's a delight,'' Scallen said
from his top-floor office in Minneapolis' signature skyscraper, the
IDS Center.
   Splitting time between Minneapolis and an office in Hollywood,
Scallen operates the company with a skeletal administration that
includes no middle managers. He says he won't make an acquisition
``unless it's a business I can run myself,'' and he still spends
time at the ice rink staging Ice Capades shows.
   ``That's how I get my kicks,'' Scallen said. ``Those shows are
the last big spectaculars in this country.''
   Carolyn Follese, who follows International Broadcasting for
Summit Investment Co. of Bloomington, Minn., said her only concern
about the company is that Scallen tries to do everything.
   ``When I started with this stock it was a dime,'' Follese said.
``I just thought Scallen was going to do it and sure enough he did.
He's performed some real nice miracles lately.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Friday Sept. 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
