<1ST_LINE>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv21   09-20 0677</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 21 ,0695</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Wednesday Sept. 21</NOTE>
<HEAD>Terrorizing the American Family</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the most popular games played today is
terrorizing the American household. It's great fun, and profitable,
too.
   Among those at the forefront of the movement are the media, the
government, the business community, the fraternity of seers in such
fields as economics, finance and science, and the outright
exploiters. Fear sells, you know.
   You can sell fear to anyone concerned about physical or economic
well being, and if you don't think so just take a look at the
magazine rack or the book stall. The field is wide open; if fear
doesn't exist, you can create it.
   Some of the fears are legitimate perhaps, but since there is no
end to them, it becomes impossible to sort them out. How can you
worry about radon, the well water, the air you breath and the
weather together?
   Are you sure your children aren't overdosing on vitamins? Are
they consuming too many fats, too much salt? What's your
cholesterol level? When did you last check your blood pressure? You
say you haven't had a physical?
   You were warned about the hurricane danger and still you haven't
taken precautions? Don't you know the season continues into
October? Tornados, you know, can occur at any time of year. Are you
the kind of person who hasn't yet begun preparing for the
greenhouse effect?
   You say that the latter hasn't even been demonstrated? That's
pride and arrogance talking, especially if you live on the
seacoast. Just what will you do if the ice caps melt, raises the
ocean level and swallows up your city?
   More to the moment, winter is coming. Are you sure your pipes
are insulated? Had your flu shots? Remember that little leak in the
roof last winter? It could become a big one in January.
   How are your finances? Do you mean to say that in these perilous
times, when nobody knows what awful thing will happen next, you
have no financial plan? No will? When was the last time you checked
your health insurance?
   Are you prepared for the coming recession? Have you made plans
to benefit from the coming boom if that comes before the coming
recession? And what if deflation comes instead? You have to be
ready for that possibility, too.
   Your economic preparedness kit should include procedures for
handling the coming real estate collapse, the stock market
collapse, the bank collapse. Have you really considered the dangers
of that variable rate mortgage of yours?
   No matter what the politicians say, incidentally, you should
worry about higher taxes. But you should worry, too, if they aren't
raised, because then the federal budget will remain in deficit, and
that is bad.
   Hold on, says economist Howard Ruff. He says you should add the
shrinking federal defict to your fear list.
   ``It is to be feared in the same way that a junkie fears the
cutoff of his supply,'' he warns. ``The withdrawal symptoms could
be severe. A deficit stimulates an economy. When it shrinks, the
junkies get sick.''
   Ruff's fear list includes deflation, higher interest rates,
Dukakis' election, inflation-hedge investments, the stock market
and the collapse of the American family, ``my greatest concern.''
   There are so many things to fear that, for diversion, some
securities seers have strung together lists of things not to fear,
such as missing out on a bull market in stocks or failing to
prepare for a strong economy.
   Having exploited fear a decade ago with the book ``The Coming
Real Estate Crash,'' which either didn't occur or somehow wasn't
observed by millions of Americans, the same author has now written
``Panic-Proof Investing.''
   ``A fearsome situation is developing,'' said a worrier the other
day. ``What are we ever going to do about all these used and unused
fears that are piling up and polluting the environment?''
   He said it was really something to worry about.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday Sept. 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
