<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     09-20 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Closes Lower; Gold Rises Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted lower against most major
foreign currencies in light European trading Tuesday, reflecting
more reluctance by dealers to do business ahead of top-level
finance minister meetings this week.
   Gold prices rose slightly in quiet trading.
   Markets ignored a downward revision in U.S. gross national
product figures for the second quarter to 3.0 percent from 3.3
percent, foreign currency dealers said. They were more concerned
with the potential impact of meetings starting Thursday by the
World Bank and International Monetary Fund.
   The IMF-World Bank discussions on international debt will be
followed by a Saturday gathering of finance ministers from the
leading industrialized democracies. Both meetings will be held in
West Berlin.
   Ministers from the so-called Group of Seven countries _ the
United States, Japan, West Germany, France, Great Britain, Italy
and Canada _ are expected to push for stable currency exchange
rates, dealers said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar edged up 0.35 Japanese yen to a closing 134.15 yen.
Later in London it retreated to 133.90 yen.
   Many dealers said the worsening health of Emperor Hirohito and a
second-quarter decline of 1.0 percent in Japan's gross national
product pushed the yen down.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.6865 to buy one pound, more expensive than its $1.6785 level
late Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe compared with late Monday:
1.8641 West German marks, down from 1.8695; 1.5740 Swiss francs,
down from 1.5793; 6.3385 French francs, down from 6.3520; 2.1075
Dutch guilders, down from 2.1100; 1,391.50 Italian lire, down from
1,393.50; 1.2203 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2194.
   Higher gold prices reflected internal market influences rather
than renewed interest in the metal, said one Zurich bullion dealer.
   In London, gold edged up to $410 a troy ounce from late Monday's
$409.30.
   In Zurich, gold closed at $410.50, up from $408.50 late Monday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong gold rose $1.72 to close at $413.12.
   Silver bullion prices rose in London to $6.36 a troy ounce, from
Monday's $6.28.
</TEXT>
