   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, which fell 17.07
points on Monday, was up 6.22 points to 2,087.30 with two hours
left in the session.
   Advancing issues led decliners by a margin of 7-to-6 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 736 up, 610 down and 548 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 102.69 million shares at 2 p.m. on Wall
Street, compared with 95.33 million shares at the same point on
Monday.
   The government's downward revision of its estimate of
second-quarter economic growth failed to provide any stimulus to
traders.
   Charles Jensen, a technical market analyst for the investment
firm MKI Securities Corp., said traders were ``waiting for
something more conclusive to stir them off the sidelines.''
   Jensen noted that offsetting the positive implications of more
moderate growth was an increase in a measure of inflation tied to
the gross national product. As a result, he said bond prices were
virtually unchanged.
   With bond yields still relatively attractive, Jensen said many
traders have found incentive to take the risks associated with the
uncertain returns on stocks.
   Among the blue chip issues, American Telephone & Telegraph was
up [ at 26], General Electric was unchanged at 43[ and Exxon was up
[ at 45[.
