<HEAD>Pillsbury First-Quarter Income Up 26 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. reported Tuesday its
first-quarter earnings rose 26 percent, in part because of a change
in accounting for income taxes.
   Pillsbury said it earned $71.4 million, or 83 cents per share,
during the quarter ended Aug. 31, compared with $56.8 million, or
66 cents per share, in the same period a year ago.
   The company noted in a statement that its income was boosted $14
million as a result of the recalculation of prior years' deferred
income taxes.
   Sales rose 2 percent to $1.48 billion from $1.46 billion.
   ``This represents the first step toward a better year in fiscal
1989, a year in which we expect to gain momentum toward much better
long-term prospects,'' said Philip L. Smith, Pillsbury's chairman,
president and chief executive officer.
   Pillsbury's food business has shown improvement, but the company
is still spending heavily to boost its slumping restaurants
division, Smith said.
   The restaurants unit reported a 34 percent decline in operating
profit to $48.7 million from $73.5 million as sales declined 7
percent to $655 million. The unit includes Burger King, Steak and
Ale and Godfather's Pizza.
   On Monday, Pillsbury announced it was selling Godfather's to the
chain's management for an undisclosed amount.
</TEXT>
