<HEAD>Grains Close Higher On Trade Rumors; Soybeans Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat and corn futures closed higher Tuesday on
the Chicago Board of Trade amid rumors of new U.S. grain sales to
the Soviet Union but soybeans finished narrowly mixed on a lack of
strong bullish signals.
   ``It was a day pretty much ruled by rumors,'' said Victor
Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Talk that the Soviets had purchased 1 million to 2 million
metric tons of both corn and wheat prompted buying in those
markets, he said.
   Rumors that government officials had scheduled an afternoon news
conference regarding the ongoing grain-trade negotiations with the
Soviet Union added further fuel to the rally. But officials later
denied a news conference was planned.
   A rumor that the Soviets had purchased 500,000 metric tons of
Argentine soybean meal lent only marginal support to the soybean
market. Such a purchase would indicate new demand for soybeans but
players in the U.S. soybean market are looking for more demand for
the homegrown product to develop.
   At the close, wheat was 3{ cents to 8\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $4.04 a bushel; corn was 2{
cents lower to 2} cents higher with September at $2.73{ a bushel;
oats were } cent lower to 4 cents higher with September at $2.51{ a
bushel; soybeans were } cent lower to 10{ cents higher with
September at $8.21 a bushel.
