<1ST_LINE>r f AM-IBMProducts     09-20 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IBM Products,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IBM Offers One-Stop Service For Others' Equipment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. said
Tuesday it would offer one-stop service for equipment made by other
companies, but analysts said most customers would rather deal
directly with their suppliers than go through IBM.
   IBM's offer was part of its biggest announcement since June 1987
in the field of computer networking products and services, Ellen
Hancock, the general manager of communications systems, said in an
interview.
   Among other things, IBM announced easier ways for its computers
to connect to equipment made by other companies using international
communications standards, and better methods for customers to
manage their networks by remote control.
   Several analysts said they had doubts about how customers would
respond to IBM's offer to serve as the single point of contact for
customers when they had problems with any of their equipment,
whether made by IBM or another company.
   Digital Equipment Corp. launched a similar service last week, a
signal that both companies see the possibility of a lucrative
business in managing and servicing computer networks.
   If customers have a problem with equipment made by, say, Wang
Laboratories Inc., they would rather deal directly with Wang than
go through IBM, which is a competitor of Wang, said Stephen Payne,
chief executive of PA Consulting in Hightstown, N.J.
   Payne said he also doubted how many customers would opt for
another service in which IBM would install probes in a company's
network and then monitor it for trouble from an IBM location.
   ``You could think of lots and lots of reasons why this might not
fly,'' said Bart Stuck, a vice president at Probe Research Inc. in
Cedar Knolls, N.J.
   Ms. Hancock agreed that the services were not for everyone, but
said some customers would prefer to have someone else handle their
network management and service.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
