<HEAD>Gold Prices Fall to 19-Month Low</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold futures prices fell to a 19-month low Tuesday on the New
York's Commodity Exchange as gold producers sold futures to hedge
against further declines in the cash market, analysts said.
   On other markets, coffee futures rallied strongly; pork futures
led the livestock complex higher; grains and soybeans were mixed;
energy futures were mixed; and stock-index futures advanced.
   Gold for October delivery traded as low as $402.30 a troy ounce,
the lowest price since Feb. 24, 1987, when gold futures last dipped
below $400. Prices recovered a bit near the close when traders
holding short (sell) took profits by buying at the low levels,
analysts said.
   Gold producers were the among the heaviest sellers after the
market registered little interest in the Commerce Department's
report on the gross national product, said Bette Raptopoulos,
metals analyst in New York with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   The report showed the U.S. economy expanded at a rate of 3.0
percent in the April-June quarter compared with a rate of 3.4
percent in the previous quarter.
   The GNP number added to the already bearish sentiment in the
inflation-sensitive gold market but another number in the report,
the GNP deflator, rose at an inflationary annual rate of 5.5
percent compared with 1.7 percent in the first quarter.
   The deflator reflects changes in buying patterns as well as
prices.
   Ms. Raptopolous said gold producers were watching the market's
reaction to the deflator and sold when the market failed to rally.
   John Norris, chief trader of precious metals for Citibank in New
York, said the sell-off reflected further bearishness in the market
``on the lack of any perception of inflation on the horizon.
   ``It could go through $400 and is going to get tested at that
level,'' he said.
   Silver futures followed gold lower on the Comex while platinum
futures fell sharply on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Gold settled $3.90 to $4.70 lower with the contract for delivery
in October at $406.20 a troy ounce; silver was 11.8 cents to 12.8
cents lower with September at $6.252 a troy ounce; platinum was
$8.10 to $8.70 lower with October at $494.90 a troy ounce.
   Coffee futures surged on New York's Coffee, Sugar & Cocoa
Exchange amid optimism about negotiations between consumer and
producer nation-members of the International Coffee Organization.
   The ICO convened a two-week meeting in London on Monday to
discuss changes in its price-support policies.
   ``There seems to be an aura of cooperation and the prospects for
delegates completing their work by the first of October is very
bright at this point,'' said Bert Ruiz, a coffee broker with
Balfour Maclaine Corp in New York.
   Coffee settled 1.25 cents to 3.21 cents higher with September at
$1.23 a pound.
   Pork futures gained sharply on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange
on a mixture of chart-based factors and position-evening ahead of
the Agriculture Department's Sept. 30 hogs and pigs report, a
quarterly look at the size of the U.S. hog herd.
   Cattle futures gained on spillover buying from the pork market
and bullish attitudes about the long-term outlook for the
cattle-market, analysts said.
   Live cattle settled .27 cent to .70 cent higher with October at
69.37 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent to .52 cent higher
with September at 80.37 cents a pound; hogs were .45 cent to 1.25
cents higher with October at 38.77 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .95 cent to 1.17 cents higher with February at 50.70
cents a pound.
   Wheat and corn futures advanced on the Chicago Board of Trade
amid rumors of new U.S. grain sales to the Soviet Union but
soybeans finished mixed on a lack of strong bullish signals.
   Wheat settled 5} cents to 8\ cents higher with September at
$4.04{ a bushel; corn was 2{ cents lower to 2} cents higher with
September at $2.73} a bushel; oats were 1{ cents lower to 4 cents
higher with September at $2.50{ a bushel; soybeans were { cent
lower to 10{ cents higher with September at $8.20{ a bushel.
   Energy futures were mixed on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 6 cents lower to 31
cents higher with October at $15.04 a barrel; heating oil was .09
cent lower to .14 cent higher with October at 41.32 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .20 cent to .27 cent higher with October at
44.43 cents a gallon.
   Stock-index futures advanced slightly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for December delivery of the Standard
& Poor's 500 index settled .80 point higher at 272.65.
</TEXT>
