<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Murdoch-Elle     09-20 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Murdoch-Elle,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>News Corp. Sells Half-Interest in Elle Magazine to Hachette</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. Ltd. said Tuesday it
had sold its half-interest in the Elle magazine joint ventures in
the United States and the United Kingdom to its lone partner,
France's Hachette Group.
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed, but a source familiar with
it and speaking on condition that he not be identified said the
price was about $150 million. The sale is subject to negotiation of
a definitive agreement.
   It was expected News Corp. would use the proceeds of the sale to
help finance its $3 billion acquisition of Triangle Publications
Inc., which publishes TV Guide, the Daily Racing Form and Seventeen
magazine.
   In a separate announcement, Murdoch and Walter Annenberg,
chairman of Triangle, said they had signed a merger agreement
providing for the purchase of Triangle. The two men had announced
in early August that they had agreed to the deal, subject to
reaching a definitive agreement, among other things.
   The Triangle purchase remains subject to obtaining necessary
government approvals and satisfaction of certain conditions in the
merger agreement, the statement said.
   Murdoch, chief executive of News Corp., has previously said he
would sell some assets to help finance the purchase of Triangle,
but had singled out only its stake in Reuters Holdings PLC and some
land in Britain and Australia. He has said his goal is to raise
half of the needed funds through asset sales and borrow the rest.
   The U.S. units of News Corp. and Hachette formed their joint
venture for a U.S. version of Elle magazine in September 1985 and
for the British version two months later. Hachette also publishes
nearly a dozen other versions of Elle.
   The U.S. version of the magazine, aimed at affluent,
fashion-conscious women, has proven quite successful with a monthly
circulation reaching 825,000 and advertising pages estimated at
2,150 this year.
   In a statement, Murdoch said the sale of its interest in Elle to
Hachette would put both companies ``in the best possible position
to pursue the full development of their own magazine interests in
the U.S. and the U.K.''
   He noted News Corp. and Hachette continued to publish jointly
two magazines, Premiere and Sky.
   Daniel Filipacchi, vice chairman of Hachette Group, said Elle
will become part of Hachette's Diamandis Communications Inc. unit,
which Hachette acquired earlier this year and publishes 13 major
magazines, including Road & Track, Memories and Car and Driver.
   In that connection, Diamandis announced that Anne Sutherland
Fuchs, the vice president and publisher of its Woman's Day
magazine, would become senior vice president and publisher of Elle.
   Robert Mate, vice president and advertising director for Woman's
Day, moves up to publisher at that magazine, the announcement said.
</TEXT>
