<HEAD>Stocks Tumble, Dollar Higher In Tokyo Morning Session</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning Nikkei, comments. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices fell sharply after a slight rebound in
morning trading Wednesday, while the U.S. dollar inched up against
the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Exchange of 225 selected issues, a 352.42-point
loser Tuesday, closed the morning session down another 253.02
points at 27,295.56, after rising slightly in the minutes of
trading.
   ``Share prices were lower across the board, even print-related
issues declined,'' a Nomura Securities' analyst said.
   ``Participants just didn't know what to do because they were
worried about what would happen to the stock market in case the
emperor died. So most of them were trying to get rid of the issues
they were unsure of in the future,'' he said, speaking on condition
of anonymity.
   The Imperial Household Agency said Wednesday morning that
Emperor Hirohito's condition was improving after three blood
transfusions and other treatment Tuesday. News reports said he has
been in serious condition since vomiting blood Monday night and
early Tuesday morning.
   The analyst also said investors were pessimistic over the
decline in the growth rate of Japan's gross national product for
the second quarter, which was reported Tuesday.
   The Economic Planning Agency reported Japan's gross national
product for the April-June period was 3.9 percent, down 0.1 percent
from the previous quarter. According to the EPA report, it was the
first decline after increases in the last nine quarters.
   In foreign exchange, the dollar was quoted at 134.18 yen by late
morning, up from 134.15 yen at Tuesday's close and from 134.05 yen
at the opening of trading.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
